{"title_page": "Emayatzy Corinealdi", "text_new": "{{short description|American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Emayatzy Corinealdi\n|image = Emayatzy Corinealdi.jpg\n| caption = Corinealdi in June 2012\n| occupation  = Actress\n| years_active = 2008\u2013present\n| spouse       =\n| children     =\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|01|14|}}\n|birth_place=[[Fort Knox|Fort Knox, Kentucky]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Emayatzy Evett Corinealdi'''<ref name='KY-Birth'>{{cite web |url= |title=Kentucky, Birth Index, 1911-1999 [database on-line] |last= |first= |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=2006 |website=Ancestry.com |series= |publisher= Ancestry.com Operations Inc. |quote=Original data: Kentucky Department for Libraries and Archives. Kentucky Birth, Marriage, and Death Databases: Births 1911-1999. Frankfort, Kentucky: Kentucky Department for Libraries and Archives. |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u025b|m|e\u026a|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|t|s|i|_|\u02cc|k|\u0252r|\u026a|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|l|d|i}} {{respell|EM|ay|AHT|see|_|KORR|ih|NAHL|dee}}; born January 14, 1980)<ref name='KY-Birth'/> is an American actress. She is best known for her leading role in the [[Ava DuVernay]] film ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'' (2012).\n\n==Early life==\nCorinealdi was born in [[Fort Knox|Fort Knox, Kentucky]],<ref name='KY-Birth'/><ref name=BET1>{{cite web| url= http://www.bet.com/topics/e/emayatzy-corinealdi.html |title= Emayatzy Corinealdi | website= BET.com |publisher=BET Interactive, LLC |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> the daughter of Rosemarie Hilton and Edward Corinealdi. Her father is [[Panamanians|Panamanian]], while her mother is [[African-American]] from [[Ohio]].<ref name='KY-Birth'/><ref>[http://blackactors.net/2011/06/the-cast-of-ava-duvernays-middle-of-nowhere/ THE CAST OF AVA DUVERNAY'S 'MIDDLE OF NOWHERE'] at BlackActors.net</ref><ref name=\"backstage breakout\">{{cite web| url= http://www.backstage.com/interview/middle-nowhere-star-emayatzy-corinealdi-her-breakout-leading-role/ | title= Interview: 'Middle of Nowhere' Star Emayatzy Corinealdi on Her Breakout Leading Role | first= Jenelle |last= Riley |date= 11 September 2012 |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> As a member of a military family, she was raised between [[Germany]] and the U.S. states of Ohio, [[Kansas]], and [[New Jersey]].<ref name=\"backstage breakout\" /><ref name= \"good role\">{{cite news| title= Emayatzy Corinealdi finds a good role in 'Middle of Nowhere' | date= 13 October 2012| first= Nicole |last= Sperling |work= Los Angeles Times |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/13/entertainment/la-et-mn-emayatzy-corinealdi-20121014 | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> She studied in New Jersey at the Actor's Training Studio, then at the [[William Esper Studio]] in [[New York City]], then at Playhouse West.<ref name= \"good role\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn her early career, Corinealdi co-starred in a number of independent and short films, had the recurring role on the CBS daytime soap opera, ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', and appeared in the Hallmark television film, ''[[The Nanny Express]]'' (2008). In 2012, she made her feature film debut as the lead in the drama ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]''. Corinealdi won the 14th Annual [[American Black Film Festival]] Star Project,<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.clutchmagonline.com/2014/09/look-book-favorite-emayatzy-corinealdi-style-beauty-looks/ | work= Clutch Magazine| publisher= Sutton New Media LLC| title = Look Book: Our Favorite Emayatzy Corinealdi Style and Beauty Looks |author= Clutch |date= September 2014 | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> an international acting competition for emerging multicultural artists. Later that year, she won the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://hellobeautiful.com/2012/11/28/middle-of-nowhere-emayatzy-corinealdi-wins-best-actor-gotham-film-awards/ | title= Emayatzy Corinealdi Of 'Middle Of Nowhere' Wins Gotham Film Awards' Best Actor | date= 28 November 2012 |first= Danielle |last= Young | website= HelloBeautiful.com | publisher= Interactive One| accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref>  She was also nominated for an [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]].<ref>{{cite news| title= Spirit Awards reaction: Jack Black, Matthew McConaughey, Benh Zeitlin, David O. Russell, more weigh in | work= Entertainment Weekly | first= Lindsey |last= Bahr |date= 27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Corinealdi appeared in the short film ''The Door'', part of [[Miu Miu]]'s fashion series ''Women's Tales'', which reunited her with her ''Middle of Nowhere'' director [[Ava DuVernay]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.miumiu.com/en/women_tales/5/film | title= \"The Door\" by Ava DuVernay, Women's Tales #5 | publisher= MiuMiu.com | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Corinealdi was cast in the [[Amazon Studios|Amazon]] drama series ''[[Hand of God (TV series)|Hand of God]]''. Later that year, she won the role of Frances Taylor, the wife of [[Miles Davis]] in the biographical film ''[[Miles Ahead (film)|Miles Ahead]]''.<ref name=\"BET replace\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bet.com/news/celebrities/2014/06/25/middle-of-nowhere-star-to-replace-zoe-saldana-in-miles-davis-biopic.html |title=Middle of Nowhere Star to Replace Zoe Saldana in Miles Davis Biopic  |last1=Diaz |first1=Evelyn |last2= |first2= |date=25 June 2014 |website=BET.com |publisher=BET Interactive, LLC |accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Pretty Lady'' \n| Azizi\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Vampz'' \n| Eve\n| \n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Beauty Shop]]'' \n| Client of Ida\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''My American Nurse'' \n| \n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Cordially Invited'' \n| Grace Ingrahm\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Akira's Hip-Hop Shop''\n| Daphne\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Wednesday Again'' \n| Roberta\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'' \n| Ruby\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor]]<br />[[African-American Film Critics Association|African-American Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Motion Picture]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Actress]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Ensemble]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Village Voice Film Poll|Village Voice Film Poll Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Addicted (2014 film)|Addicted]]'' \n| Brina\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''In the Morning'' \n| Cadence\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Invitation (2015 film)|The Invitation]]'' \n| Kira\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Miles Ahead (film)|Miles Ahead]]'' \n| [[Miles Davis|Frances Taylor]]\n| \n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Beats (American film)|Beats]]'' \n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' \n| Nurse Susan Mehta\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Katrina'' \n| Katrina\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Nanny Express]]'' \n| Lorraine\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Romantically Challenged]]'' \n| Tiffany\n| Episode: \"Rebecca's One Night Stand\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' \n| Ellen Samsen\n| Episode: \"The Edge of Winter\"\n|-\n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[Hand of God (TV series)|Hand of God]]'' \n| Tessie Graham \n| 20 episodes \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Rosewood (TV series)|Rosewood]]''\n| Gigi Gaston\n| Episode: \"Fashionistas and Fasciitis\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Roots (2016 miniseries)|Roots]]''\n| Belle\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017 - 2018\n| ''[[Ballers]]''\n| Candace Brewer\n| Recurring\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Red Line (TV series)|The Red Line]]''\n| Tia Young\n| Main role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1538675}}\n\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corinealdi, Emayatzy}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Panamanian descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actress|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Emayatzy Corinealdi\n|image = Emayatzy Corinealdi.jpg\n| caption = Corinealdi in June 2012\n| occupation  = Actress\n| years_active = 2008\u2013present\n| spouse       =\n| children     =\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1980|01|14|}}\n|birth_place=[[Fort Knox|Fort Knox, Kentucky]], U.S.\n}}\n\n'''Emayatzy Evett Corinealdi'''<ref name='KY-Birth'>{{cite web |url= |title=Kentucky, Birth Index, 1911-1999 [database on-line] |last= |first= |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.-->|year=2006 |website=Ancestry.com |series= |publisher= Ancestry.com Operations Inc. |quote=Original data: Kentucky Department for Libraries and Archives. Kentucky Birth, Marriage, and Death Databases: Births 1911-1999. Frankfort, Kentucky: Kentucky Department for Libraries and Archives. |ref= |separator= |postscript= }}</ref> ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|\u025b|m|e\u026a|\u02c8|\u0251\u02d0|t|s|i|_|\u02cc|k|\u0252r|\u026a|\u02c8|n|\u0251\u02d0|l|d|i}} {{respell|EM|ay|AHT|see|_|KORR|ih|NAHL|dee}}; born January 14, 1980)<ref name='KY-Birth'/> is an American actress. She is best known for her leading role in the [[Ava DuVernay]] film ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'' (2012).\n\n==Early life==\nCorinealdi was born in [[Fort Knox|Fort Knox, Kentucky]],<ref name='KY-Birth'/><ref name=BET1>{{cite web| url= http://www.bet.com/topics/e/emayatzy-corinealdi.html |title= Emayatzy Corinealdi | website= BET.com |publisher=BET Interactive, LLC |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> the daughter of Rosemarie Hilton and Edward Corinealdi. Her father is [[Panamanians|Panamanian]], while her mother is [[African-American]] from [[Ohio]].<ref name='KY-Birth'/><ref>[http://blackactors.net/2011/06/the-cast-of-ava-duvernays-middle-of-nowhere/ THE CAST OF AVA DUVERNAY'S 'MIDDLE OF NOWHERE'] at BlackActors.net</ref><ref name=\"backstage breakout\">{{cite web| url= http://www.backstage.com/interview/middle-nowhere-star-emayatzy-corinealdi-her-breakout-leading-role/ | title= Interview: 'Middle of Nowhere' Star Emayatzy Corinealdi on Her Breakout Leading Role | first= Jenelle |last= Riley |date= 11 September 2012 |accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> As a member of a military family, she was raised between [[Germany]] and the U.S. states of Ohio, [[Kansas]], and [[New Jersey]].<ref name=\"backstage breakout\" /><ref name= \"good role\">{{cite news| title= Emayatzy Corinealdi finds a good role in 'Middle of Nowhere' | date= 13 October 2012| first= Nicole |last= Sperling |work= Los Angeles Times |url= http://articles.latimes.com/2012/oct/13/entertainment/la-et-mn-emayatzy-corinealdi-20121014 | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> She studied in New Jersey at the Actor's Training Studio, then at the [[William Esper Studio]] in [[New York City]], then at Playhouse West.<ref name= \"good role\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn her early career, Corinealdi co-starred in a number of independent and short films, had the recurring role on the CBS daytime soap opera, ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'', and appeared in the Hallmark television film, ''[[The Nanny Express]]'' (2008). In 2012, she made her feature film debut as the lead in the drama ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]''. Corinealdi won the 14th Annual [[American Black Film Festival]] Star Project,<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.clutchmagonline.com/2014/09/look-book-favorite-emayatzy-corinealdi-style-beauty-looks/ | work= Clutch Magazine| publisher= Sutton New Media LLC| title = Look Book: Our Favorite Emayatzy Corinealdi Style and Beauty Looks |author= Clutch |date= September 2014 | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> an international acting competition for emerging multicultural artists. Later that year, she won the [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor]] for the film.<ref>{{cite web| url= http://hellobeautiful.com/2012/11/28/middle-of-nowhere-emayatzy-corinealdi-wins-best-actor-gotham-film-awards/ | title= Emayatzy Corinealdi Of 'Middle Of Nowhere' Wins Gotham Film Awards' Best Actor | date= 28 November 2012 |first= Danielle |last= Young | website= HelloBeautiful.com | publisher= Interactive One| accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref>  She was also nominated for an [[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]].<ref>{{cite news| title= Spirit Awards reaction: Jack Black, Matthew McConaughey, Benh Zeitlin, David O. Russell, more weigh in | work= Entertainment Weekly | first= Lindsey |last= Bahr |date= 27 November 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn 2013 Corinealdi appeared in the short film ''The Door'', part of [[Miu Miu]]'s fashion series ''Women's Tales'', which reunited her with her ''Middle of Nowhere'' director [[Ava DuVernay]].<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.miumiu.com/en/women_tales/5/film | title= \"The Door\" by Ava DuVernay, Women's Tales #5 | publisher= MiuMiu.com | accessdate= 29 December 2014}}</ref> In 2014, Corinealdi was cast in the [[Amazon Studios|Amazon]] drama series ''[[Hand of God (TV series)|Hand of God]]''. Later that year, she won the role of Frances Taylor, the wife of [[Miles Davis]] in the biographical film ''[[Miles Ahead (film)|Miles Ahead]]''.<ref name=\"BET replace\">{{cite web |url=http://www.bet.com/news/celebrities/2014/06/25/middle-of-nowhere-star-to-replace-zoe-saldana-in-miles-davis-biopic.html |title=Middle of Nowhere Star to Replace Zoe Saldana in Miles Davis Biopic  |last1=Diaz |first1=Evelyn |last2= |first2= |date=25 June 2014 |website=BET.com |publisher=BET Interactive, LLC |accessdate=16 November 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2003\n| ''Pretty Lady'' \n| Azizi\n| \n|-\n| 2004\n| ''Vampz'' \n| Eve\n| \n|-\n| 2005\n| ''[[Beauty Shop]]'' \n| Client of Ida\n| Uncredited\n|-\n| 2006\n| ''My American Nurse'' \n| \n| \n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Cordially Invited'' \n| Grace Ingrahm\n|\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Akira's Hip-Hop Shop''\n| Daphne\n|\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''Wednesday Again'' \n| Roberta\n| \n|-\n| 2012\n| ''[[Middle of Nowhere (2012 film)|Middle of Nowhere]]'' \n| Ruby\n| [[Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor]]<br />[[African-American Film Critics Association|African-American Film Critics Association Award for Best Actress]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Independent Spirit Award for Best Female Lead]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[NAACP Image Award for Outstanding Actress in a Motion Picture]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Actress]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Black Reel Award for Best Ensemble]]<br />Nominated\u2014[[Village Voice Film Poll|Village Voice Film Poll Award for Best Breakthrough Performance]]\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Addicted (2014 film)|Addicted]]'' \n| Brina\n| \n|-\n| 2014\n| ''In the Morning'' \n| Cadence\n| \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[The Invitation (2015 film)|The Invitation]]'' \n| Kira\n|\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Miles Ahead (film)|Miles Ahead]]'' \n| [[Miles Davis|Frances Taylor]]\n| \n|-\n| 2019 \n| ''[[Beats (American film)|Beats]]'' \n|\n|\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! class=\"unsortable\" |Notes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''[[The Young and the Restless]]'' \n| Nurse Susan Mehta\n| 4 episodes\n|-\n| 2007\n| ''Katrina'' \n| Katrina\n| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n| 2008\n| ''[[The Nanny Express]]'' \n| Lorraine\n| Television film\n|-\n| 2010\n| ''[[Romantically Challenged]]'' \n| Tiffany\n| Episode: \"Rebecca's One Night Stand\"\n|-\n| 2014\n| ''[[Criminal Minds]]'' \n| Ellen Samsen\n| Episode: \"The Edge of Winter\"\n|-\n| 2014\u20132017\n| ''[[Hand of God (TV series)|Hand of God]]'' \n| Tessie Graham \n| 20 episodes \n|-\n| 2015\n| ''[[Rosewood (TV series)|Rosewood]]''\n| Gigi Gaston\n| Episode: \"Fashionistas and Fasciitis\"\n|-\n| 2016\n| ''[[Roots (2016 miniseries)|Roots]]''\n| Belle\n| 2 episodes\n|-\n| 2017\n| ''[[Ballers]]''\n| Candace Brewer\n| Recurring\n|-\n| 2019\n| ''[[The Red Line (TV series)|The Red Line]]''\n| Tia Young\n| Main role\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{IMDb name|1538675}}\n\n{{Gotham Independent Film Award for Breakthrough Actor}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Corinealdi, Emayatzy}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Kentucky]]\n[[Category:Actresses from New Jersey]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American people of Panamanian descent]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Military brats]]\n[[Category:African-American actresses]]\n", "name_user": "Highly beloved", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eTelevision", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emayatzy_Corinealdi"}
{"title_page": "Josef Michl", "text_new": "'''Josef Michl''' (Born 12 March 1939 in [[Prague]]) is a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]]-[[United States|American]] [[Chemist]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nMichl was born in Prague, which was then the capital of the short-lived [[Second Czechoslovak Republic]] (1938\u20131939), in 12 March 1939. This was a few days before Nazi Germany incorporated Prague and the rest of the Czech part of the country as the [[protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]].\n\nMichl began studying chemistry at [[Charles University]] in Prague in 1956 and earned a Master's degree in 1961 under V. Hor\u00e1k and P. Zuman. In 1965 he earned [[Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences]] a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] under [[Rudolf Zahradn\u00edk]]. He worked as a [[Postdoctoral researcher]] from 1965 to 1970 for R. S. Becker at the [[University of Houston]], for [[Michael J. S. Dewar]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] and with F. E. Harris at the [[University of Utah]]. In the meantime he was research assistant at the Institute for Physical Chemistry of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences in 1967\u20131968 and assistant professor of Jan Linderberg at the Department of Chemistry at the [[Aarhus University]] in 1968\u20131969.\n\n1970 Michl received his first independent professorship at the [[University of Utah]] at [[Salt Lake City]] (Research Associate Professor), in 1971 he became an associate professor and in 1975 he received a full professorship. In 1986 Michl moved to the [[University of Texas at Austin]], but remained connected to the University of Utah as an adjunct professor. In 1991 he received a call to the University of Colorado Boulder. Since 2006, Michl has also worked as a research director for the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the [[Czech Academy of Sciences]].\n\n== Career ==\nMichl has made important contributions to numerous areas of chemistry during his career:<ref>[http://www.iaqms.org/members/michl.php Josef Michl] from the ''International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science'' (iaqms.org); accessed 10 May 2014</ref> theoretical and experimental aspects of organic [[photochemistry]], [[magnetic circular dichroism]], chemistry and theory of biradicals and biradicaloids, electronic and vibrational [[spectroscopy]] with [[Polarization (waves)|polarized light]], [[silicon]] chemistry and electronic structure, theory and experiment of [[Sputtering|sputtered]] frozen gases, properties and theory of organic [[Reaction intermediate]]s, [[Cluster chemistry|cluster-ions]], molecular building blocks for [[Supramolecular chemistry|supramolecular structures]] and [[boron]] chemistry.\n\nMichl was editor of the ACS journal [[Chemical Reviews]] from 1984 to 2014. He is co-author of five textbooks on [[Photochemistry]] and Polarization spectroscopy, is author of more than 570 scientific publications and holds 11 patents.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 1971\u20131975 [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation]] [[Sloan Research Fellowship|Research Fellowship]]\n* 1984/85 [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim-Stipend]]\n* 1986 Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]]\n* 1990 [[Honorary doctorate]] from [[Georgetown University]]\n* 1992 [[Schr\u00f6dinger Medal]]\n* 1994 Heyrovsk\u00fd-Medaille from [[Czech Academy of Sciences]]\n* 1995 Gold medal [[Charles University]]\n* 1995 Honorary member of the [[Learned Society of the Czech Republic]]\n* 1996 Honorary doctorate from [[University of Pardubice|Universit\u00e4t Pardubice]]\n* 1999 Mitglied of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* 2001 [[James Flack Norris Award for Outstanding Achievement in the Teaching of Chemistry|James Flack Norris Award]] from [[American Chemical Society]]\n* 2001 [[Otto Wichterle]] prize from Czech chemical society\n* 2004 Honorary doctorate from [[Masaryk University]]\n\n== External links==\n\n* [http://encyklopedie.brna.cz/home-mmb/?acc=profil_osobnosti&load=3028 Prof. Josef Michl] on encyklopedie.brna.cz\n* [https://chem.colorado.edu/michlgroup/ Michl Research Group] on the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] website\n* [http://www.uochb.cz/web/structure/338.html?do%5BloadData%5D=1&itemKey=en_1 Prof. Josef Michl, Ph.D.] on the IOCB website\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science members]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Utah faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "'''Josef Michl''' (Born 12 March 1939 in [[Prague]]) is a [[Czechoslovakia|Czechoslovak]]-[[United States|American]] [[Chemist]].\n==Early life and education==\nMichl was born in Prague, which was then the capital of the short-lived [[Second Czechoslovak Republic]] (1938\u20131939), in 12 March 1939. This was a few days before Nazi Germany incorporated Prague and the rest of the Czech part of the country as the [[protectorate of Bohemia and Moravia]].\n\nMichl began studying chemistry at [[Charles University]] in Prague in 1956 and earned a Master's degree in 1961 under V. Hor\u00e1k and P. Zuman. In 1965 he earned [[Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences]] a [[Doctor of Philosophy|Ph.D.]] under [[Rudolf Zahradn\u00edk]]. He worked as a [[Postdoctoral researcher]] from 1965 to 1970 for R. S. Becker at the [[University of Houston]], for [[Michael J. S. Dewar]] at the [[University of Texas at Austin]] and with F. E. Harris at the [[University of Utah]]. In the meantime he was research assistant at the Institute for Physical Chemistry of the Czechoslovak Academy of Sciences in 1967\u20131968 and assistant professor of Jan Linderberg at the Department of Chemistry at the [[Aarhus University]] in 1968\u20131969.\n\n1970 Michl received his first independent professorship at the [[University of Utah]] at [[Salt Lake City]] (Research Associate Professor), in 1971 he became an associate professor and in 1975 he received a full professorship. In 1986 Michl moved to the [[University of Texas at Austin]], but remained connected to the University of Utah as an adjunct professor. In 1991 he received a call to the University of Colorado Boulder. Since 2006, Michl has also worked as a research director for the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry at the [[Czech Academy of Sciences]].\n\n== Career ==\nMichl has made important contributions to numerous areas of chemistry during his career::<ref>[http://www.iaqms.org/members/michl.php Josef Michl] from the ''International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science'' (iaqms.org); accessed 10 May 2014</ref> theoretical and experimental aspects of organic [[photochemistry]], [[magnetic circular dichroism]], chemistry and theory of biradicals and biradicaloids, electronic and vibrational [[spectroscopy]] with [[Polarization (waves)|polarized light]], [[silicon]] chemistry and electronic structure, theory and experiment of [[Sputtering|sputtered]] frozen gases, properties and theory of organic [[Reaction intermediate]]s, [[Cluster chemistry|cluster-ions]], molecular building blocks for [[Supramolecular chemistry|supramolecular structures]] and [[boron]] chemistry.\n\nMichl was editor of the ACS journal [[Chemical Reviews]] from 1984 to 2014. He is co-author of five textbooks on [[Photochemistry]] and Polarization spectroscopy, is author of more than 570 scientific publications and holds 11 patents.\n\n== Awards ==\n\n* 1971\u20131975 [[Alfred P. Sloan Foundation]] [[Sloan Research Fellowship|Research Fellowship]]\n* 1984/85 [[Guggenheim Fellowship|Guggenheim-Stipend]]\n* 1986 Member of the [[National Academy of Sciences]]\n* 1990 [[Honorary doctorate]] from [[Georgetown University]]\n* 1992 [[Schr\u00f6dinger Medal]]\n* 1994 Heyrovsk\u00fd-Medaille from [[Czech Academy of Sciences]]\n* 1995 Gold medal [[Charles University]]\n* 1995 Honorary member of the [[Learned Society of the Czech Republic]]\n* 1996 Honorary doctorate from [[University of Pardubice|Universit\u00e4t Pardubice]]\n* 1999 Mitglied of the [[American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n* 2001 [[James Flack Norris Award for Outstanding Achievement in the Teaching of Chemistry|James Flack Norris Award]] from [[American Chemical Society]]\n* 2001 [[Otto Wichterle]] prize from Czech chemical society\n* 2004 Honorary doctorate from [[Masaryk University]]\n\n== External links==\n\n* [http://encyklopedie.brna.cz/home-mmb/?acc=profil_osobnosti&load=3028 Prof. Josef Michl] on encyklopedie.brna.cz\n* [https://chem.colorado.edu/michlgroup/ Michl Research Group] on the [[University of Colorado Boulder]] website\n* [http://www.uochb.cz/web/structure/338.html?do%5BloadData%5D=1&itemKey=en_1 Prof. Josef Michl, Ph.D.] on the IOCB website\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:International Academy of Quantum Molecular Science members]]\n[[Category:Fellows of the American Academy of Arts and Sciences]]\n[[Category:Members of the United States National Academy of Sciences]]\n[[Category:University of Colorado Boulder faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Texas at Austin faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Utah faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:20th-century chemists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Josef_Michl"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic on Charles de Gaulle", "text_new": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on Charles de Gaulle}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on ''Charles de Gaulle''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board ''Charles de Gaulle''\n| image = French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91) underway on 24 April 2019 (190424-M-BP588-1005).jpg\n| caption = ''Charles de Gaulle'' in April 2019\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[North Sea]]\n| first_case = {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}}\n| arrival_date = 10 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = Unknown\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 1,046<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/covid-19-940-marins-positifs-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-et-son-escorte-20200417|title=Covid-19: 1081 marins positifs sur le \"Charles de Gaulle\" et son escorte|trans-title=Covid-19: 1081 positive sailors on the \"Charles de Gaulle\" and his escort|website=lefigaro.fr|date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.rtl.fr/actu/bien-etre/coronavirus-en-france-un-deuxieme-marin-du-charles-de-gaulle-en-reanimation-7800413759 Coronavirus en France : un deuxi\u00e8me marin du Charles de Gaulle en r\u00e9animation]</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nIn April 2020, the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} and the Aeronaval Group of the [[Naval Action Force]], its [[carrier battle group]].\n\n== Background ==\n''Charles de Gaulle'' was constructed for the [[French Navy]] in [[Brest, France|Brest]] from 1980 to 2001.<ref name=\"InsideOver\">{{Cite news|last=Bartoccini|first=Davide|url=https://www.insideover.com/indepths/war/the-charles-de-gaulle-aircraft-carrier-frances-naval-power.html|title=The Charles de Gaulle aircraft carrier: France\u2019s naval power|date=7 February 2020|work=InsideOver|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|others=Translated by Ruth Lebens}}</ref> The ship's completion was severely delayed by budget cuts and mechanical problems, which included a snapped propeller.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whitney|first=Craig R.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/08/world/brest-french-home-port-sees-future-of-mothballs.html|title=Brest, French Home Port, Sees Future of Mothballs|date=8 August 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fleming|first=Charles|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1002834194102673920|title=Troubled Aircraft Carrier Illustrates France's\nPoor Military Preparedness|date=12 October 2001|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A mid-sized carrier, ''Charles de Gaulle'' is smaller than American [[supercarrier]]s but larger than similar ships operated or retired by Russia, India, and Brazil.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lyons|first=Patrick J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/10/world/what-in-the-world/whos-got-a-carrier-to-rival-the-us-navy-hint-not-russia.html|title=Who\u2019s Got a Carrier to Rival the U.S. Navy\u2019s? (Hint: Not Russia.)|date=9 August 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Charles de Gaulle'' was commissioned, the French government quickly deployed it to support the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]. The ship also saw active service in supporting NATO's [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]] (2011) and the [[International military intervention against ISIL]] (2015). In 2017, the aircraft carrier underwent a nearly two-year refit which modernized it for an intended additional twenty years of service.<ref name=\"InsideOver\"/> In January 2020, the French government ordered ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its assocated [[carrier battle group#France|carrier battle group]] to deploy to the Eastern Mediterranean for further operations against ISIL, after which it would transit through the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] and engage in multinational training exercises in the Atlantic Ocean and [[North Sea]].<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\">{{Cite news|last=Breeden|first=Aurelien|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/europe/france-navy-ship-coronavirus.html|title=How an Invisible Foe Slipped Aboard a French Navy Ship|date=19 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"leopold.naval\">{{Cite news|last=Vavasseur|first=Xavier|url=https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2020/01/french-carrier-strike-group-begins-foch-deployment/|title=French Carrier Strike Group Begins \u2018Foch\u2019 Deployment|date=22 January 2020|work=Naval News|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Causes and event ==\nAfter several weeks on station in the eastern Mediterranean, ''Charles de Gaulle'' proceeded to the Atlantic and North Sea for naval exercises. From 13&ndash;15 March, the ship was docked in Brest for a brief port visit. The enactment of a strict lockdown to combat the ongoing coronavirus pandemic came two days after the ship left Brest, and the sailors were allowed [[shore leave]] that included seeing family members and visiting local commercial establishments.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Willsher|first=Kim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/16/inquiry-french-aircraft-carrier-crew-catch-coronavirus-charles-de-gaulle|title=Inquiry after 668 of French aircraft carrier's crew catch coronavirus|date=16 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sabbagh|first2=Dan}}</ref> ''Charles de Gaulle''{{'}}s crew did not have contact with the outside world for the next three weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|date=11 April 2020|work=franceinfo|language=French|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Belgium's [[frigate]] {{ship|Belgian frigate|Leopold I|F930|2}}, part of the carrier battle group, was ordered to prepare to leave the force on 24 March after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on military ships#Leopold I|detecting a single coronavirus case]].<ref name=\"leopold.naval\"/><ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruxelles2.eu/2020/04/covid-19-did-belgium-make-the-right-choice-by-interrupting-the-foch-mission/?lang=en|title=Covid-19. Did Belgium make the right choice by interrupting the Foch mission|first=Nicolas|last=Gros-Verheyde|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The nature of warships, which includes working with others in small enclosed areas and a lack of private quarters for the vast majority of crew, lent themselves to the rapid spread of the disease to a degree even greater than that seen on [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|cruise ships]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Faturechi|first=Robert|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/after-discovering-a-sailor-with-coronavirus-the-us-navy-crowded-dozens-into-one-room|title=After Discovering a Sailor With Coronavirus, the U.S. Navy Crowded Dozens Into One Room|date=16 March 2020|work=ProPublica|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Rose|first2=Megan|last3=Miller|first3=T. Christian}}</ref> Indeed, on ''Charles de Gaulle'' there were places where 20 people would sleep together on three or four floors of [[Berth (sleeping)|berths]].<ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/marins-contamines-au-covid-19-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-a-des-endroits-il-y-a-une-vingtaine-de-matelots-qui-dorment-sur-3-ou-4-etages-de-couchettes_3922411.html |title=Marins contamin\u00e9s au Covid-19 sur le \"Charles-de-Gaulle\" : \"\u00c0 des endroits, il y a une vingtaine de matelots qui dorment sur 3 ou 4 \u00e9tages de couchettes\" |language=fr |access-date=18 April 2020| website=franceinfo}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, several [[common cold]]s were registered onboard, but the level of sick sailors was not above the ordinary for the frigid -5&nbsp;\u00b0C temperature and strong winds of the region ''Charles de Gaulle'' was operating in.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref name=\"figaro\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/france-un-tiers-des-marins-du-porte-avions-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-coronavirus-20200415|title=Coronavirus: un tiers des marins du porte-avions Charles-de-Gaulle sont infect\u00e9s|language=fr|access-date=18 April 2020|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref> Starting on 5 April, however, the number of crew members reporting to the infirmary began growing exponentially to alarming levels. Two sailors were medically scanned and found to be infected by the coronavirus, after which the French defense minister [[Florence Parly]] ordered the carrier to return to its home port of Toulon.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/fr/20200408-coronavirus-plusieurs-cas-suspects-\u00e0-bord-du-porte-avions-fran\u00e7ais-charles-de-gaulle |title=Coronavirus : plusieurs cas suspects \u00e0 bord du porte-avions fran\u00e7ais Charles-de-Gaulle |language=French |work=France 24 |trans-title=Coronavirus: several suspected cases on board the French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters-heading\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-military/french-military-ship-heading-back-to-port-due-to-possible-covid-19-cases-idUSKBN21Q0SY |title=French aircraft carrier heads home early due to possible COVID-19 cases |work=Reuters |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, French news outlets reported that out of 66 tests conducted onboard the aircraft carrier, 50 had returned positive.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/coronavirus-50-cas-de-contamination-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-trois-marins-evacues-10-04-2020-8297511.php |title=Coronavirus : 50 cas de contamination \u00e0 bord du \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", trois marins \u00e9vacu\u00e9s |work=Le Parisien |language=French |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Three sailors were evacuated by air to {{ill|Saint Anne Army Teaching Hospital|fr|H\u00f4pital d'instruction des arm\u00e9es Sainte-Anne}}.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\" /><ref name=\"gaulle.times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/10/world/europe/10reuters-health-coronavirus-france-aircraftcarrier.html|title=France Reports 50 COVID-19 Cases Aboard Aircraft Carrier |website=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There were 1,760 personnel on board.<ref name=\"reuters-heading\"/> \n\nThe carrier arrived in Toulon on the afternoon of 12 April, where the personnel began a 14-day quarantine.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696|title=Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\" |access-date=18 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAt first, the origin of the outbreak was unknown; there had been no contact with the outside world after the ship's stopover in Brest.<ref name=\"franceinfo\"/><ref name=\"europe1_between\"/>{{efn|Between 13 and 16 March}} The captain had given the crew orders to avoid an infection and a family day had been cancelled. However, the girlfriend of a sailor said in an interview on [[Easter Sunday]] that some sailors had eaten in the same restaurants as their wives or families. She also said that sailors of other nationalities had been there, too.<ref>http://www.europe1.fr: [https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696 ''Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s'']</ref> As of 18 April, Brest is considered the point of infection.<ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\"/>\n\nOn 15 April 2020, the Ministry of Armed Forces reported that, out of the 1,767 tests conducted on the members of the carrier battle group, 668 returned positive, with the vast majority of cases being aboard ''Charles de Gaulle''.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\">https://mobile.twitter.com/Armees_Gouv/status/1250513114161909763</ref>{{efn|30% of the tests were still inconclusive.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" />}}  The 1,700 sailors of ''Charles de Gaulle'' were subsequently quarantined for two weeks.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.bleu\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/coronavirus-au-moins-500-marins-du-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-covid-19-1586960222 |title = Coronavirus : Pr\u00e8s de 700 marins positifs au Covid-19, la majorit\u00e9 sur le porte-avions Charles de Gaulle|date = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, the numbers reported went up to more than 1,000 infected, from 2,000 tested, with 500 showing symptoms, 24 admitted to hospital and one of them to an [[intensive care unit]] (ICU).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/corona-frankreich-flugzeugtraeger-101.html |title = 1000 Seeleute auf \"Charles de Gaulle\" infiziert}}</ref> \n\n[[File:US_Navy_110321-N-0000X-027_Adm._Samuel_J._Locklear,_III_speaks_with_an_aircrew_team_from_the_French_Navy_aircraft_carrier_Charles_de_Gaulle_(R91).jpg|thumb|Admiral [[Samuel J. Locklear]] inside ''Charles de Gaulle'' (2011)]]\nOn 18 April, it was reported that 1,081 out of 2,300 people on both ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its escort, [[frigate]] {{ship|French frigate|Chevalier Paul||2}}, tested positive. Two investigations have been launched. One on the situation in Brest and one lead by admiral [[Christophe Prazuck]] on the epidemic on board of the carrier strike group.<ref name=\"figaro\"/>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Number of confirmed cases over time ==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width= <!-- 300 -->\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 10 Apr, 15 Apr, 18 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 50, 668, 1046\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{#related:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:History of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Europe]]\n[[Category:Military history of the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on transport|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the military|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic on Charles de Gaulle}}\n{{DISPLAYTITLE:2020 coronavirus pandemic on ''Charles de Gaulle''}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic on board ''Charles de Gaulle''\n| image = French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle (R91) underway on 24 April 2019 (190424-M-BP588-1005).jpg\n| caption = ''Charles de Gaulle'' in April 2019\n| map1 = \n| legend1 = \n| map2 = \n| legend2 = \n| map3 = \n| legend3 = \n| disease = [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[North Sea]]\n| first_case = {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}}\n| arrival_date = 10 April 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=04|day1=10|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = \n| recovery_cases = Unknown\n| deaths = 0\n| confirmed_cases = 1,046<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/covid-19-940-marins-positifs-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-et-son-escorte-20200417|title=Covid-19: 1081 marins positifs sur le \"Charles de Gaulle\" et son escorte|trans-title=Covid-19: 1081 positive sailors on the \"Charles de Gaulle\" and his escort|website=lefigaro.fr|date=17 April 2020}}</ref><ref>[https://www.rtl.fr/actu/bien-etre/coronavirus-en-france-un-deuxieme-marin-du-charles-de-gaulle-en-reanimation-7800413759 Coronavirus en France : un deuxi\u00e8me marin du Charles de Gaulle en r\u00e9animation]</ref>\n| suspected_cases = \n| total_ili = \n| website = \n}}\nIn April 2020, the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] reached the French aircraft carrier {{ship|French aircraft carrier|Charles de Gaulle||2}} and the Aeronaval Group of the [[Naval Action Force]], it's [[carrier battle group]].\n\n== Background ==\n''Charles de Gaulle'' was constructed for the [[French Navy]] in [[Brest, France|Brest]] from 1980 to 2001.<ref name=\"InsideOver\">{{Cite news|last=Bartoccini|first=Davide|url=https://www.insideover.com/indepths/war/the-charles-de-gaulle-aircraft-carrier-frances-naval-power.html|title=The Charles de Gaulle aircraft carrier: France\u2019s naval power|date=7 February 2020|work=InsideOver|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|others=Translated by Ruth Lebens}}</ref> The ship's completion was severely delayed by budget cuts and mechanical problems, which included a snapped propeller.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Whitney|first=Craig R.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/08/world/brest-french-home-port-sees-future-of-mothballs.html|title=Brest, French Home Port, Sees Future of Mothballs|date=8 August 1997|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=Fleming|first=Charles|url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/SB1002834194102673920|title=Troubled Aircraft Carrier Illustrates France's\nPoor Military Preparedness|date=12 October 2001|work=The Wall Street Journal|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> A mid-sized carrier, ''Charles de Gaulle'' is smaller than American [[supercarrier]]s but larger than similar ships operated or retired by Russia, India, and Brazil.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Lyons|first=Patrick J.|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/08/10/world/what-in-the-world/whos-got-a-carrier-to-rival-the-us-navy-hint-not-russia.html|title=Who\u2019s Got a Carrier to Rival the U.S. Navy\u2019s? (Hint: Not Russia.)|date=9 August 2016|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nAfter ''Charles de Gaulle'' was commissioned, the French government quickly deployed it to support the [[War in Afghanistan (2001\u2013present)|War in Afghanistan]]. The ship also saw active service in supporting NATO's [[2011 military intervention in Libya|military intervention in Libya]] (2011) and the [[International military intervention against ISIL]] (2015). In 2017, the aircraft carrier underwent a nearly two-year refit which modernized it for an intended additional twenty years of service.<ref name=\"InsideOver\"/> In January 2020, the French government ordered ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its assocated [[carrier battle group#France|carrier battle group]] to deploy to the Eastern Mediterranean for further operations against ISIL, after which it would transit through the [[Strait of Gibraltar]] and engage in multinational training exercises in the Atlantic Ocean and [[North Sea]].<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\">{{Cite news|last=Breeden|first=Aurelien|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/04/19/world/europe/france-navy-ship-coronavirus.html|title=How an Invisible Foe Slipped Aboard a French Navy Ship|date=19 April 2020|work=The New York Times|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"leopold.naval\">{{Cite news|last=Vavasseur|first=Xavier|url=https://www.navalnews.com/naval-news/2020/01/french-carrier-strike-group-begins-foch-deployment/|title=French Carrier Strike Group Begins \u2018Foch\u2019 Deployment|date=22 January 2020|work=Naval News|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Causes and event ==\nAfter several weeks on station in the eastern Mediterranean, ''Charles de Gaulle'' proceeded to the Atlantic and North Sea for naval exercises. From 13&ndash;15 March, the ship was docked in Brest for a brief port visit. The enactment of a strict lockdown to combat the ongoing coronavirus pandemic came two days after the ship left Brest, and the sailors were allowed [[shore leave]] that included seeing family members and visiting local commercial establishments.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref>{{Cite news|last=Willsher|first=Kim|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/apr/16/inquiry-french-aircraft-carrier-crew-catch-coronavirus-charles-de-gaulle|title=Inquiry after 668 of French aircraft carrier's crew catch coronavirus|date=16 April 2020|work=The Guardian|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Sabbagh|first2=Dan}}</ref> ''Charles de Gaulle''{{'}}s crew did not have contact with the outside world for the next three weeks.<ref>{{Cite news|last=|first=|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|date=11 April 2020|work=franceinfo|language=French|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Belgium's [[frigate]] {{ship|Belgian frigate|Leopold I|F930|2}}, part of the carrier battle group, was ordered to prepare to leave the force on 24 March after [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on military ships#Leopold I|detecting a single coronavirus case]].<ref name=\"leopold.naval\"/><ref name=\"leopold.bruxelles2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.bruxelles2.eu/2020/04/covid-19-did-belgium-make-the-right-choice-by-interrupting-the-foch-mission/?lang=en|title=Covid-19. Did Belgium make the right choice by interrupting the Foch mission|first=Nicolas|last=Gros-Verheyde|date=10 April 2020}}</ref> The nature of warships, which includes working with others in small enclosed areas and a lack of private quarters for the vast majority of crew, lent themselves to the rapid spread of the disease to a degree even greater than that seen on [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on cruise ships|cruise ships]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Faturechi|first=Robert|url=https://www.propublica.org/article/after-discovering-a-sailor-with-coronavirus-the-us-navy-crowded-dozens-into-one-room|title=After Discovering a Sailor With Coronavirus, the U.S. Navy Crowded Dozens Into One Room|date=16 March 2020|work=ProPublica|access-date=24 April 2020|url-status=live|last2=Rose|first2=Megan|last3=Miller|first3=T. Christian}}</ref> Indeed, on ''Charles de Gaulle'' there were places where 20 people would sleep together on three or four floors of [[Berth (sleeping)|berths]].<ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/marins-contamines-au-covid-19-sur-le-charles-de-gaulle-a-des-endroits-il-y-a-une-vingtaine-de-matelots-qui-dorment-sur-3-ou-4-etages-de-couchettes_3922411.html |title=Marins contamin\u00e9s au Covid-19 sur le \"Charles-de-Gaulle\" : \"\u00c0 des endroits, il y a une vingtaine de matelots qui dorment sur 3 ou 4 \u00e9tages de couchettes\" |language=fr |access-date=18 April 2020| website=franceinfo}}</ref>\n\nDuring this time, several [[common cold]]s were registered onboard, but the level of sick sailors was not above the ordinary for the frigid -5&nbsp;\u00b0C temperature and strong winds of the region ''Charles de Gaulle'' was operating in.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref name=\"figaro\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.lefigaro.fr/flash-actu/france-un-tiers-des-marins-du-porte-avions-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-coronavirus-20200415|title=Coronavirus: un tiers des marins du porte-avions Charles-de-Gaulle sont infect\u00e9s|language=fr|access-date=18 April 2020|website=[[Le Figaro]]}}</ref> Starting on 5 April, however, the number of crew members reporting to the infirmary began growing exponentially to alarming levels. Two sailors were medically scanned and found to be infected by the coronavirus, after which the French defense minister [[Florence Parly]] ordered the carrier to return to its home port of Toulon.<ref name=\"Invisible Foe\"/><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.france24.com/fr/20200408-coronavirus-plusieurs-cas-suspects-\u00e0-bord-du-porte-avions-fran\u00e7ais-charles-de-gaulle |title=Coronavirus : plusieurs cas suspects \u00e0 bord du porte-avions fran\u00e7ais Charles-de-Gaulle |language=French |work=France 24 |trans-title=Coronavirus: several suspected cases on board the French aircraft carrier Charles de Gaulle |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"reuters-heading\">{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-health-coronavirus-france-military/french-military-ship-heading-back-to-port-due-to-possible-covid-19-cases-idUSKBN21Q0SY |title=French aircraft carrier heads home early due to possible COVID-19 cases |work=Reuters |date=8 April 2020 |access-date=8 April 2020}}</ref> On 10 April, French news outlets reported that out of 66 tests conducted onboard the aircraft carrier, 50 had returned positive.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\">{{cite web |url=http://www.leparisien.fr/politique/coronavirus-50-cas-de-contamination-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-trois-marins-evacues-10-04-2020-8297511.php |title=Coronavirus : 50 cas de contamination \u00e0 bord du \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", trois marins \u00e9vacu\u00e9s |work=Le Parisien |language=French |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> Three sailors were evacuated by air to {{ill|Saint Anne Army Teaching Hospital|fr|H\u00f4pital d'instruction des arm\u00e9es Sainte-Anne}}.<ref name=\"gaulle.parisien\" /><ref name=\"gaulle.times\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/reuters/2020/04/10/world/europe/10reuters-health-coronavirus-france-aircraftcarrier.html|title=France Reports 50 COVID-19 Cases Aboard Aircraft Carrier |website=The New York Times |agency=Reuters |date=10 April 2020 |access-date=11 April 2020}}</ref> There were 1,760 personnel on board.<ref name=\"reuters-heading\"/> \n\nThe carrier arrived in Toulon on the afternoon of 12 April, where the personnel began a 14-day quarantine.<ref name=\"franceinfo\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.francetvinfo.fr/sante/maladie/coronavirus/coronavirus-le-porte-avions-francais-charles-de-gaulle-et-ses-50-cas-de-covid-19-a-bord-est-attendu-a-toulon-dimanche-apres-midi_3910907.html|title=Coronavirus : le porte-avions fran\u00e7ais \"Charles-de-Gaulle\", et ses 50 cas de Covid-19 \u00e0 bord, est attendu \u00e0 Toulon dimanche apr\u00e8s-midi|language=fr|access-date=12 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"europe1_between\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696|title=Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s\" |access-date=18 April 2020|language=fr}}</ref>\n\nAt first, the origin of the outbreak was unknown; there had been no contact with the outside world after the ship's stopover in Brest.<ref name=\"franceinfo\"/><ref name=\"europe1_between\"/>{{efn|Between 13 and 16 March}} The captain had given the crew orders to avoid an infection and a family day had been cancelled. However, the girlfriend of a sailor said in an interview on [[Easter Sunday]] that some sailors had eaten in the same restaurants as their wives or families. She also said that sailors of other nationalities had been there, too.<ref>http://www.europe1.fr: [https://www.europe1.fr/societe/covid-19-a-bord-du-charles-de-gaulle-les-marins-qui-nont-pas-respecte-les-regles-doivent-etre-sanctionnes-3961696 ''Les marins du Charles-de-Gaulle \"qui n\u2019ont pas respect\u00e9 les r\u00e8gles doivent \u00eatre sanctionn\u00e9s'']</ref> As of 18 April, Brest is considered the point of infection.<ref name=\"franceinfo-04-18\"/>\n\nOn 15 April 2020, the Ministry of Armed Forces reported that, out of the 1,767 tests conducted on the members of the carrier battle group, 668 returned positive, with the vast majority of cases being aboard ''Charles de Gaulle''.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\">https://mobile.twitter.com/Armees_Gouv/status/1250513114161909763</ref>{{efn|30% of the tests were still inconclusive.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" />}}  The 1,700 sailors of ''Charles de Gaulle'' were subsequently quarantined for two weeks.<ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.mda.twitter\" /><ref name=\"groupe.aeronaval.bleu\">{{Cite web | url=https://www.francebleu.fr/infos/societe/coronavirus-au-moins-500-marins-du-charles-de-gaulle-positifs-au-covid-19-1586960222 |title = Coronavirus : Pr\u00e8s de 700 marins positifs au Covid-19, la majorit\u00e9 sur le porte-avions Charles de Gaulle|date = 15 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 17 April, the numbers reported went up to more than 1,000 infected, from 2,000 tested, with 500 showing symptoms, 24 admitted to hospital and one of them to an [[intensive care unit]] (ICU).<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.tagesschau.de/ausland/corona-frankreich-flugzeugtraeger-101.html |title = 1000 Seeleute auf \"Charles de Gaulle\" infiziert}}</ref> \n\n[[File:US_Navy_110321-N-0000X-027_Adm._Samuel_J._Locklear,_III_speaks_with_an_aircrew_team_from_the_French_Navy_aircraft_carrier_Charles_de_Gaulle_(R91).jpg|thumb|Admiral [[Samuel J. Locklear]] inside ''Charles de Gaulle'' (2011)]]\nOn 18 April, it was reported that 1,081 out of 2,300 people on both ''Charles de Gaulle'' and its escort, [[frigate]] {{ship|French frigate|Chevalier Paul||2}}, tested positive. Two investigations have been launched. One on the situation in Brest and one lead by admiral [[Christophe Prazuck]] on the epidemic on board of the carrier strike group.<ref name=\"figaro\"/>\n\n== Aftermath ==\n{{expand-section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Number of confirmed cases over time ==\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n|width= <!-- 300 -->\n|colors=#F46D43\n|showValues=offset:2\n|xAxisTitle=Date\n|xAxisAngle=-40\n|type=rect\n|x= 10 Apr, 15 Apr, 18 Apr\n|yAxisTitle=Accumulated number of cases\n|legend=\n|y1= 50, 668, 1046\n|y1Title=Confirmed cases\n|yGrid= |xGrid=\n}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic on naval ships]]\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n\n\n{{COVID-19}}\n\n{{#related:2019-20 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France}}\n{{#related:2020 coronavirus pandemic on USS Theodore Roosevelt (CVN-71)}}\n\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in 2020]]\n[[Category:2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic by location|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in France|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Aircraft carriers involved in the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:History of the French Navy]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in Europe]]\n[[Category:Military history of the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Water transport in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Disasters in the North Sea]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on transport|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Impact of the 2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic on the military|Charles de Gaulle]]\n[[Category:Non-combat naval accidents]]\n", "name_user": "The ed17", "label": "safe", "comment": "typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2020_coronavirus_pandemic_on_Charles_de_Gaulle"}
{"title_page": "Mary Lou McDonald", "text_new": "{{short description|President of Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Mary Lou McDonald\n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image         = Mary Lou McDonald (official portrait).jpg\n| office        = [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| vicepresident = [[Michelle O'Neill]]\n| term_start    = 10 February 2018\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Gerry Adams]]\n| successor     = \n| office1       = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| president1    = Gerry Adams\n| term_start1   = 22 February 2009\n| term_end1     = 10 February 2018 \n| predecessor1  = [[Pat Doherty]]\n| successor1    = Michelle O'Neill\n| office2       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start2   = [[2011 Irish general election|February 2011]]\n| term_end2     = \n| constituency2 = [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]]\n| office3       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start3   = 1 July 2004\n| term_end3     = 20 June 2009\n| constituency3 = [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n| birth_name    = Mary Louise McDonald\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1969|5|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Churchtown, Dublin]], Ireland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Martin Lanigan|1996}}\n| children      = 2\n| alma_mater    = {{Ubl|[[Trinity College Dublin]]|[[University of Limerick]]|[[Dublin City University]]}}\n| website       = {{url|dublincentralsinnfein.ie|Official website}}\n|}}\n'''Mary Louise McDonald''' (born 1 May 1969) is an Irish [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] politician who has served as the [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]] since February 2018. She has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]] constituency since the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]]. She previously served as [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]] from 2009 to 2018 and a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]] constituency from 2004 to 2009.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Mary-Lou-McDonald.D.2011-03-09/|title=Mary Lou McDonald |work=Oireachtas Members Database |accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February 2018, McDonald succeeded longtime party leader [[Gerry Adams]] after a special [[ardfheis]] ([[party conference]]) in [[Dublin]].<ref name=IrishTimes2018-01-20a>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/mary-lou-mcdonald-confirmed-as-new-leader-of-sinn-f%C3%A9in-1.3362813|title=Mary Lou McDonald confirmed as new leader of Sinn F\u00e9in|work=The Irish Times|date=20 January 2018|access-date=20 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn into a [[middle-class]] family<ref name=\u201cveconomist\u201d >{{cite news|author=|title= Is Sinn Fein now a normal political party?|url= https://www.economist.com/europe/2020/03/07/is-sinn-fein-now-a-normal-political-party|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref> in [[Dublin]] to builder and surveyor Patrick McDonald and homemaker Joan, her parents separated when she was 9 years old and she stayed with her mother in [[Rathgar]].<ref>{{cite web\n | title =How Shinner babe Mary Lou came to the aid of the party\n | url =https://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/how-shinner-babe-mary-lou-came-to-the-aid-of-the-party-26221690.html\n | website =www.independent.ie\n | date =19 June 2004\n | access-date =11 February 2020  }}</ref> She has an elder brother Bernard and younger twin siblings Patrick and Joanne. Her sister Joanne had involvement with the socialist republican party [[\u00c9ir\u00edg\u00ed]] throughout the early 2000s and is a teacher.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Mary Lou McDonald \u2013 private-school educated opponent of Dublin Orange parade\n | url =https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/mary-lou-mcdonald-private-school-educated-opponent-of-dublin-orange-parade-1-8342923\n | website =www.newsletter.co.uk\n | date =23 January 2018 \n | access-date =10 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title ='Rise up and Reclaim the Republic' says new group\n | url =https://magill.ie/archive/rise-and-reclaim-republic-says-new-group\n | website =www.magill.ie\n | date =21 June 2006\n | access-date =10 February 2020 }}</ref> Her brother Patrick works as an Intellectual Property lawyer and Bernard as a scientist.\n\nMcDonald was educated at the Catholic all-girls fee paying [[Notre Dame School, Dublin|Notre Dame Des Missions]] in [[Churchtown, Dublin|Churchtown]] where she was involved in debating.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/tds-who-went-to-private-schools-split-over-cuts-3258025.html | work=Irish Independent | title=TDs who went to private schools split over cuts | date=2 December 2012}}</ref> \n\nAfter school, McDonald attended [[Trinity College Dublin]], from which she received a bachelor's degree in [[English Literature]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Grace |first=Aisling |date=February 10, 2018 |title=Trinity alumna Mary Lou McDonald elected leader of Sinn Fein |url=http://trinitynews.ie/2018/02/trinity-alumna-mary-lou-mcdonald-elected-leader-of-sinn-fein/ |work=Trinity News |location=Dublin, Ireland}}</ref> She later studied [[industrial relations]] at [[Dublin City University]],<ref>{{cite news |date=June 20, 2004 |title=Profile: Mary Lou McDonald: Shopaholic Trinity girl is face of new Sinn Fein |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/profile-mary-lou-mcdonald-shopaholic-trinity-girl-is-face-of-new-sinn-fein-fdmjch5mzbs |work=The Times |location=London, England |url-access=subscription |quote=\"...studying industrial relations at Dublin City University...\"}}</ref> and also received a [[Master of Arts]] degree in [[European integration|European Integration Studies]] from the [[University of Limerick]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |last=University of Limerick |title=My Favourite Place - Juliette Gash & Mary Lou McDonald |url=https://www.ul.ie/ullinks/our-campus/my-favourite-place-juliette-gash-mary-lou-mcdonald |work=UL Links |location=Limerick, Ireland |access-date=February 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102233609/http://www.ul.ie/ullinks/our-campus/my-favourite-place-juliette-gash-mary-lou-mcdonald |archive-date=2 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Her career to date has seen her involved in diverse roles, including consultant for the Irish Productivity Centre, researcher for the [[Institute of International and European Affairs|Institute of European Affairs]], and trainer in the Partnership Unit of the Educational and Training Services Trust.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sinn Fein Press Office |date=March 11, 2003 |title=Campaign begins to return Sinn Fein MEP for Dublin: McDonald selected as Dublin EU candidate |url=http://www.sinnfein.org/releases/03/pr031103b.html |work=Sinn Fein.org |location=Dublin, Ireland}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald became involved with the [[Irish National Congress]], a cross-party republican organisation, and became chairperson in 2000, leading a protest in [[Dublin]] against the involvement of the city's [[Lord Mayor of Dublin|Lord Mayor]] in the unveiling of a plaque at the location where the [[Grand Orange Lodge of Ireland]] held its first meeting in 1798.<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/opinion/columnists/2018/01/01/deagla-n-de-bre-adu-n-mary-lou-mcdonald-s-leadership-could-mark-a-turning-point-for-republicanism-1221623/?ref=sh Deagl\u00e1n de Br\u00e9ad\u00fan: Mary Lou McDonald's leadership could mark a turning point for republicanism], Irish News, 1 January 2018</ref>\n\n==Political career==\n===European Parliament and early D\u00e1il attempts=== \nMcDonald has been a member of the Sinn F\u00e9in party leadership since 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/28111/Mary%20Lou_McDONALD.html|title=MEP profile|accessdate=26 January 2012|publisher=[[European Parliament]]}}</ref> McDonald first ran for office when she unsuccessfully contested the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] constituency for Sinn F\u00e9in at the [[2002 Irish general election|2002 general election]], polling 8.02% of first preference votes. \n\nIn September 2003, McDonald attracted criticism when she spoke at a rally in Dublin to commemorate [[Se\u00e1n Russell]], an IRA leader with links to [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/sfs-nazi-hero-is-stalking-candidate-mary-lou-481013.html|title=SF's Nazi hero is stalking candidate Mary Lou|accessdate=25 May 2008|last=Cusack|first=Jim|date=6 June 2004|publisher=[[Irish Independent]]|quote=SINN FEIN'S Mary Lou McDonald has been accused of \"warped principles\" for participating in a republican commemoration ceremony last year for a Nazi collaborator while standing as a candidate for the European Parliament.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,6903,1391492,00.html|title=This dastardly plot|accessdate=25 May 2008|last=McDonald|first=Henry|date=16 January 2005|work=[[The Observer]]|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2004/03/14/story766283063.asp|title=Profile: Prime time Shinner|accessdate=25 May 2008|work=[[The Sunday Business Post]]|first1=Paul|last1=Colgan|first2=Neil|last2=Callanan|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041019081506/http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2004/03/14/story766283063.asp|archivedate=19 October 2004|quote=She encountered criticism after speaking at a commemoration for IRA volunteer Sean Russell last year.|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, McDonald became Sinn F\u00e9in's first [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]] when she was elected at the [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004 European Parliament election]] for the [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin constituency]], receiving over 60,000 first preference votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/result.cfm?election=2004E&cons=524|title=EU elections 2004 results \u2013 Dublin|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=14 April 2009}}</ref> She served as one of two Sinn F\u00e9in MEPs, the other being [[Bairbre de Br\u00fan]] who was representing [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]]. In 2007, she was shortlisted for the 'MEP of the Year' award by the [[European Parliament]] magazine watching for \"making the most valuable contribution in the field of employment policy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anphoblacht.com/contents/17426|title=Mary Lou McDonald shortlisted for MEP of the Year Award - An Phoblacht|website=www.anphoblacht.com}}</ref> During her time in office she led the Sinn F\u00e9in campaign against the [[Treaty of Lisbon]], which was rejected in the Republic in 2008. McDonald sat as a member of the European Parliament's Employment and Social Affairs Committee, and as a substitute of the Civil Liberties Committee.\n\nShe was an unsuccessful candidate in the [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]] constituency at the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]].\n\nMcDonald became Sinn F\u00e9in Vice President, replacing [[Pat Doherty]], following the Sinn F\u00e9in [[ardfheis]] of 22 February 2009.\n\nFor the [[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009 European Parliament election]], the number of seats for Dublin in the European Parliament was reduced from four to three. McDonald was in a tight race for the last seat against Fianna F\u00e1il's [[Eoin Ryan Jnr|Eoin Ryan]] and the [[Socialist Party (Ireland)|Socialist Party]] leader [[Joe Higgins]]. McDonald lost her seat to Higgins, being eliminated at the fifth count. Her first preference vote had declined to nearly 48,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/elections/stories/2009/0608/euroelection.html |title=Ryan loses out to Higgins in Dublin |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |date=8 June 2008 |accessdate=8 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610192742/http://www.rte.ie/news/elections/stories/2009/0608/euroelection.html |archivedate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, McDonald faced criticism after it emerged her campaign office was selling IRA souvenirs and memorabilia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheahan|first1=Fionnan|title=IRA souvenirs sell well in McDonald HQ|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/ira-souvenirs-sell-well-in-mcdonald-hq-26540510.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Independent|date=2 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinn Fein VP Mary Lou Mcdonald slammed for allowing sale of IRA souvenirs|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/sinn-fein-candidate-mary-lou-mcdonald-under-fire-for-selling-ira-trinkets-46733127-237645141.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Central|date=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2011\u2013present)===\nMcDonald contested the Dublin Central constituency again at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], this time picking up 13.1% of first preference votes; she was successful in taking the last seat in the constituency.  Following the election she became Sinn F\u00e9in's Spokesperson for Public Expenditure and Reform <ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\"/> and was a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (Ireland)|Public Accounts Committee]] from then until 2017.<ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\">[http://www.dublincentralsinnfein.ie/mary-lou-mcdonald-td/ Mary Lou McDonald TD]. Sinn F\u00e9in - Dublin Central. Retrieved 12 December 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, McDonald was awarded 'Opposition Politician of the Year' by TV3's ''Tonight with [[Vincent Browne]]'' political talk show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/vincent-browne-announces-his-2012-political-awards-723109-Dec2012/|title=Vincent Browne announces his 2012 Political Awards|first=Amy|last=Croffey|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, McDonald refused to leave the D\u00e1il chamber despite a vote suspending her, after she had questioned [[T\u00e1naiste]] [[Joan Burton]] on if the government would allow payments to be taken from citizen's wages or social welfare payments if they did not comply with the payment of newly introduced water charges. Burton, to MacDonald's mind, would not directly answer her questions and was being deliberately evasive and intractable. Her decision not to leave the chamber was in protest of Burton's refusal to answer her questions. She, along with a number of Sinn F\u00e9in colleagues, remained in the chamber for four and a half hours. In response the [[Ceann Comhairle]] [[Se\u00e1n Barrett (politician)|Se\u00e1n Barrett]] adjourned the D\u00e1il for a number of days. <ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/sinn-feins-mary-lou-mcdonald-refuses-to-leave-the-dail-despite-being-suspended-30741863.html|title=Sinn Fein's Mary Lou McDonald refuses to leave the Dail \u2013 despite being suspended|date=13 November 2014 |work=Irish Independent|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=O'Regan |first=Michael |date=13 November 2014 |title=D\u00e1il adjourned until Tuesday after Mary Lou McDonald sit-in |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/d%C3%A1il-adjourned-until-tuesday-after-mary-lou-mcdonald-sit-in-1.1999444 |work=[[Irish Times]] |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, McDonald initially backed [[Thomas Murphy (Irish criminal)|Thomas \"Slab\" Murphy]], who she described as a \"good republican\" despite him having been convicted on nine charges of tax evasion, following a trial held in the [[Special Criminal Court]] after the last person to testify against Murphy in a court was bludgeoned to death after a 1999 court case in Dublin.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moriarty|first1=Gerry|title=Gerry Adams had little choice but to stand by 'Slab' Murphy|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/gerry-adams-had-little-choice-but-to-stand-by-slab-murphy-1.2473143|accessdate=21 December 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=20 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Connor|first1=Niall|last2=Doyle|first2=Kevin|last3=Cusack|first3=Jim|title=Now Mary Lou backs \u2018good republican\u2019 Slab|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/now-mary-lou-backs-good-republican-slab-34306975.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Independent|date=22 December 2015}}</ref> She later failed to back party leader Gerry Adams' assertion that Thomas Murphy is a \"good republican\" after a [[Spotlight (BBC News)|BBC Spotlight]] investigation accused Murphy of being a \"mass murderer\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=\u00d3 Cionnaith|first1=Fiachra|title=Mary Lou McDonald stays silent on support for Thomas \u2018Slab\u2019 Murphy|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/mary-lou-mcdonald-stays-silent-on-support-for-thomas-slab-murphy-380139.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Examiner|date=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter her re-election to the D\u00e1il in [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]], in which she topped the poll in [[Dublin Central (constituency)|Dublin Central]], she became Sinn F\u00e9in's All-Ireland Spokesperson for Mental Health and Suicide Prevention, which she held until being elected president of Sinn F\u00e9in in 2018.<ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\"/><ref>[http://www.sinnfein.ie/contents/40920 Mental health service failing those at risk of suicide \u2013 McDonald]. Sinn F\u00e9in (official website). Published 21 July 2016. Retrieved 12 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in (2018\u2013present)===\nAt the party conference on 18 November 2017, Gerry Adams was re-elected party leader, but announced that he would ask the Sinn F\u00e9in party leadership to call for a special ardfheis to be held within three months to choose a new president, and that he would not stand for re-election as TD for the [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|Louth]] constituency in the [[2020 Irish general election|next election]].<ref name=\"AdamsRetirement\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/gerry-adams-to-step-down-as-sinn-fein-leader-in-2018-36332662.html|title=Gerry Adams to step down as Sinn F\u00e9in leader in 2018|last=Doyle|first=Kevin|date=18 November 2017|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the close of nominations to succeed Adams on 20 January 2018, McDonald was announced as the President-elect of Sinn F\u00e9in, as she was the sole nominee to enter the race. She was confirmed as president at a special [[ardfheis]] on 10 February 2018 in Dublin.<ref name=\"IrishTimes2018-01-20a\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, McDonald was criticised by some, including [[Fine Gael]] politician and incumbent [[T\u00e1naiste]] [[Simon Coveney]], for walking behind a banner in the [[Saint Patrick's Day in the United States#New York City|New York City St. Patrick's day parade]] which read \"England Get Out of Ireland\".<ref>{{cite news|title=SF leader condemned for marching with 'offensive' sign|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2019/0317/1036976-sinn-fein/|date=17 March 2019|journal=RT\u00c9.ie}}</ref> The banner itself had been a part of the parade since 1948,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/niallodowd/england-get-out-of-ireland-banner-nyc-patricks-day-parade |title=Why \u201cEngland Get Out of Ireland\u201d banner belongs in New York Parade |last=O'Dowd |first=Niall |date=18 March 2019 |website=Irish Central |publisher= |access-date=21 February 2020 |quote=}}</ref> however the appropriateness of its message was questioned in a post-[[Good Friday Agreement]] era. In the immediate aftermath of the incident support for Sinn F\u00e9in in opinion polls dropped from 18% to 13%, with MacDonald apologising for her actions shortly afterwards, but stated she believed the message to be directed at the British state, not the English people.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kinsella |first=Rudi |date=April 2019 |title=Mary Lou McDonald says 'England get out of Ireland' St Patrick's Day banner was not directed at English people |url=https://www.joe.ie/politics/sinn-fein-banner-apology-664039 |work= |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>  \n\nShortly afterwards on 24 May 2019, the [[2019 European Parliament election in Ireland]] and [[2019 Irish local elections]] were held simultaneously. In the European elections, Sinn F\u00e9in lost 2 MEPs and dropped their vote share by 7.8%, while in the local elections the party lost 78 (almost half) of their local councillors and dropped their vote share by 5.7%. The result was considered \"disastrous\" for Sinn F\u00e9in. MacDonald stated \"It was a really bad day out for us. But sometimes that happens in politics, and it\u2019s a test for you. I mean it\u2019s a test for me personally, obviously, as the leader\".<ref name=\"How did they do it?\">{{cite news |last=N\u00ed Aodha |first=Gr\u00e1inne |date=12 February 2020 |title=How did they do it? Sinn F\u00e9in's historic 24% win was built on learnt lessons and a fed-up electorate |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/sinn-fein-comeback-5001379-Feb2020/ |work= |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, at the [[2020 Irish general election]], the party rebounded and attained 24.5% of the first preference votes, placing them ahead of Fine Gael by 3.6% and Fianna F\u00e1il by 2.3%. It was the best general election result in the modern history of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.thejournal.ie/mary-lou-taoiseach-5001514-Feb2020/|title = Mary Lou McDonald: 'I may well be the next Taoiseach|date=10 February 2020|work=The Journal|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=McCormack|first=Jayne|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51448739|title=Who will be the next Irish prime minister?|date=2020-02-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\t\t\nMcDonald touted the party's electoral success as a \"revolution\" and expressed her desire to form a coalition government, declaring that Ireland \"is no longer a two-party system\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/09/sinn-fein-to-try-to-form-ruling-coalition-after-irish-election-success|title=Sinn F\u00e9in to try to form ruling coalition after Irish election success|last=Carroll|first=Rory|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> Sinn F\u00e9in TD [[Matt Carthy]] credited MacDonald's leadership and her ability to clarify Sinn F\u00e9in's policies to the electorate with contributing to the stark turn around between the May elections of 2019 and the general election result of 2020.<ref name=\"How did they do it?\"/> MacDonald's high satisfaction rating as party leader was also cited by others as another contributing factor in Sinn F\u00e9in's result.<ref name=\"How did they do it?\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcDonald's husband, Martin Lanigan works as a gas control superintendent for the emergency dispatch division of [[Ervia#Gas Networks Ireland|Gas Networks Ireland]], a state infrastructure provider, and the couple currently live with their two teenage children in Cabra, North Dublin.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Mary Lou McDonald's husband in line for gas firm payout\n | url =https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/mary-lou-mcdonalds-husband-in-line-for-gas-firm-payout-30221224.html\n | website =www.independent.ie\n | date =26 April 2014 \n | access-date =11 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nMcDonald has [[asthma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/coronavirus-mary-lou-mcdonald-describes-distressing-16-day-wait-for-test-results-995100.html|title=Coronavirus: Mary Lou McDonald describes 'distressing' 16-day wait for test results|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|first=Aoife|last=Moore|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, she announced that she had tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] following a test she took on 28 March.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19>{{Cite news|title=Sinn F\u00e9in leader Mary Lou McDonald tests positive for Covid-19|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19-993909.html|last=Hosford|first=Paul|date=14 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> In a statement she said that she had recovered from the condition but had developed [[pleurisy]] in her right lung.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/> She said that the Public Health Doctor had told her that she was no longer infected or infectious.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/> She expressed her appreciation for medical staff who were struggling with the illness and expressed sympathy for those affected and their families.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mary Lou McDonald}}\n* [http://www.sinnfein.ie/mary-lou-mcdonald Mary Lou McDonald's page on the Sinn F\u00e9in website]\n* {{MEP|28111|Mary Lou McDonald}}\n* [http://www.anphoblacht.com/contents/27424 The voices of women must be heard when it comes to healthcare \u2013 Mary Lou McDonald TD]. ''An Phoblacht''. Published 24 July 2018.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Patricia McKenna]]<br />{{small|[[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br />for [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n       |years  = [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004]]\u2013[[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Joe Higgins]]<br />{{small|[[Socialist Party (Ireland)|Socialist Party]]}}}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Mitchel McLaughlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Chair of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 2005\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Declan Kearney]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pat Doherty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Vice President of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] \n       |years  = 2009\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michelle O'Neill]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before = [[Gerry Adams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Cyprian Brady]]<br />{{small|[[Fianna F\u00e1il]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br />for [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]]\n       |years  = [[2011 Irish general election|2011]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (2004\u20132009)}}\n{{Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n{{Northern Ireland party leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonald, Mary Lou}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Limerick]]\n[[Category:Irish republicans]]\n[[Category:Leaders of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:People from Rathgar]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Sinn F\u00e9in MEPs]]\n[[Category:Sinn F\u00e9in TDs (post-1923)]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women Teachta\u00ed D\u00e1la]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish women politicians]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|President of Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n{{Use British English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name          = Mary Lou McDonald\n| honorific-suffix = [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]]\n| image         = Mary Lou McDonald (official portrait).jpg\n| office        = [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| vicepresident = [[Michelle O'Neill]]\n| term_start    = 10 February 2018\n| term_end      = \n| predecessor   = [[Gerry Adams]]\n| successor     = \n| office1       = [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| president1    = Gerry Adams\n| term_start1   = 22 February 2009\n| term_end1     = 10 February 2018 \n| predecessor1  = [[Pat Doherty]]\n| successor1    = Michelle O'Neill\n| office2       = [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]\n| term_start2   = [[2011 Irish general election|February 2011]]\n| term_end2     = \n| constituency2 = [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]]\n| office3       = [[Member of the European Parliament]]\n| term_start3   = 1 July 2004\n| term_end3     = 20 June 2009\n| constituency3 = [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n| birth_name    = Mary Louise McDonald\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1969|5|1|df=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Churchtown, Dublin]], Ireland\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = [[Irish people|Irish]]\n| party         = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n| spouse        = {{marriage|Martin Lanigan|1996}}\n| children      = 2\n| alma_mater    = {{Ubl|[[Trinity College Dublin]]|[[University of Limerick]]|[[Dublin City University]]}}\n| website       = {{url|dublincentralsinnfein.ie|Official website}}\n|}}\n'''Mary Louise McDonald''' (born 1 May 1969) is an Irish [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] politician who has served as the [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]] since February 2018. She has been a [[Teachta D\u00e1la]] (TD) for the [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]] constituency since the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]]. She previously served as [[Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in#Vice Presidents|Vice President of Sinn F\u00e9in]] from 2009 to 2018 and a [[Member of the European Parliament]] (MEP) for the [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]] constituency from 2004 to 2009.<ref name=oireachtas_db>{{cite web |url=https://www.oireachtas.ie/en/members/member/Mary-Lou-McDonald.D.2011-03-09/|title=Mary Lou McDonald |work=Oireachtas Members Database |accessdate=17 April 2011}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 February 2018, McDonald succeeded longtime party leader [[Gerry Adams]] after a special [[ardfheis]] ([[party conference]]) in [[Dublin]].<ref name=IrishTimes2018-01-20a>{{Cite news|url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/mary-lou-mcdonald-confirmed-as-new-leader-of-sinn-f%C3%A9in-1.3362813|title=Mary Lou McDonald confirmed as new leader of Sinn F\u00e9in|work=The Irish Times|date=20 January 2018|access-date=20 January 2018|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn into a [[middle-class]] family<ref name=\u201cveconomist\u201d >{{cite news|author=|title= Is Sinn Fein now a normal political party?|url= https://www.economist.com/europe/2020/03/07/is-sinn-fein-now-a-normal-political-party|work=[[The Economist]]|date=7 March 2020}}</ref> in [[Dublin]] to builder and surveyor Patrick McDonald and homemaker Joan, her parents separated when she was 9 years old and she stayed with her mother in [[Rathgar]].<ref>{{cite web\n | title =How Shinner babe Mary Lou came to the aid of the party\n | url =https://www.independent.ie/opinion/analysis/how-shinner-babe-mary-lou-came-to-the-aid-of-the-party-26221690.html\n | website =www.independent.ie\n | date =19 June 2004\n | access-date =11 February 2020  }}</ref> She has an elder brother Bernard and younger twin siblings Patrick and Joanne. Her sister Joanne had involvement with the socialist republican party [[\u00c9ir\u00edg\u00ed]] throughout the early 2000s and is a teacher.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Mary Lou McDonald \u2013 private-school educated opponent of Dublin Orange parade\n | url =https://www.newsletter.co.uk/news/mary-lou-mcdonald-private-school-educated-opponent-of-dublin-orange-parade-1-8342923\n | website =www.newsletter.co.uk\n | date =23 January 2018 \n | access-date =10 February 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n | title ='Rise up and Reclaim the Republic' says new group\n | url =https://magill.ie/archive/rise-and-reclaim-republic-says-new-group\n | website =www.magill.ie\n | date =21 June 2006\n | access-date =10 February 2020 }}</ref> Her brother Patrick works as an Intellectual Property lawyer and Bernard as a scientist.\n\nMcDonald was educated at the Catholic all-girls fee paying [[Notre Dame School, Dublin|Notre Dame Des Missions]] in [[Churchtown, Dublin|Churchtown]] where she was involved in debating.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/tds-who-went-to-private-schools-split-over-cuts-3258025.html | work=Irish Independent | title=TDs who went to private schools split over cuts | date=2 December 2012}}</ref> \n\nAfter school, McDonald attended [[Trinity College Dublin]], from which she received a bachelor's degree in [[English Literature]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Grace |first=Aisling |date=February 10, 2018 |title=Trinity alumna Mary Lou McDonald elected leader of Sinn Fein |url=http://trinitynews.ie/2018/02/trinity-alumna-mary-lou-mcdonald-elected-leader-of-sinn-fein/ |work=Trinity News |location=Dublin, Ireland}}</ref> She later studied [[industrial relations]] at [[Dublin City University]],<ref>{{cite news |date=June 20, 2004 |title=Profile: Mary Lou McDonald: Shopaholic Trinity girl is face of new Sinn Fein |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/profile-mary-lou-mcdonald-shopaholic-trinity-girl-is-face-of-new-sinn-fein-fdmjch5mzbs |work=The Times |location=London, England |url-access=subscription |quote=\"...studying industrial relations at Dublin City University...\"}}</ref> and also received a [[Master of Arts]] degree in [[European integration|European Integration Studies]] from the [[University of Limerick]] in 1995.<ref>{{cite news |last=University of Limerick |title=My Favourite Place - Juliette Gash & Mary Lou McDonald |url=https://www.ul.ie/ullinks/our-campus/my-favourite-place-juliette-gash-mary-lou-mcdonald |work=UL Links |location=Limerick, Ireland |access-date=February 11, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191102233609/http://www.ul.ie/ullinks/our-campus/my-favourite-place-juliette-gash-mary-lou-mcdonald |archive-date=2 November 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Her career to date has seen her involved in diverse roles, including consultant for the Irish Productivity Centre, researcher for the [[Institute of International and European Affairs|Institute of European Affairs]], and trainer in the Partnership Unit of the Educational and Training Services Trust.<ref>{{cite news |last=Sinn Fein Press Office |date=March 11, 2003 |title=Campaign begins to return Sinn Fein MEP for Dublin: McDonald selected as Dublin EU candidate |url=http://www.sinnfein.org/releases/03/pr031103b.html |work=Sinn Fein.org |location=Dublin, Ireland}}</ref>\n\nMcDonald became involved with the [[Irish National Congress]], a cross-party republican organisation, and became chairperson in 2000, leading a protest in [[Dublin]] against the involvement of the city's [[Lord Mayor of Dublin|Lord Mayor]] in the unveiling of a plaque at the location where the [[Grand Orange Lodge of Ireland]] held its first meeting in 1798.<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/opinion/columnists/2018/01/01/deagla-n-de-bre-adu-n-mary-lou-mcdonald-s-leadership-could-mark-a-turning-point-for-republicanism-1221623/?ref=sh Deagl\u00e1n de Br\u00e9ad\u00fan: Mary Lou McDonald's leadership could mark a turning point for republicanism], Irish News, 1 January 2018</ref>\n\n==European Parliament and early D\u00e1il attempts== \nMcDonald has been a member of the Sinn F\u00e9in party leadership since 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/meps/en/28111/Mary%20Lou_McDONALD.html|title=MEP profile|accessdate=26 January 2012|publisher=[[European Parliament]]}}</ref> McDonald first ran for office when she unsuccessfully contested the [[Dublin West (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin West]] constituency for Sinn F\u00e9in at the [[2002 Irish general election|2002 general election]], polling 8.02% of first preference votes. \n\nIn September 2003, McDonald attracted criticism when she spoke at a rally in Dublin to commemorate [[Se\u00e1n Russell]], an IRA leader with links to [[Nazi Germany]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.independent.ie/national-news/sfs-nazi-hero-is-stalking-candidate-mary-lou-481013.html|title=SF's Nazi hero is stalking candidate Mary Lou|accessdate=25 May 2008|last=Cusack|first=Jim|date=6 June 2004|publisher=[[Irish Independent]]|quote=SINN FEIN'S Mary Lou McDonald has been accused of \"warped principles\" for participating in a republican commemoration ceremony last year for a Nazi collaborator while standing as a candidate for the European Parliament.}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://observer.guardian.co.uk/comment/story/0,6903,1391492,00.html|title=This dastardly plot|accessdate=25 May 2008|last=McDonald|first=Henry|date=16 January 2005|work=[[The Observer]]|location=London}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2004/03/14/story766283063.asp|title=Profile: Prime time Shinner|accessdate=25 May 2008|work=[[The Sunday Business Post]]|first1=Paul|last1=Colgan|first2=Neil|last2=Callanan|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041019081506/http://archives.tcm.ie/businesspost/2004/03/14/story766283063.asp|archivedate=19 October 2004|quote=She encountered criticism after speaking at a commemoration for IRA volunteer Sean Russell last year.|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nIn 2004, McDonald became Sinn F\u00e9in's first [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]] in the [[Republic of Ireland]] when she was elected at the [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004 European Parliament election]] for the [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin constituency]], receiving over 60,000 first preference votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://electionsireland.org/result.cfm?election=2004E&cons=524|title=EU elections 2004 results \u2013 Dublin|work=ElectionsIreland.org|accessdate=14 April 2009}}</ref> She served as one of two Sinn F\u00e9in MEPs, the other being [[Bairbre de Br\u00fan]] who was representing [[Northern Ireland (European Parliament constituency)|Northern Ireland]]. In 2007, she was shortlisted for the 'MEP of the Year' award by the [[European Parliament]] magazine watching for \"making the most valuable contribution in the field of employment policy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.anphoblacht.com/contents/17426|title=Mary Lou McDonald shortlisted for MEP of the Year Award - An Phoblacht|website=www.anphoblacht.com}}</ref> During her time in office she led the Sinn F\u00e9in campaign against the [[Treaty of Lisbon]], which was rejected in the Republic in 2008. McDonald sat as a member of the European Parliament's Employment and Social Affairs Committee, and as a substitute of the Civil Liberties Committee.\n\nShe was an unsuccessful candidate in the [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]] constituency at the [[2007 Irish general election|2007 general election]].\n\nMcDonald became Sinn F\u00e9in Vice President, replacing [[Pat Doherty]], following the Sinn F\u00e9in [[ardfheis]] of 22 February 2009.\n\nFor the [[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009 European Parliament election]], the number of seats for Dublin in the European Parliament was reduced from four to three. McDonald was in a tight race for the last seat against Fianna F\u00e1il's [[Eoin Ryan Jnr|Eoin Ryan]] and the [[Socialist Party (Ireland)|Socialist Party]] leader [[Joe Higgins]]. McDonald lost her seat to Higgins, being eliminated at the fifth count. Her first preference vote had declined to nearly 48,000.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/elections/stories/2009/0608/euroelection.html |title=Ryan loses out to Higgins in Dublin |work=[[RT\u00c9 News]] |date=8 June 2008 |accessdate=8 June 2008 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090610192742/http://www.rte.ie/news/elections/stories/2009/0608/euroelection.html |archivedate=10 June 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2009, McDonald faced criticism after it emerged her campaign office was selling IRA souvenirs and memorabilia.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Sheahan|first1=Fionnan|title=IRA souvenirs sell well in McDonald HQ|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/ira-souvenirs-sell-well-in-mcdonald-hq-26540510.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Independent|date=2 June 2009}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Sinn Fein VP Mary Lou Mcdonald slammed for allowing sale of IRA souvenirs|url=http://www.irishcentral.com/news/sinn-fein-candidate-mary-lou-mcdonald-under-fire-for-selling-ira-trinkets-46733127-237645141.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Central|date=2 June 2009}}</ref>\n\n===D\u00e1il \u00c9ireann (2011\u2013present)===\nShe contested the Dublin Central constituency again at the [[2011 Irish general election|2011 general election]], this time picking up 13.1% of first preference votes; she was successful in taking the last seat in the constituency.  Following the election she became Sinn F\u00e9in's Spokesperson for Public Expenditure and Reform <ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\"/> and was a member of the [[Public Accounts Committee (Ireland)|Public Accounts Committee]] from then until 2017.<ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\">[http://www.dublincentralsinnfein.ie/mary-lou-mcdonald-td/ Mary Lou McDonald TD]. Sinn F\u00e9in - Dublin Central. Retrieved 12 December 2018.</ref>\n\nIn 2012, McDonald was awarded 'Opposition Politician of the Year' by TV3's ''Tonight with [[Vincent Browne]]'' political talk show.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejournal.ie/vincent-browne-announces-his-2012-political-awards-723109-Dec2012/|title=Vincent Browne announces his 2012 Political Awards|first=Amy|last=Croffey|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nIn November 2014, McDonald refused to leave the D\u00e1il chamber despite a vote suspending her, after she had questioned [[T\u00e1naiste]] [[Joan Burton]] on if the government would allow payments to be taken from citizen's wages or social welfare payments if they did not comply with the payment of newly introduced water charges. Burton, to MacDonald's mind, would not directly answer her questions and was being deliberately evasive and intractable. Her decision not to leave the chamber was in protest of Burton's refusal to answer her questions. She, along with a number of Sinn F\u00e9in colleagues, remained in the chamber for four and a half hours. In response the [[Ceann Comhairle]] [[Se\u00e1n Barrett (politician)|Se\u00e1n Barrett]] adjourned the D\u00e1il for a number of days. <ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/sinn-feins-mary-lou-mcdonald-refuses-to-leave-the-dail-despite-being-suspended-30741863.html|title=Sinn Fein's Mary Lou McDonald refuses to leave the Dail \u2013 despite being suspended|date=13 November 2014 |work=Irish Independent|accessdate=13 November 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=O'Regan |first=Michael |date=13 November 2014 |title=D\u00e1il adjourned until Tuesday after Mary Lou McDonald sit-in |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/politics/d%C3%A1il-adjourned-until-tuesday-after-mary-lou-mcdonald-sit-in-1.1999444 |work=[[Irish Times]] |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, McDonald initially backed [[Thomas Murphy (Irish criminal)|Thomas \"Slab\" Murphy]], who she described as a \"good republican\" despite him having been convicted on nine charges of tax evasion, following a trial held in the [[Special Criminal Court]] after the last person to testify against Murphy in a court was bludgeoned to death after a 1999 court case in Dublin.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Moriarty|first1=Gerry|title=Gerry Adams had little choice but to stand by 'Slab' Murphy|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/news/ireland/irish-news/gerry-adams-had-little-choice-but-to-stand-by-slab-murphy-1.2473143|accessdate=21 December 2015|publisher=The Irish Times|date=20 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=O'Connor|first1=Niall|last2=Doyle|first2=Kevin|last3=Cusack|first3=Jim|title=Now Mary Lou backs \u2018good republican\u2019 Slab|url=http://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/now-mary-lou-backs-good-republican-slab-34306975.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Independent|date=22 December 2015}}</ref> She later failed to back party leader Gerry Adams' assertion that Thomas Murphy is a \"good republican\" after a [[Spotlight (BBC News)|BBC Spotlight]] investigation accused Murphy of being a \"mass murderer\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=\u00d3 Cionnaith|first1=Fiachra|title=Mary Lou McDonald stays silent on support for Thomas \u2018Slab\u2019 Murphy|url=http://www.irishexaminer.com/ireland/mary-lou-mcdonald-stays-silent-on-support-for-thomas-slab-murphy-380139.html|accessdate=29 May 2016|publisher=Irish Examiner|date=5 February 2016}}</ref>\n\nAfter her re-election to the D\u00e1il in [[2016 Irish general election|2016 general election]], in which she topped the poll in [[Dublin Central (constituency)|Dublin Central]], she became Sinn F\u00e9in's All-Ireland Spokesperson for Mental Health and Suicide Prevention, which she held until being elected president of Sinn F\u00e9in in 2018.<ref name=\"Mary Lou McDonald TD\"/><ref>[http://www.sinnfein.ie/contents/40920 Mental health service failing those at risk of suicide \u2013 McDonald]. Sinn F\u00e9in (official website). Published 21 July 2016. Retrieved 12 December 2018.</ref>\n\n===Leader of Sinn F\u00e9in (2018\u2013present)===\nAt the party conference on 18 November 2017, Gerry Adams was re-elected party leader, but announced that he would ask the Sinn F\u00e9in party leadership to call for a special ardfheis to be held within three months to choose a new president, and that he would not stand for re-election as TD for the [[Louth (D\u00e1il constituency)|Louth]] constituency in the [[2020 Irish general election|next election]].<ref name=\"AdamsRetirement\">{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.ie/irish-news/politics/gerry-adams-to-step-down-as-sinn-fein-leader-in-2018-36332662.html|title=Gerry Adams to step down as Sinn F\u00e9in leader in 2018|last=Doyle|first=Kevin|date=18 November 2017|work=[[Irish Independent]]|accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref>\n\nAt the close of nominations to succeed Adams on 20 January 2018, McDonald was announced as the President-elect of Sinn F\u00e9in, as she was the sole nominee to enter the race. She was confirmed as president at a special [[ardfheis]] on 10 February 2018 in Dublin.<ref name=\"IrishTimes2018-01-20a\"/>\n\nIn March 2019, McDonald was criticised by some, including [[Fine Gael]] politician and incumbent [[T\u00e1naiste]] [[Simon Coveney]], for walking behind a banner in the [[Saint Patrick's Day in the United States#New York City|New York City St. Patrick's day parade]] which read \"England Get Out of Ireland\".<ref>{{cite news|title=SF leader condemned for marching with 'offensive' sign|url=https://www.rte.ie/news/politics/2019/0317/1036976-sinn-fein/|date=17 March 2019|journal=RT\u00c9.ie}}</ref> The banner itself had been a part of the parade since 1948,<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.irishcentral.com/opinion/niallodowd/england-get-out-of-ireland-banner-nyc-patricks-day-parade |title=Why \u201cEngland Get Out of Ireland\u201d banner belongs in New York Parade |last=O'Dowd |first=Niall |date=18 March 2019 |website=Irish Central |publisher= |access-date=21 February 2020 |quote=}}</ref> however the appropriateness of its message was questioned in a post-[[Good Friday Agreement]] era. In the immediate aftermath of the incident support for Sinn F\u00e9in in opinion polls dropped from 18% to 13%, with MacDonald apologising for her actions shortly afterwards, but stated she believed the message to be directed at the British state, not the English people.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kinsella |first=Rudi |date=April 2019 |title=Mary Lou McDonald says 'England get out of Ireland' St Patrick's Day banner was not directed at English people |url=https://www.joe.ie/politics/sinn-fein-banner-apology-664039 |work= |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>  \n\nShortly afterwards on 24 May 2019, the [[2019 European Parliament election in Ireland]] and [[2019 Irish local elections]] were held simultaneously. In the European elections, Sinn F\u00e9in lost 2 MEPs and dropped their vote share by 7.8%, while in the local elections the party lost 78 (almost half) of their local councillors and dropped their vote share by 5.7%. The result was considered \"disastrous\" for Sinn F\u00e9in. MacDonald stated \"It was a really bad day out for us. But sometimes that happens in politics, and it\u2019s a test for you. I mean it\u2019s a test for me personally, obviously, as the leader\".<ref name=\"How did they do it?\">{{cite news |last=N\u00ed Aodha |first=Gr\u00e1inne |date=12 February 2020 |title=How did they do it? Sinn F\u00e9in's historic 24% win was built on learnt lessons and a fed-up electorate |url=https://www.thejournal.ie/sinn-fein-comeback-5001379-Feb2020/ |work= |location= |access-date=21 February 2020}}</ref>\n\nHowever, at the [[2020 Irish general election]], the party rebounded and attained 24.5% of the first preference votes, placing them ahead of Fine Gael by 3.6% and Fianna F\u00e1il by 2.3%. It was the best general election result in the modern history of Sinn F\u00e9in.<ref>{{citeweb|url= https://www.thejournal.ie/mary-lou-taoiseach-5001514-Feb2020/|title = Mary Lou McDonald: 'I may well be the next Taoiseach|date=10 February 2020|work=The Journal|accessdate=11 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|last=McCormack|first=Jayne|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-northern-ireland-51448739|title=Who will be the next Irish prime minister?|date=2020-02-11|work=BBC News|access-date=2020-02-11|language=en-GB}}</ref>\t\t\nMcDonald touted the party's electoral success as a \"revolution\" and expressed her desire to form a coalition government, declaring that Ireland \"is no longer a two-party system\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2020/feb/09/sinn-fein-to-try-to-form-ruling-coalition-after-irish-election-success|title=Sinn F\u00e9in to try to form ruling coalition after Irish election success|last=Carroll|first=Rory|publisher=[[The Guardian]]|date=9 February 2020|accessdate=9 February 2020}}</ref> Sinn F\u00e9in TD [[Matt Carthy]] credited MacDonald's leadership and her ability to clarify Sinn F\u00e9in's policies to the electorate with contributing to the stark turn around between the May elections of 2019 and the general election result of 2020.<ref name=\"How did they do it?\"/> MacDonald's high satisfaction rating as party leader was also cited by others as another contributing factor in Sinn F\u00e9in's result.<ref name=\"How did they do it?\"/>\n\n==Personal life==\nMcDonald's husband, Martin Lanigan works as a gas control superintendent for the emergency dispatch division of [[Ervia#Gas Networks Ireland|Gas Networks Ireland]], a state infrastructure provider, and the couple currently live with their two teenage children in Cabra, North Dublin.<ref>{{cite web\n | title =Mary Lou McDonald's husband in line for gas firm payout\n | url =https://www.independent.ie/business/irish/mary-lou-mcdonalds-husband-in-line-for-gas-firm-payout-30221224.html\n | website =www.independent.ie\n | date =26 April 2014 \n | access-date =11 February 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Health===\nMcDonald has [[asthma]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/coronavirus-mary-lou-mcdonald-describes-distressing-16-day-wait-for-test-results-995100.html|title=Coronavirus: Mary Lou McDonald describes 'distressing' 16-day wait for test results|work=[[Irish Examiner]]|first=Aoife|last=Moore|date=20 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2020, she announced that she had tested positive for [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]] following a test she took on 28 March.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19>{{Cite news|title=Sinn F\u00e9in leader Mary Lou McDonald tests positive for Covid-19|url=https://www.irishexaminer.com/breakingnews/ireland/sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19-993909.html|last=Hosford|first=Paul|date=14 April 2020|access-date=14 April 2020|newspaper=[[Irish Examiner]]}}</ref> In a statement she said that she had recovered from the condition but had developed [[pleurisy]] in her right lung.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/> She said that the Public Health Doctor had told her that she was no longer infected or infectious.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/> She expressed her appreciation for medical staff who were struggling with the illness and expressed sympathy for those affected and their families.<ref name=ie-sinn-fein-leader-mary-lou-mcdonald-tests-positive-for-covid-19/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mary Lou McDonald}}\n* [http://www.sinnfein.ie/mary-lou-mcdonald Mary Lou McDonald's page on the Sinn F\u00e9in website]\n* {{MEP|28111|Mary Lou McDonald}}\n* [http://www.anphoblacht.com/contents/27424 The voices of women must be heard when it comes to healthcare \u2013 Mary Lou McDonald TD]. ''An Phoblacht''. Published 24 July 2018.\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|eu}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Patricia McKenna]]<br />{{small|[[Green Party (Ireland)|Green Party]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Member of the European Parliament]]<br />for [[Dublin (European Parliament constituency)|Dublin]]\n       |years  = [[2004 European Parliament election in Ireland|2004]]\u2013[[2009 European Parliament election in Ireland|2009]]}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Joe Higgins]]<br />{{small|[[Socialist Party (Ireland)|Socialist Party]]}}}}\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Mitchel McLaughlin]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Chair of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 2005\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Declan Kearney]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before = [[Pat Doherty]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = Vice President of [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] \n       |years  = 2009\u20132018}}\n{{s-aft|after  = [[Michelle O'Neill]]}}\n\n{{s-bef|before = [[Gerry Adams]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[President of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n       |years  = 2018\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-par|ie/oi}}\n{{s-bef|before = [[Cyprian Brady]]<br />{{small|[[Fianna F\u00e1il]]}}}}\n{{s-ttl|title  = [[Sinn F\u00e9in]] [[Teachta D\u00e1la]]<br />for [[Dublin Central (D\u00e1il constituency)|Dublin Central]]\n       |years  = [[2011 Irish general election|2011]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n{{Current TDs}}\n{{Members of the European Parliament for Ireland (2004\u20132009)}}\n{{Sinn F\u00e9in}}\n{{Northern Ireland party leaders}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonald, Mary Lou}}\n[[Category:1969 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Dublin City University]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Trinity College Dublin]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Limerick]]\n[[Category:Irish republicans]]\n[[Category:Leaders of Sinn F\u00e9in]]\n[[Category:MEPs for the Republic of Ireland 2004\u20132009]]\n[[Category:Members of the 31st D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 32nd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:Members of the 33rd D\u00e1il]]\n[[Category:People from Rathgar]]\n[[Category:Politicians from County Dublin]]\n[[Category:Sinn F\u00e9in MEPs]]\n[[Category:Sinn F\u00e9in TDs (post-1923)]]\n[[Category:Women MEPs for the Republic of Ireland]]\n[[Category:Women Teachta\u00ed D\u00e1la]]\n[[Category:21st-century Irish women politicians]]\n", "name_user": "Bygmester", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Lou_McDonald"}
{"title_page": "Bridges of Belgrade", "text_new": "[[File:Zemun 1688.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1688 map of [[Zemun]] and Belgrade, showing a pontoon bridge]]\n[[File:Belgrade from LH1407.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Aerial view of the [[Sava]] river, showing five out of six bridges in the urban section of the city]]\n\n[[Belgrade]], the capital of [[Serbia]], is located on two major rivers, the [[Danube]] and the [[Sava]] which are spanned by 11 bridges in total.\n\n== Introduction ==\n\nThe Greek historian [[Zosimus]] mentions the bridge in Belgrade (at that time, [[Singidunum]]) already in the 5th century, which is the oldest historical mention of any bridges in the city. Other historical records observe other bridges, from the [[Byzantine]] and later periods, like in 1521, 1595, 1688<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Zemun_1688.jpg Map of Zemun 1688]</ref> or 1717,<ref>{{cite news | author = Miroslav Stefanovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0417\u0435\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0432 - \u0412\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u043e \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0435 | trans-title = Zemun chronicles - Townspeople like Lido and kafanas | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1170 | page = 28 | language = Serbian | date = 1 March 2020}}</ref> but they were all temporary, [[pontoon bridges]], constructed solely for the purpose of conquering the city during the numerous battles and sieges of Belgrade through history.\n\nIn 1521, Karaca Pasha, military commander of the Ottoman sultan [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] built a pontoon bridge across the Sava, while in 1595 Ottomans built a pontoon over the Danube, near the village of [[Vi\u0161njica, Serbia|Vi\u0161njica]]. The bridge in 1717 was built on the orders of the Austrian commander [[Prince Eugene of Savoy]].<ref name=Politika>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Beogradski mostovi \u2013 od oblica do pilona | trans-title = Bridges of Belgrade - from logs to pylons | newspaper = [[Politika]] |language = Serbian | date = 13 August 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/187584/%D0%91%D0%B5%D0%BE%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B8-%D0%BE%D0%B4-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0-%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D0%BF%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0 }}</ref>\n\nThe chronicles mention no less than 10 pontoon bridges on the location of the modern [[Branko's Bridge]] - 5 Austrian and 5 Ottoman.<ref name=novosti>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:444377-Beogradske-price-Most-viteskog-kralja-Aleksandra | author = Zoran Nikoli\u0107 | title = Beogradske pri\u010de: Most vite\u0161kog kralja Aleksandra | trans-title = Belgrade stories: Bridge of the knightly king Alexander | date = 17 July 2013 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n\nThey can be categorized in several ways:\n\na) 10 across the Sava, 2 across the Danube;<br>b) 8 road bridges, 3 railway and 1 combined;<br>c) 7 urban, 4 suburban and 1 combined;\n\n== Bridges by water body ==\n=== Sava ===\n==== 1884 - Old Railroad Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, Old railway bridge, 10.04.2011.jpg|right|thumb|250px]]\n\n'''[[Old Railroad Bridge]]''' (''{{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442}}'') was built within the project of constructing the first railway in Serbia. It was built on a French concession which included the construction of the Belgrade\u2013[[Ni\u0161]] railway, the railway bridge over the Sava and a railway which will connect Belgrade to [[Zemun]], at the time, the border town of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref name=stari>{{Citation | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Gvozdeni konji u Ciganskoj bari | trans-title = Iron horses in the Gypsy pond | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1039 | pages = 28\u201329 | language = Serbian | date = 27 August 2017 }}</ref> It was demolished in both [[World Wars]] and the present construction was placed after the [[World War II]] ended.<ref name=Politika/> As the only connection between Serbia and the Austria-Hungary, who already positioned its army near the bridge, it was demolished by the Serbian army on 29 July 1914. It was reconstructed in 1919.<ref name=glas>{{cite web | url = http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/glas-javnosti-07-08-2007/beogradski-mostovi | author = G.J. | title = Beogradski vekovnik - Beogradski mostovi | trans-title = Belgrade century book - Belgrade bridges | date = 7 August 2007 | publisher = [[Glas Javnosti]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/300935/Srusio-most-pred-naletom-Austrougara-danas-u-zaboravu | author = Nikola Beli\u0107 | title = Sru\u0161io most pred naletom Austrougara \u2013 danas u zaboravu | trans-title = (He) demolished the bridge in front of the advancing Austro-Hungarians - today forgotten | date = 1 August 2014 | publisher = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> When Germany attacked Yugoslavia on 6 April 1941, the High Command decided to demolish all three existing bridges in Belgrade, including the railway bridge.<ref name=Politika/> It was reconstructed again in 1945, funded by the [[war reparations]].<ref name=glas/> Though projected as a temporary link in 1945, the bridge was reconstructed in 1986, when the tracks were replaced. Minor repairs on the bridge have been done in 1995 and 1996.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/dotrajali-pragovi-bice-zamenjeni/2z527ys | author = Lana Gedo\u0161evi\u0107 | title = Dotrajali pragovi bi\u0107e zamenjeni | trans-title = Worn out ties will be replaced | date = 9 February 2009 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was the only bridge in Belgrade until 1934. Also, it was the only railway bridge until 1935 and the only one across the Sava until 1979 when the New Railroad Bridge was open.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 1942 - Old Sava Bridge ====\n[[File:Belgrade Sava bridge.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Old Sava Bridge]]''' (''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was built during the German occupation. The construction of the bridge was installed over the [[Tisza|Tisa]] river near [[\u017dabalj]], but the demolition of the [[King Alexander Bridge]], led to the installation of the construction over the eight pillars on the [[Sava]] river. It was cut in pieces and transferred to Belgrade.<ref name=\"padamost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/380827/Stari-savski-most-pada-u-vodu | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Stari savski most pada u vodu | trans-title = Old Sava Bridge falls into the water | date = 18 May 2017 | publisher = Politika | page = 1 & 16 | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was the only big European bridge that was not demolished during the German withdrawals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/265473/Beograd/Tramvajski-most-most-ucitelja-Miladina-Zarica | author = Marija Brako\u010devi\u0107 | title = Tramvajski most - most u\u010ditelja Miladina Zari\u0107a | trans-title = Tram bridge - bridge of teacher Miladin Zari\u0107 | date = 31 July 2013 | publisher = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge had a wooden driveway until 1964, when the planners suggested the reconstruction of the bridge to the mayor [[Branko Pe\u0161i\u0107]]. After a five-year reconstruction a new concrete panel was placed in 1969. After opting against the construction of [[rapid transit|metro]], despite developing the project for over a decade, in 1984 the [[tramway track]]s were laid over the bridge and the concrete panel was replaced with the steel one.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Krpljenje rupa na Starom savskom mostu | trans-title = Fixing the holes on the Old Sava Bridge | newspaper = Politika | pages = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2013 }}</ref> In March 2016, mayor of Belgrade [[Sini\u0161a Mali]] announced the massive reconstruction of the bridge, slated to begin in the late 2017. He named the [[Tehran]]'s [[Tabiat Bridge]] as an inspiration.<ref name=\"padamost\"/><ref name=\"blic\">{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/rekonstrukcija-savskog-mosta-2017-godine/jh13d4h | author = Dijana Radisavljevi\u0107 | title = Rekonstrukcija Savskog mosta 2017 godine | trans-title = Reconstruction of the Sava Bridge in 2017 | date = 17 March 2016 | publisher =[[Blic]] | language = Serbian}}</ref> However, in May 2017, after the city publicized the project papers, it was obvious that all the time they wanted to demolish the bridge completely and build a new one but the old bridge will not be demolished. Instead it will be moved to another location which is still not chosen, as a pedestrian bridge.<ref name=\"padamost\"/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1953 - Ostru\u017enica Railroad Bridge ====\n\n'''[[Ostru\u017enica Railroad Bridge]]''' (''\u041e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was built in order to move the transport of toxic and explosive materials from downtown Belgrade. Built in 1953, it was damaged by [[NATO bombing of Serbia|NATO during the bombing of Serbia]] in 1999. The {{convert|658|m|abbr=on}} long bridge was repaired and open on 15 September 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.srbija.gov.rs/vesti/vest.php?id=55619 | title = Ko\u0161tunica otvorio \u017eelezni\u010dki most kod Ostru\u017enice | trans-title = Ko\u0161tunica opened the railway bridge at Ostru\u017enica | date = 15 September 2006 | publisher = Government of the Republic of Serbia | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) suburban;\n\n==== 1956 - Branko's Bridge ====\n[[File:Branko's bridge (Brankov most), Belgrade.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Branko's Bridge]]''' (''\u0411\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') replaced in 1956 the former chain-stayed [[King Alexander Bridge]], which was operational from 1934 to 1941. The bridge actually uses lower parts of the former bridge's pylons as outer constraints for its two secondary spans.<ref name=\"regenti\">{{Citation | author = Marko Lukovi\u0107 | title = \"Gazelini regenti\" preuzimaju du\u017enost | trans-title = \"Gazela's regents\" take over | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 8 July 2010 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/141657/Beograd/Gazelini-regenti-preuzimaju-duznost }}</ref> After the World War II, in the 1950s, the general idea was that trolleybuses should take over the major role in the public transportation. Line to Zemun was opened in 1956, and in time three lines over the bridge were formed: Line 14 \u2013 [[Zeleni Venac]]-[[Gornji Grad (Zemun)]]  (which was considered a successor line to the pre-war tram line), Line 15 \u2013 Zeleni Venac-[[Novi Grad (Zemun)]] and Line 16 \u2013 Zeleni Venac-Pohorska, [[New Belgrade]]. The lines were closed in 1973.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \"Trole\" vozile Novobeogra\u0111ane i Zemunce | trans-title = Trolleybuses transported inhabitants of New Belgrade and Zemun | newspaper = Politika | pages = 31 | language = Serbian | date = 2 May 2017 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/379527/Trole-vozile-Novobeogradane-i-Zemunce}}</ref> The bridge gained an infamous reputation as the [[suicide bridge]]. Some 40 people try to commit suicide jumping of the Branko's Bridge every year.<ref name=\"regenti\"/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1970 - Gazela Bridge ====\n[[File:Gazela.JPG|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Gazela Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043b\u0430'') is the most important, central bridge in the city, the main connection between downtown Belgrade and New Belgrade, carrying the transit traffic on [[E70 in Serbia|E70]] and [[E75 in Serbia|E75]] highways. Daily traffic exceeds 165,000 vehicles.<ref name=prst>{{Citation | author = Marko Laki\u0107, Nikola Mikovi\u0107| title = Preko \"Gazele\" na prstima | trans-title = Tiptoeing over \"Gazela\" | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 30 March 2009 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/81194/Ekonomija/Preko-Gazele-na-prstima }}</ref> It was built from 1966 to 1970. Immediately after the opening in 1970, a defect was noticed. Due to the miscalculations, the metallic construction began to depress in the middle of the bridge. By the 2010 reconstruction, it became visible both by watching the bridge from the side or crossing it. In order to alleviate the problem, on the metallic sections of the bridge, the concrete [[shoulder (road)|shoulders]] were replaced with the lighter, metallic ones. After a long debate, which lasted for years, on the condition of the bridge, a major reconstruction ensued in 2010-11.<ref name=prst/> After the reconstruction, city officials stated the bridge would be able to handle 200,000 vehicles daily for the next 40 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:392570-Gazela-spremna-i-za-200000-vozila | title = Gazela spremna i za 200,000 vozila | trans-title = Gazela ready for 200,000 vehicles | publisher = [[Ve\u010dernje novosti]] | date = 12 August 2012 }}</ref> However, the bridge is still overloaded, despite the significant relief when the new [[Ada Bridge]] was opened for traffic on 1 January 2012. Additional relief is expected when the [[Belgrade bypass]] is completed.\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1979 - New Railroad Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, New railway bridge, 20.04.2011.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[New Railroad Bridge]]''' (''\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0455\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') is a [[cable-stayed bridge]], the second railway bridge across the Sava in the urban section of Belgrade. The construction of the bridge began in 1975 and it was completed and opened for traffic in 1979. The bridge was built as a part of the projected [[Belgrade railway junction]] and it directly connects New Belgrade with the, still unfinished, [[Belgrade Centre railway station]] in the neighborhood of [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]].<ref name=Politika/> Designed by [[Nikola Hajdin]], it was the first bridge in Europe to use cable-stayed girder system.\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 1998 - Ostru\u017enica Bridge ====\n\n'''[[Ostru\u017enica Bridge]]''' (''\u041e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') is a three-lane semi-highway [[girder bridge]] carrying the Belgrade bypass. It was constructed from 1990 to 1998. The bridge was [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombed by NATO]] during the [[Kosovo War]] in 1999 and fully reconstructed by 2004. The additional, parallel three-lane span is under construction since January 2016. The original deadline was 26 months, or April 2018. It was then moved to March 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://mondo.rs/a867229/Info/Ekonomija/Obilaznica-oko-Beograda-Ostruznica-most-Vucic.html | title = Premijer bacio \"prvu lopatu\" mosta kod Ostru\u017enice}}</ref> In May 2019 the end of construction was set to October 2019.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0430 \u043e\u0434 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430 | trans-title = Driving across the Ostru\u017enica twin bridge from late October | newspaper = [[Politika]] | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n==== 2011 - Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge ====\n[[File:Most Obrenovac - Surcin 1.jpg|thumb|150px|right]]\n\n'''[[Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446-\u0421\u0443\u0440\u0447\u0438\u043d'') was built from 1994 to 2011. It was originally projected as the carrier for the [[district heating]] pipeline, hence the closeness to the power plant.),<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Most Obrenovac-Sur\u010din povezao dva dela Srbije | trans-title = Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge connected two parts of Serbia | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 1 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"beobild\">{{cite web | url= http://beobuild.rs/linking-obrenovac-and-surcin-p2298.html | title= Linking Obrenovac and Sur\u010din | date = 2 October 2011 | publisher = Beobuild | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was supposed to connect the [[TPP Nikola Tesla]] plant with [[New Belgrade]]. In 1997.<ref name=\"Politika1\">{{Citation | author = Dimitrije Bukvi\u0107 | title = Most u beogradskoj Posavini bi\u0107e zavr\u0161en za 45 dana | trans-title = Bridge in Belgrade's Sava valley will be finished in 45 days | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 14 October 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/194445/Beograd/Most-u-beogradskoj-Posavini-bice-zavrsen-za-45-dana}}</ref> the project was changed to include the possibility of transporting tanks and other military technics and then the idea was expanded to include the regular traffic. Due to the financial constraints, the works were halted in 1998 and the NATO bombing in 1999 pushed this project out of any future plans as so much other infrastructure had to be repaired. In the next years nothing new was done as works included only the maintenance of the already placed steel construction and the reparation of one of the pillars which was damaged by the [[barge]].The idea resurfaced in 2006 when the discussions were held on the profitability of the heating pipeline and eventually the pipeline idea was dropped.<ref name=\"beobild\"/> Tentative works on further building began in April 2010<ref name=\"Politika1\"/> and the full blown construction ensued in 2011. The bridge was opened on 1 December 2011.<ref name=\"danas\">{{cite web|url= http://www.danas.rs/danasrs/srbija/beograd/pusten_u_saobracaj_most_obrenovacsurcin.39.html?news_id=229344 |author = B.I. | title = Pu\u0161ten u saobra\u0107aj most Obrenovac-Sur\u010din | trans-title = Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge open for traffic | date = 1 December 2016 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n==== 2012 - Ada Bridge ====\n[[File:Ada Bridge.JPG|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Ada Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438'') is a cable-stayed bridge which crosses the tip of [[ada ciganiganlija]] island, connecting the municipalities of [[\u010cukarica]] and New Belgrade. The bridge [[Tower#Transportation support|pylon]] is located on the tip of the island, which has been reinforced with large amounts of concrete and has been slightly enlarged to provide stronger foundations. Construction began in 2008, and the bridge was opened on 1 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.b92.net/automobili/aktuelno.php?nav_id=530579&fs=1 | trans-title = The bridge on Ada Ciganlija (was) connected | title = Spojen most na Adi Ciganliji | publisher = B92.net | date = 9 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/uz-vatromet-otvoren-most-na-adi/584ne7y | author = M.J. | title = Uz vatromet otvoren Most na Adi | trans-title = Ada Bridge open with fireworks | date = 1 January 2012 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> Component parts of the deck were manufactured in China and delivered in transportable units on a sea and river-route via [[Rotterdam]] through the [[Rhine\u2013Main\u2013Danube Canal]] to the pre-assembly yard next to the construction site at [[Mala Ciganlija]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gradnja.rs/most-na-adi-u-magazinu-bridge/ | author = Igor Coni\u0107 | title = Most na Adi u magazinu Bridge | trans-title = Ada Bridge in the Bridge magazine | date = 8 February 2011 | publisher = Gradnja.rs | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge is designed to significantly reduce traffic passing through the city center and the Gazela Bridge. It is planned to be part of the future {{ill|Belgrade Inner City Semi-Ring Road|sr|\u0423\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0448\u045a\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d}}.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://beobuild.rs/inner-ring-road--detailed-plan-concept-p2248.html | title = Inner Ring Road - Detailed plan concept | date = 7 October 2010 | publisher = Beobuild | language = Serbian }}</ref> It has three road lanes and a tram (light rail) track in each direction.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rtrs.tv/vijesti/vijest.php?id=44324 | author = [[Tanjug]] | title = Beograd - novi most spojio obale | trans-title = Belgrade - new bridge connected the banks | date = 9 August 2011 | publisher = [[RTRS]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was featured in the fifth episode, season nine of the [[Discovery Channel]] documentary television series ''[[Build It Bigger]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://science.discovery.com/tv/build-bigger/projects/serbia/sava-river-bridge.html | title = Sava River Bridge: Extreme Engineering: Science Channel | publisher = Science.discovery.com | date = 30 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 2019 - Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge (A2 motorway) ====\n\n'''[[Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge (A2 motorway)|Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge]]''' on the [[A2 motorway (Serbia)|A2 motorway]], was in construction since 2017. Preparatory works began on 12 February and construction started on 23 May. The bridge crosses not only the Sava, but also its tributary [[Kolubara]]. This section of the A2 motorway and the access roads to the bridge were in construction since 1 March 2017. The construction company was [[China Communications Construction]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/novi-most-preko-save-priprema-se-teren-za-gradiliste-u-obrenovcu/mv9zeld | author = A.R. | title = Novi most preko Save: Priprema se teren za gradili\u0161te u Obrenovcu | trans-title = New bridge over the Sava: the ground is being prepared for the construction | date = 12 February 2017 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Novi most preko Save kod Obrenovca po planu | trans-title = New bridge over the Sava at Obrenovac goes by the plan | newspaper = Politika | pages = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 11 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/drustvo/2744427/pocela-gradnja-novog-mosta-preko-kolubare-i-save.html | author = [[Tanjug]] | title = Po\u010dela gradnja novog mosta preko Kolubare i Save | trans-title = The construction of the new bridge across the Sava and Kolubara began | date = 23 May 2017 | publisher = Radio Television Serbia | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was ceremonially opened for traffic, with the adjoining Obrenovac-Sur\u010din section of the motorway, on 17 December 2019.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0410\u0443\u0442\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0434 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0443\u0442\u043e-\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0443 \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446-\u0421\u0443\u0440\u0447\u0438\u043d | trans-title = Automobiles on the Obrenovac-Sur\u010din motorway from today | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n=== Danube ===\n==== 1946 - Pan\u010devo Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, Pancevo bridge, 07.08.2011, 2.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Pan\u010devo Bridge]]''' (''\u041f\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') replaced in 1946 the former Bridge of King Peter II, which was built in 1935 and completely destroyed in 1944. It is a combined road/railway bridge. Rebuilding began in 1945, upstream from the remnants of the destroyed supporting piers. Plans were drawn up by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] engineers of the [[Red Army]]'s technical troops. Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]]'s orders were that they should build a provisory crossing, but Yugoslav prime minister [[Josip Broz Tito]] convinced him that a proper bridge should be built. On 7 November 1946, the first train passed over the new bridge and regular road traffic started three weeks later, on 29 November. Originally, it was named the Bridge of the Red Army (''Most Crvene Armije'').<ref>{{Citation | author = Radovan Kova\u010devi\u0107 | title = Pan\u010deva\u010dki most 1946. obnovili Rusi | trans-title = Pan\u010devo Bridge was rebuilt by the Russians in 1946 | newspaper = Politika | pages = 11 | language = Serbian | date = 12 April 2008 }}</ref> It was damaged in the explosion of the Russian tanker ships convoy in 1963.<ref>{{Citation | title = Posle eksplozije kod Pan\u010deva\u010dkog mosta na Dunavu | trans-title = After explosion near the Pan\u010devo Bridge on the Danube | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 24 March 1963 }}</ref> Not counting the [[\u0110erdap]] dams on the [[Romania]]n border, Pan\u010devo Bridge was the only bridge over the Danube in Serbia that was not destroyed by NATO forces during the bombing of Serbia in 1999.<ref name=repar>{{Citation | title = Dunav premo\u0161\u0107en ratnim reparacijama | trans-title = Danube crossed thanks to the war reparations | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> Until the opening of the Pupin Bridge in 2015, it was the only Belgrade's bridge over the Danube.\n\nType: a) Danube; b) road/railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 2015 - Pupin Bridge ====\n[[File:Pupinov most.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Pupin Bridge]]''' (''\u041f\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') connects the neighborhood of [[Zemun]] and the suburb of [[Bor\u010da]]. The bridge construction was a joint venture of the Serbian and Chinese state capital (Exim Bank of China) and, with \u20ac170 million, it was China's first big infrastructure investment on the European continent.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://inserbia.info/today/2014/01/zemun-borca-bridge-to-be-completed-by-december-2014/ | title = Zemun-Borca bridge to be completed by December 2014 | date = 22 January 2014 | publisher = InSerbia Network Foundation }}</ref> Construction began in July 2011 and the bridge was opened on 18 December 2014. Due to the origin of the investors, even before the construction began, the bridge was colloquially called \"Chinese bridge\".<ref>{{Citation | author = Marko Lukovi\u0107 | title = Sutra predugovor za most Zemun \u2013 Bor\u010da | trans-title = Tomorrow is the signing of the precontract for the Zemun-Bor\u010da bridge | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 21 October 2009 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/108698/Ekonomija/Sutra-predugovor-za-most-Zemun-Borca }}</ref> During the construction, its tentative name was ''Zemun\u2013Bor\u010da bridge'', but later it got named after scientist and inventor [[Mihajlo Pupin]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/Dru%C5%A1tvo/1731586/Most+Zemun+-+bor%C4%8Da+i+zvani%C4%8Dno+Pupinov+most.html | title = Most Zemun - Bor\u010da i zvani\u010dno Pupinov most | trans-title = The Zemun-Bor\u010da Bridge is now officially Pupin's Bridge | date = 24 October 2014 | publisher = [[Radio Television Serbia]] }}</ref> It has 6 lanes and 2 pedestrian-bicycle paths and relieved a congestions on the only previously existing bridge, Pan\u010devo Bridge, which was overloaded for decades. The Bor\u010da section is still not urbanized and the construction of the bridge prompted some ideas for the future projects in the area. They include the future Chinese [[industrial park]] next to the bridge<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a248707/Biznis/Mali-Kineski-industrijski-park-kod-Pupinovog-mosta.html | author = Beta | title = Mali: Kineski industrijski park kod Pupinovog mosta | trans-title = Mayor Sini\u0161a Mali: Chinese industrial park at Pupin's Bridge | date = 14 May 2017 | publisher = [[N1 (television)|N1]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> and a controversial project of the new Belgrade port north of the bridge, in the [[Beljarica]] wetland known as the Belgrade Amazonia, which caused protest from the environmentalist and general public.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dragana Joki\u0107 Stamenkovi\u0107 | title = Peticija za spas beogradske Amazonije | trans-title = Petition for the save of Belgrade Amazonia | newspaper = Politika | pages = 09 | language = Serbian | date = 25 June 2017 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/383634/Peticija-za-spas-beogradske-Amazonije }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://noizz.rs/noizz-news/posetili-smo-beogradsku-amazoniju-o-kojoj-bruje-drustvene-mreze-i-vratili-se-besni/l7vdwe0?placement=WidgetPopular&position=1 | author = Ljubica Krsti\u0107 | title = Posetili smo \"beogradsku Amazoniju\" o kojoj bruje dru\u0161tvene mre\u017ee i vratili se besni | trans-title = We visited the Belgrade Amazonia that social networks are buzzing about and came back annoyed | date = 21 June 2017 | publisher = Noizz | language = Serbian}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Danube; b) road; c) urban (Zemun)/suburban (Bor\u010da);\n\n== Former bridges ==\n=== 1688-1691 - Long Bridge ===\n\n'''[[Long Bridge, Belgrade|Long Bridge]]''' (''\u0414\u0443\u0433\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was constructed further to the south from the city, near the village of [[Ostru\u017enica]] on [[\u0160umadija]] side of the river. As the [[Syrmia]]n side across the Sava was a vast marsh at the time (modern New Belgrade), the bridge didn't stop at the bank but continued for some length above the swamp. Because of that, the people also called it the Bridge above the marsh (''Most preko mo\u010dvare''). The Long Bridge was built by the Austrians to help them conquer Belgrade from the Ottomans during the [[Siege of Belgrade (1688)|1688 Siege of Belgrade]]. According to the records, a seasoned Belgrade [[master craftsman]] \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 \"in only one month, with the help of his 400 workers, built the Long Bridge, using 2,000 tree trunks, 1,100 wooden piles, 15,500 bundles of palings and 12,000 palisade pickets.\" If not before, the bridge had to be demolished by 1691 when the Ottomans reconquered Belgrade. The Long Bridge is the first permanent bridge in Belgrade history. Right next to it, bit closer to the island of Ada Ciganlija, the Austrians constructed another, classical pontoon bridge, which \"leaned on the Long Bridge\".<ref name=Politika/>\n\n=== 1934-1941 - King Alexander Bridge ===\n[[File:King Aleksandar bridge in Belgrade.jpg|thumb|200px|right]]\n\n'''[[King Alexander Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0430'') was a road and tram bridge over the Sava. It was the first permanent road bridge across the Sava in Belgrade after almost 250 years and the Long Bridge from 1688.<ref name=Politika/><ref name=novosti/> Construction began in July 1930 and the bridge was modeled after the [[M\u00fclheim Bridge, Cologne|M\u00fclheim Bridge]] over the [[Rhine]], in [[Cologne]], Germany. The third \"twin\", based on almost the same project was built in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], crossing the [[Danube]] - the second incarnation of the [[Reichsbr\u00fccke]] which collapsed due to the structural failure on 1 August 1976. King Alexander Bridge was ceremonially open on 16 December 1934 with 700 horsemen crossing over it and on 5 November 1935 the first tram line over the bridge was established.<ref name=novosti/><ref name=novosti2>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:639760-Beogradske-price-Kako-smo-se-oprostili-od-Aleksandrovog-mosta | author = Zoran Nikoli\u0107 | title = Kako smo se oprostili od Aleksandrovog mosta | trans-title = How we said goodbye to Alexander's bridge | date = 15 December 2016 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was demolished by the Yugoslav army on 11 April 1941 in order to prevent the advance of the German army.<ref name=Politika/><ref name=novosti/> Though unusable since April 1941, the remains of the bridge persisted until the heavy \"Easter bombing\" of Belgrade by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] on 16 April 1944 when it was demolished completely.<ref name=Politika/> The construction of the bridge was patterned in the [[Serbo-Byzantine Revival|Serbo-Byzantine style]], placed on two pylons made of [[reinforced concrete]], while it was held by the steel cables.<ref name=Politika/> It was praised for having both the important infrastructural and symbolicIvalue as it was the first road bridge spawning the Sava, ending its purpose as the border river and marking the directions in which the city will develop.<ref>{{cite book | title = Grbovi na javnim zdanjima Beograda, Vol. III | trans-title = Coats of arms on the public edifices in Belgrade, Vol. III | publisher = City of Belgrade Yearbook, Book XLIII, 1996 }}</ref> The bridge was revered while existed being described as \"gorgeous\" and \"one of the most important object ever built in Belgrade\".<ref name=novosti/> Its pylons were later used for the modern Branko's Bridge in 1956.<ref name=\"regenti\"/>\n\n=== 1935-1944 - Bridge of King Peter II ===\n\n'''[[Pan\u010devo Bridge#History|Bridge of King Peter II]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 II'') was the first bridge across the Danube in Belgrade. Construction of the combined, road-railway bridge began in 1933. It was inaugurated on 27 October 1935 and named after the still minor [[King of Yugoslavia]], [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Petar II]].<ref name=repar/> Just like the Old Railway Bridge and the Bridge of King Alexander, it was destroyed by the Yugoslav army in a vain attempt to slow down the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] advancement. It was destroyed on the night 10/11 April 1941. Germans repaired the bridge for their purposes during the period of occupation in 1941-1944. In the spring of 1944, the Allied Anglo-American bombing of Belgrade began. The bridge was hit and damaged in the bombings of 16 April 16 and 3 September 1944. When the Germans began to withdraw from Belgrade in October 1944, they destroyed the bridge themselves.<ref name=repar/> Pan\u010devo Bridge was built instead of it in 1946.\n\n== Seasonal bridges ==\n[[File:Great War Island pontoon bridge.jpg|thumb|150px|right]]\n\n=== Lido Pontoon Bridge ===\n\nSince the early 2000s, a military pontoon bridge has been placed each summer during the swimming season on [[Lido, Belgrade|Lido Beach]], on the [[Great War Island]] in Zemun. It connects the beach and the neighborhood of [[Zemunski Kej]], across an arm of the Danube. As the beach was almost wiped out during the disastrous [[2006 European floods]], the bridge wasn't laid in 2006-08.<ref>{{Citation | author = D.Moji\u0107 | title = Po\u010delo leto na Lidu | trans-title = Summer at Lido began | newspaper = Glas javnosti | language = Serbian | date = 3 July 2008 | url = http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/beograd/glas-javnosti-03-07-2008/pocelo-leto-na-lidu }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = N.M. | title = Sezona na Lidu od sutra | trans-title = Season on Lido starts tomorrow | newspaper = Politika | page = 24 | language = Serbian | date = 1 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn general, the bridge is laid from July to September. It is {{convert|375|m|abbr=on}} long and placed by the engineering units of the [[Serbian Armed Forces]]. Placing of the bridge regularly sparks protest from the boatmen, either those who work as a ferrymen when there is no bridge, or those who are simply blocked in the Danube's arm between the island and the bank across it.<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u0443 | trans-title = Pontoon to Lido placed  | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 26 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Planned bridges ==\n=== Ada Huja Bridge ===\n[[File:Belgrade bypass.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Projected traffic routes of Belgrade, showing locations of Ada Huja and Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo bridges]]\n\nEvery Belgrade's general urban plan (GUP) since the mid-1950s included the bridge over the Danube, connecting the neighborhoods of Vi\u0161njica and [[Krnja\u010da]], over the peninsula of [[Ada Huja]]. Parallel to the existing Pan\u010devo Bridge, and projected east of it, the Ada Huja bridge was always envisioned as the important freight transport route. In 2005 city administration announced the construction of the bridge which was to last for 3 years. In April 2008 the construction was announced again, but in March 2009 it was said that it is not a priority. New announcement came in September 2016 with a deadline for the complete paperwork to be finished set at the end of 2017 or early 2018. The bridge will be part of the future Belgrade City Middle Ring Road. In April 2017 city officials stated that the construction of the bridge will start \"soon\".<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Most na Adi Huji \u010deka najbolju ideju | trans-title = Ada Huja Bridge awaits the best idea | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 6 September 2016 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/362965/Most-na-Adi-Huji-ceka-najbolju-ideju }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = Tanjug | title = Gradi\u0107e se novi most na Dunavu kod Ade Huje | trans-title = New bridge will be build on the Danube at Ada Huja | newspaper = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian | date = 17 April 2017 | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:660756-Gradice-se-novi-most-na-Dunavu-kod-Ade-Huje }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.istinomer.rs/ocena/1398/Ada-Huja-dobija-most | author = Istinomer team | title = Ada Huja dobija most| trans-title = Ada Huja gets a bridge | date = 24 October 2011 | publisher = Istinomer | language = Serbian }}</ref> In April 2018 it was announced that work on the conceptual design and feasibility study began and that it will be finished by the mid-2019.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Beta | title = Vesi\u0107: Po\u010dinje izrada idejnog projekta za most kod Ade Huje | trans-title = Vesi\u0107: Work on the conceptual design for the Ada Huja bridge began | newspaper = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2018 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a378284/Vesti/Izrada-idejnog-projekta-za-most-kod-Ade-Huje.html }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | title = \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0438\u0434\u0435\u0458\u043d\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0410\u0434\u0435 \u0425\u0443\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Work on the conceptual design for the Ada Huja bridge began  | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 10 April 2018 }}</ref> Deputy mayor Goran Vesi\u0107 stated in July 2018 that the construction will commence in 2020,<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0432\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438 \u0425\u0443\u0458\u0438, \u043f\u0430 \u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \"\u041f\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0430\" | trans-title = First bridge on Ada Huja, then reconstruction of Pan\u010devo Bridge | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 23 July 2018}}</ref> but in May 2019 moved it to 2021.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107  | title = \u041e\u0434 \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0432\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438 | trans-title = By train across the Ada Bridge from June | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo Bridge ===\n\nA combined road-rail bridge, proposed as a part of the still unfinished [[Belgrade bypass]]. It will connect the [[Banat]] region of [[Vojvodina]] directly with central Serbia, which would reroute traffic, especially the freight and hazardous transports, from downtown Belgrade to the outer suburban area. Three variants of the bridge were presented in August 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/tri-varijante-mosta-kod-vince/dt8g2jh | author = D.Dra\u017ei\u0107 | title = Tri varijante mosta kod Vin\u010de | trans-title = Three variants of the Vin\u010da bridge | date = 7 August 2007 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref> In 2012 it was announced that Chinese investors have a project.<ref name=bild>[http://beobuild.rs/forum/viewtopic.php?t=2706#p199422 Drumsko \u017eelezni\u010dki most Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo (Road-railway bridge Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo, August 2012]</ref> In February 2015 it was confirmed that the Chinese investors will build this bridge, too, with a deadline of 3 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/ekonomija/otkrivamo-kinezi-nam-grade-jos-jedan-most-u-beogradu/zn2hpc9 | author = Mateja Beljan | title = Kinezi nam grade jo\u0161 jedan most u Beogradu  | trans-title = Chinese are building another bridge in Belgrade | date = 28 February 2015 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref> Partial documentation was gathered by September 2015 and in February 2016 the government of Serbia confirmed the construction of the bridge, defining it as a strategic project but labeling the bridge as the \"special problem\".<ref>[http://www.mgsi.gov.rs/lat/projekti/izgradnja-obilazne-pruge-beli-potok-vinca-sa-izgradnjom-drumsko-zeleznickog-mosta-i Ministry of construction, transportation and infrastructure, The project, 17 February 2016]</ref> The bridge will extend from the projected section of the bypass beginning at the interchange of [[Bubanj Potok]] and ending at the suburb of Vin\u010da.<ref name=bild/> On the Pan\u010devo side, the bridge will cross at the village of [[Omoljica]]. The construction of the bridge is directly connected with the completing of the bypass which, as of April 2020, is not even close to be finished.\n\n=== Metro Bridge ===\n [[File:Metro proposal 2018.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Map of the 2018 subway project with crossing over the Sava (red line)]]\n\nThe bridge was conceived in the 1970s as the carrier of the subway system across the Sava (Serbian ''metro'', subway). It was envisioned as the two-leveled bridge, where upper level would be used by the traffic, pedestrians and cyclists, while the lover level would be used by the subway trains. Its planned location was {{convert|80|m|abbr=on}} upstream from the Old Sava Bridge.<ref name=bakic>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aROvaHiJ4lE&t=10m00s | author = Aleksandar Pavkovi\u0107 | title = Interview: Dragoljub Baki\u0107 - Beograd \u0107e propasti ako ne bude ozbiljnih projekata | trans-title = Interview: Dragoljub Baki\u0107 - Belgrade will collapse if there are no serious projects | date = 18 January 2020 | publisher = Balkan Info | language = Serbian}}</ref> Plans for the entire subway grid were fully finished in 1976 but the construction never began, and in 1982 city decided to scrap the subway plans completely. The idea was revived in the 1990s and the talks of the bridge resurfaced in 1998 but again nothing happened.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Metro pola veka na po\u010detnoj stanici | trans-title = Metro still on the starting point after half a century | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 11 February 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/398145/Metro-pola-veka-na-pocetnoj-stanici }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Marijana Avakumovi\u0107  | title = Metro opet na \u010dekanju | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 30 October 2009 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/109830/Ekonomija/Metro-opet-na-cekanju}}</ref> The latest subway plan from 2018-2019 also includes this bridge and alleges the beginning of the construction in 2020, but since the government changed the grid projects several times, as of April 2020 the project for the new bridge isn't drafted at all and it is not known where it will be located or what it would look like. Even if construction would start in 2020, the line planned to commute over the bridge may not be finished in six years after that, with one city plan giving even 2033 as the year when the line will be finished.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/rok-se-produzuje-metro-prioritet-tek-za-2027-godinu/ | author = A. Popovi\u0107 | title = Rok se produ\u017euje, metro prioritet tek za 2027. godinu | trans-title = Deadline is extending, metro priority only in 2027 | date = 23 March 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Plan za metro \u2013 za dve godine  | trans-title = Plan for the metro - in two years | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 27 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/406271/Plan-za-metro-za-dve-godine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a399188/Vesti/Sednica-Skupstine-Beograda-o-metrou-i-Vinci.html | author = Emina Kova\u010devi\u0107 | title = Do prve linije metroa ipak te\u0161ko do 2022, ni Vesi\u0107 ne veruje | trans-title = Hardly to the first metro line by 2022, Vesi\u0107 doesn't believe it either | date = 26 June 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n=== New Belgrade-Ada Ciganlija Bridge ===\n\nIn March 2020, it was announced that the construction of the first pedestrian-cyclist bridge in Belgrade will commence in 2021. It will connect New Belgrade with the island of Ada Ciganlija across the Sava, as the continuation of the Omladinskih Brigada street in Block 70. Public, partially underground garage with 300 parking spots will be built at the end of the street. This is the second part of the project city administration alleged is the result of citizens' online voting (first part is relocation of the Old Sava Bridge on dry land, in the [[U%C5%A1%C4%87e,_Belgrade#Park_U\u0161\u0107e|Park U\u0161\u0107e]] to become an \"attraction\"). Reporters and public distanced from the voting or debunked it as being rigged.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 |script-title=sr: \u041f\u0435\u0448\u0430\u0447\u043a\u043e-\u0431\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438 | trans-title = Pedestrian-cyclist bridge, first in the capital  | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet | author = Dule Astro | user = astrodule | number = 1188190950474108928 | date = 26 October 2019 | language = Serbian | title = Trenutno se de\u0161avaju velike neregularnosti na anketi o sudbini Starog savskog mosta.... | trans-title = Major irregularities are happening at the voting for the future of the Old Sava Bridgge... | link = https://twitter.com/astrodule/status/1188190950474108928}}</ref><ref name=anketa>{{cite news | author = Mladen Savatovi\u0107 | title = Stari savski most - od mosta na Savi do mosta na travi | trans-title = Old Sava Bridge - from bridge on Sava to bridge on grass | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 19 December 2019 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Vesti/a553937/Stari-savski-most-od-mosta-na-Savi-do-mosta-na-travi.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Pe\u0161a\u010dko-biciklisti\u010dki most za manje automobila na Adi | trans-title = Pedestrian-bicycle bridge for less cars on Ada | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 23 April 2020 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/452804/Pesacko-biciklisticki-most-za-manje-automobila-na-Adi}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed bridges ==\n=== Nemanjina Bridge ===\n [[File:Belgrad street.JPG|right|thumb|100px|Ending of the [[Nemanjina Street]], where the proposed bridge should start]]\n\nThe bridge across the Sava in the extension of the [[Nemanjina Street]] ([[Savamala]], old Belgrade-[[Staro Sajmi\u0161te]], New Belgrade) is considered to be the \"ideal\" missing bridge in Belgrade, due to its location. In the 1970s, the measurements were made, geometric survey was conducted, locations of the pillars were set and in the end, even the project was finished.<ref name=bakic/> However, the construction of such bridge would be extremely difficult as the areas on the river banks are already urbanized. It would take massive demolitions to clear the area and it was concluded it wouldn't be financially wise either. The idea of the bridge on this location, however, keeps popping-up regularly in discussions regarding transportation in Belgrade.<ref name=hajdin>{{cite news | author = Nikola Hajdin (interview with) | title = Most vredi svaki evro | trans-title = The bridge is worth every euro | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 10 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Ada Bridge II ===\n\nWhen plans were made for the Ada Bridge, one of the proposals was the location on the opposite, upstream tip of Ada Ciganlija, instead of the downstream one, where it was built in the end. It would connect [[Maki\u0161]] on the right, and [[Savski Nasip]] on the left bank of the Sava.<ref>{{cite news | author = Zoran Majdin | title = \u017dirafa pored gazelle | trans-title = Giraffe next to gazelle | newspaper = Vreme, No. 935 | language = Serbian | date = 4 December 2008 | url = https://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=764160}}</ref> When Ada Bridge was close to be finished, architects suggested this other location as the place where the next Belgrade bridge might or should be built.<ref name=hajdin/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of bridges in Serbia]]\n* [[Transport in Belgrade]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Transport in Belgrade}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Belgrade]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Zemun 1688.jpg|right|thumb|250px|1688 map of [[Zemun]] and Belgrade, showing a pontoon bridge]]\n[[File:Belgrade from LH1407.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Aerial view of the [[Sava]] river, showing five out of six bridges in the urban section of the city]]\n\n[[Belgrade]], the capital of [[Serbia]], is located on two major rivers, the [[Danube]] and the [[Sava]] which are spanned by 11 bridges in total.\n\n== Introduction ==\n\nThe Greek historian [[Zosimus]] mentions the bridge in Belgrade (at that time, [[Singidunum]]) already in the 5th century, which is the oldest historical mention of any bridges in the city. Other historical records observe other bridges, from the [[Byzantine]] and later periods, like in 1521, 1595, 1688<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Zemun_1688.jpg Map of Zemun 1688]</ref> or 1717,<ref>{{cite news | author = Miroslav Stefanovi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0417\u0435\u043c\u0443\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u0432\u0440\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043f\u043b\u043e\u0432 - \u0412\u0430\u0440\u043e\u0448\u0430\u043d\u0438 \u0432\u043e\u043b\u0435\u043b\u0438 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u043e \u0438 \u043a\u0430\u0444\u0430\u043d\u0435 | trans-title = Zemun chronicles - Townspeople like Lido and kafanas | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1170 | page = 28 | language = Serbian | date = 1 March 2020}}</ref> but they were all temporary, [[pontoon bridges]], constructed solely for the purpose of conquering the city during the numerous battles and sieges of Belgrade through history.\n\nIn 1521, Karaca Pasha, military commander of the Ottoman sultan [[Suleiman the Magnificent]] built a pontoon bridge across the Sava, while in 1595 Ottomans built a pontoon over the Danube, near the village of [[Vi\u0161njica, Serbia|Vi\u0161njica]]. The bridge in 1717 was built on the orders of the Austrian commander [[Prince Eugene of Savoy]].<ref name=Politika>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Beogradski mostovi \u2013 od oblica do pilona | trans-title = Bridges of Belgrade - from logs to pylons | newspaper = [[Politika]] |language = Serbian | date = 13 August 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/187584/%D0%91%D0%B5%D0%BE%D0%B3%D1%80%D0%B0%D0%B4%D1%81%D0%BA%D0%B8-%D0%BC%D0%BE%D1%81%D1%82%D0%BE%D0%B2%D0%B8-%D0%BE%D0%B4-%D0%BE%D0%B1%D0%BB%D0%B8%D1%86%D0%B0-%D0%B4%D0%BE-%D0%BF%D0%B8%D0%BB%D0%BE%D0%BD%D0%B0 }}</ref>\n\nThe chronicles mention no less than 10 pontoon bridges on the location of the modern [[Branko's Bridge]] - 5 Austrian and 5 Ottoman.<ref name=novosti>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:444377-Beogradske-price-Most-viteskog-kralja-Aleksandra | author = Zoran Nikoli\u0107 | title = Beogradske pri\u010de: Most vite\u0161kog kralja Aleksandra | trans-title = Belgrade stories: Bridge of the knightly king Alexander | date = 17 July 2013 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n== Types ==\n\nThey can be categorized in several ways:\n\na) 10 across the Sava, 2 across the Danube;<br>b) 8 road bridges, 3 railway and 1 combined;<br>c) 7 urban, 4 suburban and 1 combined;\n\n== Bridges by water body ==\n=== Sava ===\n==== 1884 - Old Railroad Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, Old railway bridge, 10.04.2011.jpg|right|thumb|250px]]\n\n'''[[Old Railroad Bridge]]''' (''{{lang-sr|\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442}}'') was built within the project of constructing the first railway in Serbia. It was built on a French concession which included the construction of the Belgrade\u2013[[Ni\u0161]] railway, the railway bridge over the Sava and a railway which will connect Belgrade to [[Zemun]], at the time, the border town of [[Austria-Hungary]].<ref name=stari>{{Citation | author = Dragan Peri\u0107 | title = Gvozdeni konji u Ciganskoj bari | trans-title = Iron horses in the Gypsy pond | newspaper = Politika-Magazin, No. 1039 | pages = 28\u201329 | language = Serbian | date = 27 August 2017 }}</ref> It was demolished in both [[World Wars]] and the present construction was placed after the [[World War II]] ended.<ref name=Politika/> As the only connection between Serbia and the Austria-Hungary, who already positioned its army near the bridge, it was demolished by the Serbian army on 29 July 1914. It was reconstructed in 1919.<ref name=glas>{{cite web | url = http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/glas-javnosti-07-08-2007/beogradski-mostovi | author = G.J. | title = Beogradski vekovnik - Beogradski mostovi | trans-title = Belgrade century book - Belgrade bridges | date = 7 August 2007 | publisher = [[Glas Javnosti]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/300935/Srusio-most-pred-naletom-Austrougara-danas-u-zaboravu | author = Nikola Beli\u0107 | title = Sru\u0161io most pred naletom Austrougara \u2013 danas u zaboravu | trans-title = (He) demolished the bridge in front of the advancing Austro-Hungarians - today forgotten | date = 1 August 2014 | publisher = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> When Germany attacked Yugoslavia on 6 April 1941, the High Command decided to demolish all three existing bridges in Belgrade, including the railway bridge.<ref name=Politika/> It was reconstructed again in 1945, funded by the [[war reparations]].<ref name=glas/> Though projected as a temporary link in 1945, the bridge was reconstructed in 1986, when the tracks were replaced. Minor repairs on the bridge have been done in 1995 and 1996.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/dotrajali-pragovi-bice-zamenjeni/2z527ys | author = Lana Gedo\u0161evi\u0107 | title = Dotrajali pragovi bi\u0107e zamenjeni | trans-title = Worn out ties will be replaced | date = 9 February 2009 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was the only bridge in Belgrade until 1934. Also, it was the only railway bridge until 1935 and the only one across the Sava until 1979 when the New Railroad Bridge was open.<ref name=Politika/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 1942 - Old Sava Bridge ====\n[[File:Belgrade Sava bridge.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Old Sava Bridge]]''' (''\u0421\u0442\u0430\u0440\u0438 \u0441\u0430\u0432\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was built during the German occupation. The construction of the bridge was installed over the [[Tisza|Tisa]] river near [[\u017dabalj]], but the demolition of the [[King Alexander Bridge]], led to the installation of the construction over the eight pillars on the [[Sava]] river. It was cut in pieces and transferred to Belgrade.<ref name=\"padamost\">{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/380827/Stari-savski-most-pada-u-vodu | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Stari savski most pada u vodu | trans-title = Old Sava Bridge falls into the water | date = 18 May 2017 | publisher = Politika | page = 1 & 16 | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was the only big European bridge that was not demolished during the German withdrawals.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/265473/Beograd/Tramvajski-most-most-ucitelja-Miladina-Zarica | author = Marija Brako\u010devi\u0107 | title = Tramvajski most - most u\u010ditelja Miladina Zari\u0107a | trans-title = Tram bridge - bridge of teacher Miladin Zari\u0107 | date = 31 July 2013 | publisher = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge had a wooden driveway until 1964, when the planners suggested the reconstruction of the bridge to the mayor [[Branko Pe\u0161i\u0107]]. After a five-year reconstruction a new concrete panel was placed in 1969. After opting against the construction of [[rapid transit|metro]], despite developing the project for over a decade, in 1984 the [[tramway track]]s were laid over the bridge and the concrete panel was replaced with the steel one.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Krpljenje rupa na Starom savskom mostu | trans-title = Fixing the holes on the Old Sava Bridge | newspaper = Politika | pages = 16 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2013 }}</ref> In March 2016, mayor of Belgrade [[Sini\u0161a Mali]] announced the massive reconstruction of the bridge, slated to begin in the late 2017. He named the [[Tehran]]'s [[Tabiat Bridge]] as an inspiration.<ref name=\"padamost\"/><ref name=\"blic\">{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/rekonstrukcija-savskog-mosta-2017-godine/jh13d4h | author = Dijana Radisavljevi\u0107 | title = Rekonstrukcija Savskog mosta 2017 godine | trans-title = Reconstruction of the Sava Bridge in 2017 | date = 17 March 2016 | publisher =[[Blic]] | language = Serbian}}</ref> However, in May 2017, after the city publicized the project papers, it was obvious that all the time they wanted to demolish the bridge completely and build a new one but the old bridge will not be demolished. Instead it will be moved to another location which is still not chosen, as a pedestrian bridge.<ref name=\"padamost\"/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1953 - Ostru\u017enica Railroad Bridge ====\n\n'''[[Ostru\u017enica Railroad Bridge]]''' (''\u041e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0437\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was built in order to move the transport of toxic and explosive materials from downtown Belgrade. Built in 1953, it was damaged by [[NATO bombing of Serbia|NATO during the bombing of Serbia]] in 1999. The {{convert|658|m|abbr=on}} long bridge was repaired and open on 15 September 2006.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.srbija.gov.rs/vesti/vest.php?id=55619 | title = Ko\u0161tunica otvorio \u017eelezni\u010dki most kod Ostru\u017enice | trans-title = Ko\u0161tunica opened the railway bridge at Ostru\u017enica | date = 15 September 2006 | publisher = Government of the Republic of Serbia | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) suburban;\n\n==== 1956 - Branko's Bridge ====\n[[File:Branko's bridge (Brankov most), Belgrade.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Branko's Bridge]]''' (''\u0411\u0440\u0430\u043d\u043a\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') replaced in 1956 the former chain-stayed [[King Alexander Bridge]], which was operational from 1934 to 1941. The bridge actually uses lower parts of the former bridge's pylons as outer constraints for its two secondary spans.<ref name=\"regenti\">{{Citation | author = Marko Lukovi\u0107 | title = \"Gazelini regenti\" preuzimaju du\u017enost | trans-title = \"Gazela's regents\" take over | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 8 July 2010 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/141657/Beograd/Gazelini-regenti-preuzimaju-duznost }}</ref> After the World War II, in the 1950s, the general idea was that trolleybuses should take over the major role in the public transportation. Line to Zemun was opened in 1956, and in time three lines over the bridge were formed: Line 14 \u2013 [[Zeleni Venac]]-[[Gornji Grad (Zemun)]]  (which was considered a successor line to the pre-war tram line), Line 15 \u2013 Zeleni Venac-[[Novi Grad (Zemun)]] and Line 16 \u2013 Zeleni Venac-Pohorska, [[New Belgrade]]. The lines were closed in 1973.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \"Trole\" vozile Novobeogra\u0111ane i Zemunce | trans-title = Trolleybuses transported inhabitants of New Belgrade and Zemun | newspaper = Politika | pages = 31 | language = Serbian | date = 2 May 2017 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/379527/Trole-vozile-Novobeogradane-i-Zemunce}}</ref> The bridge gained an infamous reputation as the [[suicide bridge]]. Some 40 people try to commit suicide jumping of the Branko's Bridge every year.<ref name=\"regenti\"/>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1970 - Gazela Bridge ====\n[[File:Gazela.JPG|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Gazela Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u0413\u0430\u0437\u0435\u043b\u0430'') is the most important, central bridge in the city, the main connection between downtown Belgrade and New Belgrade, carrying the transit traffic on [[E70 in Serbia|E70]] and [[E75 in Serbia|E75]] highways. Daily traffic exceeds 165,000 vehicles.<ref name=prst>{{Citation | author = Marko Laki\u0107, Nikola Mikovi\u0107| title = Preko \"Gazele\" na prstima | trans-title = Tiptoeing over \"Gazela\" | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 30 March 2009 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/81194/Ekonomija/Preko-Gazele-na-prstima }}</ref> It was built from 1966 to 1970. Immediately after the opening in 1970, a defect was noticed. Due to the miscalculations, the metallic construction began to depress in the middle of the bridge. By the 2010 reconstruction, it became visible both by watching the bridge from the side or crossing it. In order to alleviate the problem, on the metallic sections of the bridge, the concrete [[shoulder (road)|shoulders]] were replaced with the lighter, metallic ones. After a long debate, which lasted for years, on the condition of the bridge, a major reconstruction ensued in 2010-11.<ref name=prst/> After the reconstruction, city officials stated the bridge would be able to handle 200,000 vehicles daily for the next 40 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:392570-Gazela-spremna-i-za-200000-vozila | title = Gazela spremna i za 200,000 vozila | trans-title = Gazela ready for 200,000 vehicles | publisher = [[Ve\u010dernje novosti]] | date = 12 August 2012 }}</ref> However, the bridge is still overloaded, despite the significant relief when the new [[Ada Bridge]] was opened for traffic on 1 January 2012. Additional relief is expected when the [[Belgrade bypass]] is completed.\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 1979 - New Railroad Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, New railway bridge, 20.04.2011.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[New Railroad Bridge]]''' (''\u041d\u043e\u0432\u0438 \u0436\u0435\u043b\u0435\u0455\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') is a [[cable-stayed bridge]], the second railway bridge across the Sava in the urban section of Belgrade. The construction of the bridge began in 1975 and it was completed and opened for traffic in 1979. The bridge was built as a part of the projected [[Belgrade railway junction]] and it directly connects New Belgrade with the, still unfinished, [[Belgrade Centre railway station]] in the neighborhood of [[Prokop (Belgrade)|Prokop]].<ref name=Politika/> Designed by [[Nikola Hajdin]], it was the first bridge in Europe to use cable-stayed girder system.\n\nType: a) Sava; b) railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 1998 - Ostru\u017enica Bridge ====\n\n'''[[Ostru\u017enica Bridge]]''' (''\u041e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') is a three-lane semi-highway [[girder bridge]] carrying the Belgrade bypass. It was constructed from 1990 to 1998. The bridge was [[NATO bombing of Yugoslavia|bombed by NATO]] during the [[Kosovo War]] in 1999 and fully reconstructed by 2004. The additional, parallel three-lane span is under construction since January 2016. The original deadline was 26 months, or April 2018. It was then moved to March 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://mondo.rs/a867229/Info/Ekonomija/Obilaznica-oko-Beograda-Ostruznica-most-Vucic.html | title = Premijer bacio \"prvu lopatu\" mosta kod Ostru\u017enice}}</ref> In May 2019 the end of construction was set to October 2019.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u043e\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0443\u0436\u043d\u0438\u0447\u043a\u043e\u0433 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u0431\u043b\u0438\u0437\u0430\u043d\u0446\u0430 \u043e\u0434 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0458\u0430 \u043e\u043a\u0442\u043e\u0431\u0440\u0430 | trans-title = Driving across the Ostru\u017enica twin bridge from late October | newspaper = [[Politika]] | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 8 May 2019}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n==== 2011 - Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge ====\n[[File:Most Obrenovac - Surcin 1.jpg|thumb|150px|right]]\n\n'''[[Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446-\u0421\u0443\u0440\u0447\u0438\u043d'') was built from 1994 to 2011. It was originally projected as the carrier for the [[district heating]] pipeline, hence the closeness to the power plant.),<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Spalovi\u0107 | title = Most Obrenovac-Sur\u010din povezao dva dela Srbije | trans-title = Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge connected two parts of Serbia | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 1 December 2011 }}</ref><ref name=\"beobild\">{{cite web | url= http://beobuild.rs/linking-obrenovac-and-surcin-p2298.html | title= Linking Obrenovac and Sur\u010din | date = 2 October 2011 | publisher = Beobuild | language = Serbian }}</ref> It was supposed to connect the [[TPP Nikola Tesla]] plant with [[New Belgrade]]. In 1997.<ref name=\"Politika1\">{{Citation | author = Dimitrije Bukvi\u0107 | title = Most u beogradskoj Posavini bi\u0107e zavr\u0161en za 45 dana | trans-title = Bridge in Belgrade's Sava valley will be finished in 45 days | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 14 October 2011 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/194445/Beograd/Most-u-beogradskoj-Posavini-bice-zavrsen-za-45-dana}}</ref> the project was changed to include the possibility of transporting tanks and other military technics and then the idea was expanded to include the regular traffic. Due to the financial constraints, the works were halted in 1998 and the NATO bombing in 1999 pushed this project out of any future plans as so much other infrastructure had to be repaired. In the next years nothing new was done as works included only the maintenance of the already placed steel construction and the reparation of one of the pillars which was damaged by the [[barge]].The idea resurfaced in 2006 when the discussions were held on the profitability of the heating pipeline and eventually the pipeline idea was dropped.<ref name=\"beobild\"/> Tentative works on further building began in April 2010<ref name=\"Politika1\"/> and the full blown construction ensued in 2011. The bridge was opened on 1 December 2011.<ref name=\"danas\">{{cite web|url= http://www.danas.rs/danasrs/srbija/beograd/pusten_u_saobracaj_most_obrenovacsurcin.39.html?news_id=229344 |author = B.I. | title = Pu\u0161ten u saobra\u0107aj most Obrenovac-Sur\u010din | trans-title = Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge open for traffic | date = 1 December 2016 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n==== 2012 - Ada Bridge ====\n[[File:Ada Bridge.JPG|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Ada Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438'') is a cable-stayed bridge which crosses the tip of [[Ada Ciganlija]] island, connecting the municipalities of [[\u010cukarica]] and New Belgrade. The bridge [[Tower#Transportation support|pylon]] is located on the tip of the island, which has been reinforced with large amounts of concrete and has been slightly enlarged to provide stronger foundations. Construction began in 2008, and the bridge was opened on 1 January 2012.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.b92.net/automobili/aktuelno.php?nav_id=530579&fs=1 | trans-title = The bridge on Ada Ciganlija (was) connected | title = Spojen most na Adi Ciganliji | publisher = B92.net | date = 9 August 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/uz-vatromet-otvoren-most-na-adi/584ne7y | author = M.J. | title = Uz vatromet otvoren Most na Adi | trans-title = Ada Bridge open with fireworks | date = 1 January 2012 | publisher = [[Blic]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> Component parts of the deck were manufactured in China and delivered in transportable units on a sea and river-route via [[Rotterdam]] through the [[Rhine\u2013Main\u2013Danube Canal]] to the pre-assembly yard next to the construction site at [[Mala Ciganlija]] in Belgrade.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.gradnja.rs/most-na-adi-u-magazinu-bridge/ | author = Igor Coni\u0107 | title = Most na Adi u magazinu Bridge | trans-title = Ada Bridge in the Bridge magazine | date = 8 February 2011 | publisher = Gradnja.rs | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge is designed to significantly reduce traffic passing through the city center and the Gazela Bridge. It is planned to be part of the future {{ill|Belgrade Inner City Semi-Ring Road|sr|\u0423\u043d\u0443\u0442\u0440\u0430\u0448\u045a\u0438 \u043c\u0430\u0433\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0440\u0430\u043b\u043d\u0438 \u043f\u043e\u043b\u0443\u043f\u0440\u0441\u0442\u0435\u043d}}.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://beobuild.rs/inner-ring-road--detailed-plan-concept-p2248.html | title = Inner Ring Road - Detailed plan concept | date = 7 October 2010 | publisher = Beobuild | language = Serbian }}</ref> It has three road lanes and a tram (light rail) track in each direction.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rtrs.tv/vijesti/vijest.php?id=44324 | author = [[Tanjug]] | title = Beograd - novi most spojio obale | trans-title = Belgrade - new bridge connected the banks | date = 9 August 2011 | publisher = [[RTRS]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was featured in the fifth episode, season nine of the [[Discovery Channel]] documentary television series ''[[Build It Bigger]]''.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://science.discovery.com/tv/build-bigger/projects/serbia/sava-river-bridge.html | title = Sava River Bridge: Extreme Engineering: Science Channel | publisher = Science.discovery.com | date = 30 March 2010 }}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) urban;\n\n==== 2019 - Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge (A2 motorway) ====\n\n'''[[Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge (A2 motorway)|Obrenovac-Sur\u010din Bridge]]''' on the [[A2 motorway (Serbia)|A2 motorway]], was in construction since 2017. Preparatory works began on 12 February and construction started on 23 May. The bridge crosses not only the Sava, but also its tributary [[Kolubara]]. This section of the A2 motorway and the access roads to the bridge were in construction since 1 March 2017. The construction company was [[China Communications Construction]].<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/novi-most-preko-save-priprema-se-teren-za-gradiliste-u-obrenovcu/mv9zeld | author = A.R. | title = Novi most preko Save: Priprema se teren za gradili\u0161te u Obrenovcu | trans-title = New bridge over the Sava: the ground is being prepared for the construction | date = 12 February 2017 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Novi most preko Save kod Obrenovca po planu | trans-title = New bridge over the Sava at Obrenovac goes by the plan | newspaper = Politika | pages = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 11 August 2017 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/drustvo/2744427/pocela-gradnja-novog-mosta-preko-kolubare-i-save.html | author = [[Tanjug]] | title = Po\u010dela gradnja novog mosta preko Kolubare i Save | trans-title = The construction of the new bridge across the Sava and Kolubara began | date = 23 May 2017 | publisher = Radio Television Serbia | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was ceremonially opened for traffic, with the adjoining Obrenovac-Sur\u010din section of the motorway, on 17 December 2019.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | script-title=sr: \u0410\u0443\u0442\u043e\u043c\u043e\u0431\u0438\u043b\u0438 \u043e\u0434 \u0434\u0430\u043d\u0430\u0441 \u043d\u0430 \u0430\u0443\u0442\u043e-\u043f\u0443\u0442\u0443 \u041e\u0431\u0440\u0435\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430\u0446-\u0421\u0443\u0440\u0447\u0438\u043d | trans-title = Automobiles on the Obrenovac-Sur\u010din motorway from today | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 18 December 2019}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Sava; b) road; c) suburban;\n\n=== Danube ===\n==== 1946 - Pan\u010devo Bridge ====\n[[File:Serbia, Belgrade, Pancevo bridge, 07.08.2011, 2.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Pan\u010devo Bridge]]''' (''\u041f\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0430\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') replaced in 1946 the former Bridge of King Peter II, which was built in 1935 and completely destroyed in 1944. It is a combined road/railway bridge. Rebuilding began in 1945, upstream from the remnants of the destroyed supporting piers. Plans were drawn up by the [[Soviet Union|Soviet]] engineers of the [[Red Army]]'s technical troops. Soviet leader [[Joseph Stalin]]'s orders were that they should build a provisory crossing, but Yugoslav prime minister [[Josip Broz Tito]] convinced him that a proper bridge should be built. On 7 November 1946, the first train passed over the new bridge and regular road traffic started three weeks later, on 29 November. Originally, it was named the Bridge of the Red Army (''Most Crvene Armije'').<ref>{{Citation | author = Radovan Kova\u010devi\u0107 | title = Pan\u010deva\u010dki most 1946. obnovili Rusi | trans-title = Pan\u010devo Bridge was rebuilt by the Russians in 1946 | newspaper = Politika | pages = 11 | language = Serbian | date = 12 April 2008 }}</ref> It was damaged in the explosion of the Russian tanker ships convoy in 1963.<ref>{{Citation | title = Posle eksplozije kod Pan\u010deva\u010dkog mosta na Dunavu | trans-title = After explosion near the Pan\u010devo Bridge on the Danube | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 24 March 1963 }}</ref> Not counting the [[\u0110erdap]] dams on the [[Romania]]n border, Pan\u010devo Bridge was the only bridge over the Danube in Serbia that was not destroyed by NATO forces during the bombing of Serbia in 1999.<ref name=repar>{{Citation | title = Dunav premo\u0161\u0107en ratnim reparacijama | trans-title = Danube crossed thanks to the war reparations | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian }}</ref> Until the opening of the Pupin Bridge in 2015, it was the only Belgrade's bridge over the Danube.\n\nType: a) Danube; b) road/railway; c) urban;\n\n==== 2015 - Pupin Bridge ====\n[[File:Pupinov most.jpg|thumb|250px|right]]\n\n'''[[Pupin Bridge]]''' (''\u041f\u0443\u043f\u0438\u043d\u043e\u0432 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') connects the neighborhood of [[Zemun]] and the suburb of [[Bor\u010da]]. The bridge construction was a joint venture of the Serbian and Chinese state capital (Exim Bank of China) and, with \u20ac170 million, it was China's first big infrastructure investment on the European continent.<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://inserbia.info/today/2014/01/zemun-borca-bridge-to-be-completed-by-december-2014/ | title = Zemun-Borca bridge to be completed by December 2014 | date = 22 January 2014 | publisher = InSerbia Network Foundation }}</ref> Construction began in July 2011 and the bridge was opened on 18 December 2014. Due to the origin of the investors, even before the construction began, the bridge was colloquially called \"Chinese bridge\".<ref>{{Citation | author = Marko Lukovi\u0107 | title = Sutra predugovor za most Zemun \u2013 Bor\u010da | trans-title = Tomorrow is the signing of the precontract for the Zemun-Bor\u010da bridge | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 21 October 2009 | url = http://www.politika.co.rs/sr/clanak/108698/Ekonomija/Sutra-predugovor-za-most-Zemun-Borca }}</ref> During the construction, its tentative name was ''Zemun\u2013Bor\u010da bridge'', but later it got named after scientist and inventor [[Mihajlo Pupin]].<ref>{{Cite news | url = http://www.rts.rs/page/stories/sr/story/125/Dru%C5%A1tvo/1731586/Most+Zemun+-+bor%C4%8Da+i+zvani%C4%8Dno+Pupinov+most.html | title = Most Zemun - Bor\u010da i zvani\u010dno Pupinov most | trans-title = The Zemun-Bor\u010da Bridge is now officially Pupin's Bridge | date = 24 October 2014 | publisher = [[Radio Television Serbia]] }}</ref> It has 6 lanes and 2 pedestrian-bicycle paths and relieved a congestions on the only previously existing bridge, Pan\u010devo Bridge, which was overloaded for decades. The Bor\u010da section is still not urbanized and the construction of the bridge prompted some ideas for the future projects in the area. They include the future Chinese [[industrial park]] next to the bridge<ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a248707/Biznis/Mali-Kineski-industrijski-park-kod-Pupinovog-mosta.html | author = Beta | title = Mali: Kineski industrijski park kod Pupinovog mosta | trans-title = Mayor Sini\u0161a Mali: Chinese industrial park at Pupin's Bridge | date = 14 May 2017 | publisher = [[N1 (television)|N1]] | language = Serbian }}</ref> and a controversial project of the new Belgrade port north of the bridge, in the [[Beljarica]] wetland known as the Belgrade Amazonia, which caused protest from the environmentalist and general public.<ref>{{Citation | author = Dragana Joki\u0107 Stamenkovi\u0107 | title = Peticija za spas beogradske Amazonije | trans-title = Petition for the save of Belgrade Amazonia | newspaper = Politika | pages = 09 | language = Serbian | date = 25 June 2017 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/383634/Peticija-za-spas-beogradske-Amazonije }}</ref><ref>{{cite web| url= http://noizz.rs/noizz-news/posetili-smo-beogradsku-amazoniju-o-kojoj-bruje-drustvene-mreze-i-vratili-se-besni/l7vdwe0?placement=WidgetPopular&position=1 | author = Ljubica Krsti\u0107 | title = Posetili smo \"beogradsku Amazoniju\" o kojoj bruje dru\u0161tvene mre\u017ee i vratili se besni | trans-title = We visited the Belgrade Amazonia that social networks are buzzing about and came back annoyed | date = 21 June 2017 | publisher = Noizz | language = Serbian}}</ref>\n\nType: a) Danube; b) road; c) urban (Zemun)/suburban (Bor\u010da);\n\n== Former bridges ==\n=== 1688-1691 - Long Bridge ===\n\n'''[[Long Bridge, Belgrade|Long Bridge]]''' (''\u0414\u0443\u0433\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442'') was constructed further to the south from the city, near the village of [[Ostru\u017enica]] on [[\u0160umadija]] side of the river. As the [[Syrmia]]n side across the Sava was a vast marsh at the time (modern New Belgrade), the bridge didn't stop at the bank but continued for some length above the swamp. Because of that, the people also called it the Bridge above the marsh (''Most preko mo\u010dvare''). The Long Bridge was built by the Austrians to help them conquer Belgrade from the Ottomans during the [[Siege of Belgrade (1688)|1688 Siege of Belgrade]]. According to the records, a seasoned Belgrade [[master craftsman]] \u0110or\u0111evi\u0107 \"in only one month, with the help of his 400 workers, built the Long Bridge, using 2,000 tree trunks, 1,100 wooden piles, 15,500 bundles of palings and 12,000 palisade pickets.\" If not before, the bridge had to be demolished by 1691 when the Ottomans reconquered Belgrade. The Long Bridge is the first permanent bridge in Belgrade history. Right next to it, bit closer to the island of Ada Ciganlija, the Austrians constructed another, classical pontoon bridge, which \"leaned on the Long Bridge\".<ref name=Politika/>\n\n=== 1934-1941 - King Alexander Bridge ===\n[[File:King Aleksandar bridge in Belgrade.jpg|thumb|200px|right]]\n\n'''[[King Alexander Bridge]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0430 \u0410\u043b\u0435\u043a\u0441\u0430\u043d\u0434\u0440\u0430'') was a road and tram bridge over the Sava. It was the first permanent road bridge across the Sava in Belgrade after almost 250 years and the Long Bridge from 1688.<ref name=Politika/><ref name=novosti/> Construction began in July 1930 and the bridge was modeled after the [[M\u00fclheim Bridge, Cologne|M\u00fclheim Bridge]] over the [[Rhine]], in [[Cologne]], Germany. The third \"twin\", based on almost the same project was built in [[Vienna]], [[Austria]], crossing the [[Danube]] - the second incarnation of the [[Reichsbr\u00fccke]] which collapsed due to the structural failure on 1 August 1976. King Alexander Bridge was ceremonially open on 16 December 1934 with 700 horsemen crossing over it and on 5 November 1935 the first tram line over the bridge was established.<ref name=novosti/><ref name=novosti2>{{cite web | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:639760-Beogradske-price-Kako-smo-se-oprostili-od-Aleksandrovog-mosta | author = Zoran Nikoli\u0107 | title = Kako smo se oprostili od Aleksandrovog mosta | trans-title = How we said goodbye to Alexander's bridge | date = 15 December 2016 | publisher = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian }}</ref> The bridge was demolished by the Yugoslav army on 11 April 1941 in order to prevent the advance of the German army.<ref name=Politika/><ref name=novosti/> Though unusable since April 1941, the remains of the bridge persisted until the heavy \"Easter bombing\" of Belgrade by the [[Allies of World War II|Allies]] on 16 April 1944 when it was demolished completely.<ref name=Politika/> The construction of the bridge was patterned in the [[Serbo-Byzantine Revival|Serbo-Byzantine style]], placed on two pylons made of [[reinforced concrete]], while it was held by the steel cables.<ref name=Politika/> It was praised for having both the important infrastructural and symbolicIvalue as it was the first road bridge spawning the Sava, ending its purpose as the border river and marking the directions in which the city will develop.<ref>{{cite book | title = Grbovi na javnim zdanjima Beograda, Vol. III | trans-title = Coats of arms on the public edifices in Belgrade, Vol. III | publisher = City of Belgrade Yearbook, Book XLIII, 1996 }}</ref> The bridge was revered while existed being described as \"gorgeous\" and \"one of the most important object ever built in Belgrade\".<ref name=novosti/> Its pylons were later used for the modern Branko's Bridge in 1956.<ref name=\"regenti\"/>\n\n=== 1935-1944 - Bridge of King Peter II ===\n\n'''[[Pan\u010devo Bridge#History|Bridge of King Peter II]]''' (''\u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043a\u0440\u0430\u0459\u0430 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u0430 II'') was the first bridge across the Danube in Belgrade. Construction of the combined, road-railway bridge began in 1933. It was inaugurated on 27 October 1935 and named after the still minor [[King of Yugoslavia]], [[Peter II of Yugoslavia|Petar II]].<ref name=repar/> Just like the Old Railway Bridge and the Bridge of King Alexander, it was destroyed by the Yugoslav army in a vain attempt to slow down the [[German Army (Wehrmacht)|German Army]] advancement. It was destroyed on the night 10/11 April 1941. Germans repaired the bridge for their purposes during the period of occupation in 1941-1944. In the spring of 1944, the Allied Anglo-American bombing of Belgrade began. The bridge was hit and damaged in the bombings of 16 April 16 and 3 September 1944. When the Germans began to withdraw from Belgrade in October 1944, they destroyed the bridge themselves.<ref name=repar/> Pan\u010devo Bridge was built instead of it in 1946.\n\n== Seasonal bridges ==\n[[File:Great War Island pontoon bridge.jpg|thumb|150px|right]]\n\n=== Lido Pontoon Bridge ===\n\nSince the early 2000s, a military pontoon bridge has been placed each summer during the swimming season on [[Lido, Belgrade|Lido Beach]], on the [[Great War Island]] in Zemun. It connects the beach and the neighborhood of [[Zemunski Kej]], across an arm of the Danube. As the beach was almost wiped out during the disastrous [[2006 European floods]], the bridge wasn't laid in 2006-08.<ref>{{Citation | author = D.Moji\u0107 | title = Po\u010delo leto na Lidu | trans-title = Summer at Lido began | newspaper = Glas javnosti | language = Serbian | date = 3 July 2008 | url = http://www.glas-javnosti.rs/clanak/beograd/glas-javnosti-03-07-2008/pocelo-leto-na-lidu }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = N.M. | title = Sezona na Lidu od sutra | trans-title = Season on Lido starts tomorrow | newspaper = Politika | page = 24 | language = Serbian | date = 1 July 2008 }}</ref>\n\nIn general, the bridge is laid from July to September. It is {{convert|375|m|abbr=on}} long and placed by the engineering units of the [[Serbian Armed Forces]]. Placing of the bridge regularly sparks protest from the boatmen, either those who work as a ferrymen when there is no bridge, or those who are simply blocked in the Danube's arm between the island and the bank across it.<ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430\u0432\u0459\u0435\u043d \u043f\u043e\u043d\u0442\u043e\u043d \u043a\u0430 \u041b\u0438\u0434\u0443 | trans-title = Pontoon to Lido placed  | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 26 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\n== Planned bridges ==\n=== Ada Huja Bridge ===\n[[File:Belgrade bypass.jpg|thumb|150px|right|Projected traffic routes of Belgrade, showing locations of Ada Huja and Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo bridges]]\n\nEvery Belgrade's general urban plan (GUP) since the mid-1950s included the bridge over the Danube, connecting the neighborhoods of Vi\u0161njica and [[Krnja\u010da]], over the peninsula of [[Ada Huja]]. Parallel to the existing Pan\u010devo Bridge, and projected east of it, the Ada Huja bridge was always envisioned as the important freight transport route. In 2005 city administration announced the construction of the bridge which was to last for 3 years. In April 2008 the construction was announced again, but in March 2009 it was said that it is not a priority. New announcement came in September 2016 with a deadline for the complete paperwork to be finished set at the end of 2017 or early 2018. The bridge will be part of the future Belgrade City Middle Ring Road. In April 2017 city officials stated that the construction of the bridge will start \"soon\".<ref>{{Citation | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = Most na Adi Huji \u010deka najbolju ideju | trans-title = Ada Huja Bridge awaits the best idea | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 6 September 2016 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/362965/Most-na-Adi-Huji-ceka-najbolju-ideju }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | author = Tanjug | title = Gradi\u0107e se novi most na Dunavu kod Ade Huje | trans-title = New bridge will be build on the Danube at Ada Huja | newspaper = Ve\u010dernje Novosti | language = Serbian | date = 17 April 2017 | url = http://www.novosti.rs/vesti/beograd.74.html:660756-Gradice-se-novi-most-na-Dunavu-kod-Ade-Huje }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.istinomer.rs/ocena/1398/Ada-Huja-dobija-most | author = Istinomer team | title = Ada Huja dobija most| trans-title = Ada Huja gets a bridge | date = 24 October 2011 | publisher = Istinomer | language = Serbian }}</ref> In April 2018 it was announced that work on the conceptual design and feasibility study began and that it will be finished by the mid-2019.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Beta | title = Vesi\u0107: Po\u010dinje izrada idejnog projekta za most kod Ade Huje | trans-title = Vesi\u0107: Work on the conceptual design for the Ada Huja bridge began | newspaper = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 9 April 2018 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a378284/Vesti/Izrada-idejnog-projekta-za-most-kod-Ade-Huje.html }}</ref><ref>{{ cite news | title = \u041f\u043e\u0447\u0438\u045a\u0435 \u0438\u0437\u0440\u0430\u0434\u0430 \u0438\u0434\u0435\u0458\u043d\u043e\u0433 \u043f\u0440\u043e\u0458\u0435\u043a\u0442\u0430 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043a\u043e\u0434 \u0410\u0434\u0435 \u0425\u0443\u0458\u0435 | trans-title = Work on the conceptual design for the Ada Huja bridge began  | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 10 April 2018 }}</ref> Deputy mayor Goran Vesi\u0107 stated in July 2018 that the construction will commence in 2020,<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107 | title = \u041f\u0440\u0432\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438 \u0425\u0443\u0458\u0438, \u043f\u0430 \u043e\u043d\u0434\u0430 \u043e\u0431\u043d\u043e\u0432\u0430 \"\u041f\u0430\u043d\u0447\u0435\u0432\u0446\u0430\" | trans-title = First bridge on Ada Huja, then reconstruction of Pan\u010devo Bridge | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 23 July 2018}}</ref> but in May 2019 moved it to 2021.<ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107  | title = \u041e\u0434 \u0458\u0443\u043d\u0430 \u0442\u0440\u0430\u043c\u0432\u0430\u0458\u0435\u043c \u043f\u0440\u0435\u043a\u043e \u041c\u043e\u0441\u0442\u0430 \u043d\u0430 \u0410\u0434\u0438 | trans-title = By train across the Ada Bridge from June | newspaper = Politika | page = 13 | language = Serbian | date = 11 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo Bridge ===\n\nA combined road-rail bridge, proposed as a part of the still unfinished [[Belgrade bypass]]. It will connect the [[Banat]] region of [[Vojvodina]] directly with central Serbia, which would reroute traffic, especially the freight and hazardous transports, from downtown Belgrade to the outer suburban area. Three variants of the bridge were presented in August 2007.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/beograd/tri-varijante-mosta-kod-vince/dt8g2jh | author = D.Dra\u017ei\u0107 | title = Tri varijante mosta kod Vin\u010de | trans-title = Three variants of the Vin\u010da bridge | date = 7 August 2007 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref> In 2012 it was announced that Chinese investors have a project.<ref name=bild>[http://beobuild.rs/forum/viewtopic.php?t=2706#p199422 Drumsko \u017eelezni\u010dki most Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo (Road-railway bridge Vin\u010da-Pan\u010devo, August 2012]</ref> In February 2015 it was confirmed that the Chinese investors will build this bridge, too, with a deadline of 3 years.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.blic.rs/vesti/ekonomija/otkrivamo-kinezi-nam-grade-jos-jedan-most-u-beogradu/zn2hpc9 | author = Mateja Beljan | title = Kinezi nam grade jo\u0161 jedan most u Beogradu  | trans-title = Chinese are building another bridge in Belgrade | date = 28 February 2015 | publisher = Blic | language = Serbian }}</ref> Partial documentation was gathered by September 2015 and in February 2016 the government of Serbia confirmed the construction of the bridge, defining it as a strategic project but labeling the bridge as the \"special problem\".<ref>[http://www.mgsi.gov.rs/lat/projekti/izgradnja-obilazne-pruge-beli-potok-vinca-sa-izgradnjom-drumsko-zeleznickog-mosta-i Ministry of construction, transportation and infrastructure, The project, 17 February 2016]</ref> The bridge will extend from the projected section of the bypass beginning at the interchange of [[Bubanj Potok]] and ending at the suburb of Vin\u010da.<ref name=bild/> On the Pan\u010devo side, the bridge will cross at the village of [[Omoljica]]. The construction of the bridge is directly connected with the completing of the bypass which, as of April 2020, is not even close to be finished.\n\n=== Metro Bridge ===\n [[File:Metro proposal 2018.jpg|right|thumb|250px|Map of the 2018 subway project with crossing over the Sava (red line)]]\n\nThe bridge was conceived in the 1970s as the carrier of the subway system across the Sava (Serbian ''metro'', subway). It was envisioned as the two-leveled bridge, where upper level would be used by the traffic, pedestrians and cyclists, while the lover level would be used by the subway trains. Its planned location was {{convert|80|m|abbr=on}} upstream from the Old Sava Bridge.<ref name=bakic>{{cite web | url = https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=aROvaHiJ4lE&t=10m00s | author = Aleksandar Pavkovi\u0107 | title = Interview: Dragoljub Baki\u0107 - Beograd \u0107e propasti ako ne bude ozbiljnih projekata | trans-title = Interview: Dragoljub Baki\u0107 - Belgrade will collapse if there are no serious projects | date = 18 January 2020 | publisher = Balkan Info | language = Serbian}}</ref> Plans for the entire subway grid were fully finished in 1976 but the construction never began, and in 1982 city decided to scrap the subway plans completely. The idea was revived in the 1990s and the talks of the bridge resurfaced in 1998 but again nothing happened.<ref>{{ cite news | author = Dejan Aleksi\u0107, Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 | title = Metro pola veka na po\u010detnoj stanici | trans-title = Metro still on the starting point after half a century | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 11 February 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/398145/Metro-pola-veka-na-pocetnoj-stanici }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = | first = | author = Marijana Avakumovi\u0107  | title = Metro opet na \u010dekanju | newspaper = [[Politika]] | language = Serbian | date = 30 October 2009 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/109830/Ekonomija/Metro-opet-na-cekanju}}</ref> The latest subway plan from 2018-2019 also includes this bridge and alleges the beginning of the construction in 2020, but since the government changed the grid projects several times, as of April 2020 the project for the new bridge isn't drafted at all and it is not known where it will be located or what it would look like. Even if construction would start in 2020, the line planned to commute over the bridge may not be finished in six years after that, with one city plan giving even 2033 as the year when the line will be finished.<ref>{{ cite web | url = https://www.danas.rs/beograd/rok-se-produzuje-metro-prioritet-tek-za-2027-godinu/ | author = A. Popovi\u0107 | title = Rok se produ\u017euje, metro prioritet tek za 2027. godinu | trans-title = Deadline is extending, metro priority only in 2027 | date = 23 March 2018 | publisher = [[Danas (newspaper)|Danas]] | language = Serbian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Branka Vasiljevi\u0107 | title = Plan za metro \u2013 za dve godine  | trans-title = Plan for the metro - in two years | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 27 June 2018 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/406271/Plan-za-metro-za-dve-godine }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://rs.n1info.com/a399188/Vesti/Sednica-Skupstine-Beograda-o-metrou-i-Vinci.html | author = Emina Kova\u010devi\u0107 | title = Do prve linije metroa ipak te\u0161ko do 2022, ni Vesi\u0107 ne veruje | trans-title = Hardly to the first metro line by 2022, Vesi\u0107 doesn't believe it either | date = 26 June 2018 | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian }}</ref>\n\n=== New Belgrade-Ada Ciganlija Bridge ===\n\nIn March 2020, it was announced that the construction of the first pedestrian-cyclist bridge in Belgrade will commence in 2021. It will connect New Belgrade with the island of Ada Ciganlija across the Sava, as the continuation of the Omladinskih Brigada street in Block 70. Public, partially underground garage with 300 parking spots will be built at the end of the street. This is the second part of the project city administration alleged is the result of citizens' online voting (first part is relocation of the Old Sava Bridge on dry land, in the [[U%C5%A1%C4%87e,_Belgrade#Park_U\u0161\u0107e|Park U\u0161\u0107e]] to become an \"attraction\"). Reporters and public distanced from the voting or debunked it as being rigged.<ref>{{cite news | author = Daliborka Mu\u010dibabi\u0107 |script-title=sr: \u041f\u0435\u0448\u0430\u0447\u043a\u043e-\u0431\u0438\u0446\u0438\u043a\u043b\u0438\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0447\u043a\u0438 \u043c\u043e\u0441\u0442 \u043f\u0440\u0432\u0438 \u0443 \u043f\u0440\u0435\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043d\u0438\u0446\u0438 | trans-title = Pedestrian-cyclist bridge, first in the capital  | newspaper = Politika | page = 14 | language = Serbian | date = 1 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet | author = Dule Astro | user = astrodule | number = 1188190950474108928 | date = 26 October 2019 | language = Serbian | title = Trenutno se de\u0161avaju velike neregularnosti na anketi o sudbini Starog savskog mosta.... | trans-title = Major irregularities are happening at the voting for the future of the Old Sava Bridgge... | link = https://twitter.com/astrodule/status/1188190950474108928}}</ref><ref name=anketa>{{cite news | author = Mladen Savatovi\u0107 | title = Stari savski most - od mosta na Savi do mosta na travi | trans-title = Old Sava Bridge - from bridge on Sava to bridge on grass | publisher = N1 | language = Serbian | date = 19 December 2019 | url = http://rs.n1info.com/Vesti/a553937/Stari-savski-most-od-mosta-na-Savi-do-mosta-na-travi.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news | author = Dejan ALeksi\u0107 | title = Pe\u0161a\u010dko-biciklisti\u010dki most za manje automobila na Adi | trans-title = Pedestrian-bicycle bridge for less cars on Ada | newspaper = Politika | page = 15 | language = Serbian | date = 23 April 2020 | url = http://www.politika.rs/sr/clanak/452804/Pesacko-biciklisticki-most-za-manje-automobila-na-Adi}}</ref>\n\n== Proposed bridges ==\n=== Nemanjina Bridge ===\n [[File:Belgrad street.JPG|right|thumb|100px|Ending of the [[Nemanjina Street]], where the proposed bridge should start]]\n\nThe bridge across the Sava in the extension of the [[Nemanjina Street]] ([[Savamala]], old Belgrade-[[Staro Sajmi\u0161te]], New Belgrade) is considered to be the \"ideal\" missing bridge in Belgrade, due to its location. In the 1970s, the measurements were made, geometric survey was conducted, locations of the pillars were set and in the end, even the project was finished.<ref name=bakic/> However, the construction of such bridge would be extremely difficult as the areas on the river banks are already urbanized. It would take massive demolitions to clear the area and it was concluded it wouldn't be financially wise either. The idea of the bridge on this location, however, keeps popping-up regularly in discussions regarding transportation in Belgrade.<ref name=hajdin>{{cite news | author = Nikola Hajdin (interview with) | title = Most vredi svaki evro | trans-title = The bridge is worth every euro | newspaper = Politika | language = Serbian | date = 10 August 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== Ada Bridge II ===\n\nWhen plans were made for the Ada Bridge, one of the proposals was the location on the opposite, upstream tip of Ada Ciganlija, instead of the downstream one, where it was built in the end. It would connect [[Maki\u0161]] on the right, and [[Savski Nasip]] on the left bank of the Sava.<ref>{{cite news | author = Zoran Majdin | title = \u017dirafa pored gazelle | trans-title = Giraffe next to gazelle | newspaper = Vreme, No. 935 | language = Serbian | date = 4 December 2008 | url = https://www.vreme.com/cms/view.php?id=764160}}</ref> When Ada Bridge was close to be finished, architects suggested this other location as the place where the next Belgrade bridge might or should be built.<ref name=hajdin/>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[List of bridges in Serbia]]\n* [[Transport in Belgrade]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Transport in Belgrade}}\n\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Belgrade]]\n[[Category:Bridges in Belgrade]]\n", "name_user": "PajaBG", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bridges_of_Belgrade"}
{"title_page": "John Mitchell (chemist)", "text_new": "{{short description|American chemist and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John F Mitchell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = Cornell University (BA), University of Chicago (PhD)\n| awards             = University of Chicago Distinguished Performance Award (2006)\n<br>Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (2000)<br /> Department of Energy Early Career Award (1999)\n| organization       = [https://www.anl.gov/ Argonne National Laboratory]\n| website            = https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell\n}}'''John F. Mitchell''' is an American [[chemist]] and researcher. He is the Associate Director<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> of the Materials Science Division at the [[U.S. Department of Energy]]\u2019s (DOE) [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and leads Argonne's Emerging Materials Group.\n\nMitchell's expertise is in the discovery, synthesis, crystal growth, and study of quantum materials, including correlated electron oxides, quantum magnets, and topological matter. He has authored or co-authored over 320 peer-reviewed articles in scholarly journals.\n\nMitchell is an Argonne Distinguished Fellow and is<ref name=\":0\" />  a fellow of the American Physical Society, and a member of the American Physical Society, American Association for the Advancement of Science, and the Materials Research Society.  He served in the Chair line of the Division of Materials Physics of the American Physical Society from 2013\u20132017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMitchell received<ref name=\":0\" />  his A.B. degree ''summa cum laude'' in Chemistry from [[Cornell University]] in 1987, and his Ph.D. in Chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1993 for theoretical studies of defect structures and order-disorder transitions of early transition metal chalcogenides.\n\nMitchell joined<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/system/files/2020-03/Curriculum%20Vitae_03162020.pdf|title=John F Mitchell Curriculum Vitae|url-status=live}}</ref> Argonne as a DOE Distinguished Postdoctoral Fellow in 1993. He went on to become<ref name=\":1\" /> a Senior Chemist in 2009. Mitchell became<ref name=\":1\" /> Associate Director of the Materials Science Division in 2012 and served as Division Director from 2017\u20132019. Mitchell is also an adjunct professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://materials.ucsb.edu/people/adjunct-and-distinguished-faculty/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=materials.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in the Materials Science and Engineering Department of the University of California, Santa Barbara.\n\n==Research==\nMitchell's research focuses on strategic synthesis, crystal growth, and structural studies of correlated electron transition metal oxides and [[chalcogenides]], principally using neutron and x-ray scattering. He has coordinated the development team for a high-resolution powder diffractometer at the Advanced Photon Source, and led Argonne's strategic initiative in Materials and Molecular Design and Discovery. Mitchell has also led a project study in the DOE Center of Excellence for the Synthesis and Processing of Advanced Materials, entitled, \u201cSpin Polarized Transport in Complex Oxides.\u201d\n\nEarly in his career, Mitchell focused on understanding the electronic and magnetic properties of 2D manganese oxides that exhibit colossal magnetoresistance (CMR).  Among several key findings,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Osborn|first2=R.|last3=Argyriou|first3=D.N.|last4=Vasiliu-Doloc|first4=L.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Sinha|first6=S.K.|last7=Ruett|first7=U.|last8=Ling|first8=C.D.|last9=Islam|first9=Z.|last10=Lynn|first10=J.W.|title=Structure of nanoscale polaron correlations in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7,|journal=Phys. Rev. B|date=2002|language=en|volume=65|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.65.014427|arxiv=cond-mat/0106477}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Sun|first=Z.|last2=Chuang|first2=YD.|last3=Fedorov|first3=A.V.|last4=Douglas|first4=J.F.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Reznik|first6=D.|last7=Weber|first7=F.|last8=Aliouane|first8=N.|last9=Argyriou|first9=D.N.|last10=Zheng|first10=H.|last11=Kimura|first11=T.|last12=Tokura|first12=Y|last13=Revcolevschi|first13=A.|last14=Dessau|first14=D.S|title=Quasiparticlelike peaks, kinks, and electron-phonon coupling at the (\u03c0, 0) regions in the CMR oxide La2-2xSr1+2xMn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. lett.|language=en|date=2006|volume=97|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.97.056401|arxiv=cond-mat/0510255}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mannella|first=N.|last2=Yang|first2=W.L.|last3=Zhou|first3=X.J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Zaanen|first6=J.|last7=Devereaux|first7=T.P.|last8=Nagaosa|first8=N.|last9=Hussain|first9=Z.|last10=Shen|first10=Z.X.|title=Polaronic orbital polarization in a layered colossal magnetoresistive manganite|journal=Phys. Rev. B|language=en|date=2003|volume=67|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevB.67.020409}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Sinha|first2=S.K.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Rosenkranz|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Argyriou|first6=D.N.|last7=Vasiliu-Doloc|first7=L.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lynn|first9=J.W.|title=Nodal quasiparticle in pseudogapped colossal magnetoresistive manganites|journal=Nature|language=en|date=2005|volume=438|pages=474\u2013478|DOI=10.1038/nature04273|hdl=1887/5127|hdl-access=free}}</ref> Mitchell's work directly led to the widespread understanding of local polaronic distortions and the \u2018melting\u2019 of their short-range correlations as a mechanism behind the CMR effect.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Vasiliu-Doloc|first=L.|last2=Rosenkranz|first2=S.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Sinha|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Lynn|first6=J.W.|last7=Mesot|first7=J.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lee|first9=W-K|last10=Preosti|first10=G.|last11=Fedro|first11=A.J.|url=https://www.aps.anl.gov/APS-Science-Highlight/2000-06-28/charge-melting-polaron-collapse-in-la12sr18mn207|title=Charge Melting and Polaron Collapse in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.4393}}</ref>\n\nTurning to heavy transition metals, Mitchell explored the behavior of iridium based oxides in which electron correlation and spin-orbit coupling meet on similar energy scales.  Mitchell's group discovered evidence for electronic and magnetic properties in these systems that parallel those found in high-temperature copper oxide superconductors.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Y.K.|last2=Krupin|first2=O.|last3=Denlinger|first3=J.D.|last4=Bostwick|first4=A.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Rotenberg|first6=E.|last7=Zhao|first7=Q.|last8=Allen|first8=J.W.|last9=Kim|first9=B.J.|url=https://www.anl.gov/argonne-scientific-publications/pub/103141|title=Fermi Arcs in a Doped Pseudospin-1/2 Heisenberg Antiferromagnet|journal=Science|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|issn=0036-8075|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1126/science.1251151|arxiv=1406.4489}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Jungho|last2=Casa|first2=D.|last3=Upton|first3=1 M. H.|last4=Gog|first4=T.|last5=Kim|first5=Young-June|last6=Veenendaal|first6=M. van|last7=Daghofer|first7=M.|last8=van den Brink|first8=J.|last9=Khaliullin|first9=G.|last10=Kim|first10=B.J.|title=Magnetic Excitation Spectra of Sr2IrO4 Probed by Resonant Inelastic X-Ray Scattering: Establishing Links to Cuprate Superconductors|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett|language=en|date=2012|volume=108|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>  Mitchell's group also found direct evidence of bond-directional anisotropy in the candidate quantum spin liquid Na<sub>2</sub>IrO<sub>3</sub>, validating the dominant role of this interaction.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Chun|first=S.H.|last2=Kim|first2=J-W|last3=Kim|first3=J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Malliakas|first5=C.|last6=Stoumpos|first6=C.|last7=Mehlawat|first7=K.|last8=Singh|first8=Y.|last9=Choi|first9=Y.|last10=Gog|first10=T.|last11=Al-Zein|first11=A.|last12=Moretti Sala|first12=M.|last13=Krisch|first13=M.|last14=Chaloupka|first14=J.|last15=Jackeli|first15=G.|last16=Khaliullin|first16=G.|last17=Kim|first17=B.J.|last18=Mitchel|first18=J.F|title=Direct Evidence for Dominant Bond-directional Interactions in a Honeycomb Lattice Iridate Na2IrO3|journal=Nature Physics|language=en|date=2015|volume=11|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMitchell then discovered routes to grow single crystals of two-dimensional nickel oxides that, like the iridium systems, mimic cuprate superconductors.  In a series of papers he and his group showed that these nickel oxides exhibit stripe phases, intertwined density waves, and strong in-plane orbital polarization believed to be key to superconductivity.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Pajerowski|first2=D.|last3=Botana|first3=A.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Harriger|first5=L.|last6=Rodriguez-Rivera|first6=J.|last7=Ruff|first7=J.|last8=Schreiber|first8=N.|last9=Wang|first9=B.|last10=Chen|first10=Y.|last11=Chen|first11=W.|last12=Norman|first12=M.|last13=Rosenkranz|first13=S.|last14=Phelan|first14=D.|last15=Mitchel|first15=J.F|title=Spin Stripe Order in a Square Planar Trilayer Nickelate|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=2019|volume=122|issue=24|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.122.247201|arxiv=1903.03246}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Shen|first2=Y.S.|last3=Norman|first3=M.R.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|title=Stacked charge stripes in the trilayer nickelate La4Ni3O8|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.|language=en|date=2016|volume=113|issue=32|pages=8945\u20138950|issn=1091-6490|DOI=10.1073/pnas.1606637113|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Botana|first2=A.S.|last3=Freeland|first3=J.W.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|last6=Phelan|first6=D|last7=Pardo|first7=V|last8=Norman|first8=M.|title=Large Orbital Polarization in a Metallic Square-Planar Nickelate|journal=Nature Physics |language=en|date=2017|volume=13|pages=864\u2013869|issn=1745-2481|DOI=10.1038/nphys4149|arxiv=1705.00563}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*Argonne Distinguished Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/pse/awards-recognition|title=Physical Sciences and Engineering Awards and Recognition|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the American Physical Society<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=&unit_id=&institution=Argonne+National+Laboratory|title=APS Fellow Archive|website=www.www.aps.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Member of the American Physical Society, American Crystallographic Society, Materials Research Society, and American Chemical Society\n*Former fellow of the University of Chicago Institute for Molecular Engineering, 2015-2017\n*[[Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers]], 2000\n*Department of Energy Outstanding Young Investigator Award, 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov/WH/EOP/OSTP/html/00413_2.html|title=President honors outstanding young scientist|website=clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, John}}\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American chemist and researcher}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = John F Mitchell\n| image              = \n| caption            = \n| alma_mater         = Cornell University (BA), University of Chicago (PhD)\n| awards             = University of Chicago Distinguished Performance Award (2006)\n<br>Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers (2000)<br /> Department of Energy Early Career Award (1999)\n| organization       = [https://www.anl.gov/ Argonne National Laboratory]\n| website            = https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell\n}}'''John F. Mitchell''' is an American [[chemist]] and researcher. He is the Associate Director<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/profile/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> of the Materials Science Division at the [[U.S. Department of Energy]]\u2019s (DOE) [[Argonne National Laboratory]] and leads Argonne's Emerging Materials Group.\n\nMitchell's expertise is in the discovery, synthesis, crystal growth, and study of quantum materials, including correlated electron oxides, quantum magnets, and topological matter. He has authored or co-authored over 320 peer-reviewed articles in scholarly journals.\n\nMitchell is an Argonne Distinguished Fellow and is<ref name=\":0\" />  a fellow of the American Physical Society, and a member of the American Physical Society, American Association for the Advancement of Science, and the Materials Research Society.  He served in the Chair line of the Division of Materials Physics of the American Physical Society from 2013\u20132017.\n\n==Early life and education==\nMitchell received<ref name=\":0\" />  his A.B. degree ''summa cum laude'' in Chemistry from [[Cornell University]] in 1987, and his Ph.D. in Chemistry from the University of Chicago in 1993 for theoretical studies of defect structures and order-disorder transitions of early transition metal chalcogenides.\n\nMitchell joined<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/system/files/2020-03/Curriculum%20Vitae_03162020.pdf|title=John F Mitchell Curriculum Vitae|url-status=live}}</ref> Argonne as a DOE Distinguished Postdoctoral Fellow in 1993. He went on to become<ref name=\":1\" /> a Senior Chemist in 2009. Mitchell became<ref name=\":1\" /> Associate Director of the Materials Science Division in 2012 and served as Division Director from 2017\u20132019. Mitchell is also an adjunct professor<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://materials.ucsb.edu/people/adjunct-and-distinguished-faculty/john-mitchell|title=John Mitchell|website=materials.ucsb.edu|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref> in the Materials Science and Engineering Department of the University of California, Santa Barbara.\n\n==Research==\nMitchell's research focuses on strategic synthesis, crystal growth, and structural studies of correlated electron transition metal oxides and [[chalcogenides]], principally using neutron and x-ray scattering. He has coordinated the development team for a high-resolution powder diffractometer at the Advanced Photon Source, and led Argonne's strategic initiative in Materials and Molecular Design and Discovery. Mitchell has also led a project study in the DOE Center of Excellence for the Synthesis and Processing of Advanced Materials, entitled, \u201cSpin Polarized Transport in Complex Oxides.\u201d\n\nEarly in his career, Mitchell focused on understanding the electronic and magnetic properties of 2D manganese oxides that exhibit colossal magnetoresistance (CMR).  Among several key findings,<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Osborn|first2=R.|last3=Argyriou|first3=D.N.|last4=Vasiliu-Doloc|first4=L.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Sinha|first6=S.K.|last7=Ruett|first7=U.|last8=Ling|first8=C.D.|last9=Islam|first9=Z.|last10=Lynn|first10=J.W.|title=Structure of nanoscale polaron correlations in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7,|journal=Phys. Rev. B|date=2002|language=en|volume=65|doi=10.1103/PhysRevB.65.014427|arxiv=cond-mat/0106477}}</ref><ref name=\":4\">{{Cite journal|last=Sun|first=Z.|last2=Chuang|first2=YD.|last3=Fedorov|first3=A.V.|last4=Douglas|first4=J.F.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Reznik|first6=D.|last7=Weber|first7=F.|last8=Aliouane|first8=N.|last9=Argyriou|first9=D.N.|last10=Zheng|first10=H.|last11=Kimura|first11=T.|last12=Tokura|first12=Y|last13=Revcolevschi|first13=A.|last14=Dessau|first14=D.S|title=Quasiparticlelike peaks, kinks, and electron-phonon coupling at the (\u03c0, 0) regions in the CMR oxide La2-2xSr1+2xMn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. lett.|language=en|date=2006|volume=97|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.97.056401|arxiv=cond-mat/0510255}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Mannella|first=N.|last2=Yang|first2=W.L.|last3=Zhou|first3=X.J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Zaanen|first6=J.|last7=Devereaux|first7=T.P.|last8=Nagaosa|first8=N.|last9=Hussain|first9=Z.|last10=Shen|first10=Z.X.|title=Polaronic orbital polarization in a layered colossal magnetoresistive manganite|journal=Phys. Rev. B|language=en|date=2003|volume=67|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevB.67.020409}}</ref><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last=Campbell|first=B.J.|last2=Sinha|first2=S.K.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Rosenkranz|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Argyriou|first6=D.N.|last7=Vasiliu-Doloc|first7=L.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lynn|first9=J.W.|title=Nodal quasiparticle in pseudogapped colossal magnetoresistive manganites|journal=Nature|language=en|date=2005|volume=438|pages=474\u2013478|DOI=10.1038/nature04273|hdl=1887/5127|hdl-access=free}}</ref> Mitchell's work directly led to the widespread understanding of local polaronic distortions and the \u2018melting\u2019 of their short-range correlations as a mechanism behind the CMR effect.<ref name=\":7\">{{Cite journal|last=Vasiliu-Doloc|first=L.|last2=Rosenkranz|first2=S.|last3=Osborn|first3=R.|last4=Sinha|first4=S.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Lynn|first6=J.W.|last7=Mesot|first7=J.|last8=Seeck|first8=O.H.|last9=Lee|first9=W-K|last10=Preosti|first10=G.|last11=Fedro|first11=A.J.|url=https://www.aps.anl.gov/APS-Science-Highlight/2000-06-28/charge-melting-polaron-collapse-in-la12sr18mn207|title=Charge Melting and Polaron Collapse in La1.2Sr1.8Mn2O7|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.83.4393}}</ref>\n\nTurning to heavy transition metals, Mitchell explored the behavior of iridium based oxides in which electron correlation and spin-orbit coupling meet on similar energy scales.  Mitchell's group discovered evidence for electronic and magnetic properties in these systems that parallel those found in high-temperature copper oxide superconductors.<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Y.K.|last2=Krupin|first2=O.|last3=Denlinger|first3=J.D.|last4=Bostwick|first4=A.|last5=Mitchell|first5=J.F.|last6=Rotenberg|first6=E.|last7=Zhao|first7=Q.|last8=Allen|first8=J.W.|last9=Kim|first9=B.J.|url=https://www.anl.gov/argonne-scientific-publications/pub/103141|title=Fermi Arcs in a Doped Pseudospin-1/2 Heisenberg Antiferromagnet|journal=Science|language=en|date=1999|volume=83|issue=21|issn=0036-8075|pages=4393\u20134396|DOI=10.1126/science.1251151|arxiv=1406.4489}}</ref><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Kim|first=Jungho|last2=Casa|first2=D.|last3=Upton|first3=1 M. H.|last4=Gog|first4=T.|last5=Kim|first5=Young-June|last6=Veenendaal|first6=M. van|last7=Daghofer|first7=M.|last8=van den Brink|first8=J.|last9=Khaliullin|first9=G.|last10=Kim|first10=B.J.|title=Magnetic Excitation Spectra of Sr2IrO4 Probed by Resonant Inelastic X-Ray Scattering: Establishing Links to Cuprate Superconductors|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett|language=en|date=2012|volume=108|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>  Mitchell's group also found direct evidence of bond-directional anisotropy in the candidate quantum spin liquid Na<sub>2</sub>IrO<sub>3</sub>, validating the dominant role of this interaction.<ref name=\":10\">{{Cite journal|last=Chun|first=S.H.|last2=Kim|first2=J-W|last3=Kim|first3=J.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Malliakas|first5=C.|last6=Stoumpos|first6=C.|last7=Mehlawat|first7=K.|last8=Singh|first8=Y.|last9=Choi|first9=Y.|last10=Gog|first10=T.|last11=Al-Zein|first11=A.|last12=Moretti Sala|first12=M.|last13=Krisch|first13=M.|last14=Chaloupka|first14=J.|last15=Jackeli|first15=G.|last16=Khaliullin|first16=G.|last17=Kim|first17=B.J.|last18=Mitchel|first18=J.F|title=Direct Evidence for Dominant Bond-directional Interactions in a Honeycomb Lattice Iridate Na2IrO3|journal=Nature Physics|language=en|date=2015|volume=11|issue=17|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.108.177003|doi-access=free}}</ref>\n\nMitchell then discovered routes to grow single crystals of two-dimensional nickel oxides that, like the iridium systems, mimic cuprate superconductors.  In a series of papers he and his group showed that these nickel oxides exhibit stripe phases, intertwined density waves, and strong in-plane orbital polarization believed to be key to superconductivity.<ref name=\":11\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Pajerowski|first2=D.|last3=Botana|first3=A.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Harriger|first5=L.|last6=Rodriguez-Rivera|first6=J.|last7=Ruff|first7=J.|last8=Schreiber|first8=N.|last9=Wang|first9=B.|last10=Chen|first10=Y.|last11=Chen|first11=W.|last12=Norman|first12=M.|last13=Rosenkranz|first13=S.|last14=Phelan|first14=D.|last15=Mitchel|first15=J.F|title=Spin Stripe Order in a Square Planar Trilayer Nickelate|journal=Phys. Rev. Lett.|language=en|date=2019|volume=122|issue=24|issn=1079-7114|DOI=10.1103/PhysRevLett.122.247201|arxiv=1903.03246}}</ref><ref name=\":12\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Shen|first2=Y.S.|last3=Norman|first3=M.R.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|title=Stacked charge stripes in the trilayer nickelate La4Ni3O8|journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci.|language=en|date=2016|volume=113|issue=32|pages=8945\u20138950|issn=1091-6490|DOI=10.1073/pnas.1606637113|doi-access=free}}</ref><ref name=\":13\">{{Cite journal|last=Zhang|first=J.|last2=Botana|first2=A.S.|last3=Freeland|first3=J.W.|last4=Zheng|first4=H.|last5=Mitchel|first5=J.F|last6=Phelan|first6=D|last7=Pardo|first7=V|last8=Norman|first8=M.|title=Large Orbital Polarization in a Metallic Square-Planar Nickelate|journal=Nature Physics |language=en|date=2017|volume=13|pages=864\u2013869|issn=1745-2481|DOI=10.1038/nphys4149|arxiv=1705.00563}}</ref>\n\n==Honors and awards==\n*Argonne Distinguished Fellow<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.anl.gov/pse/awards-recognition|title=Physical Sciences and Engineering Awards and Recognition|website=www.anl.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Fellow of the American Physical Society<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.aps.org/programs/honors/fellowships/archive-all.cfm?initial=&year=&unit_id=&institution=Argonne+National+Laboratory|title=APS Fellow Archive|website=www.www.aps.org|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*Member of the American Physical Society, American Crystallographic Society, Materials Research Society, and American Chemical Society\n*Former fellow of the University of Chicago Institute for Molecular Engineering, 2015-2017\n*[[Presidential Early Career Award for Scientists and Engineers]], 2000\n*Department of Energy Outstanding Young Investigator Award, 1999.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov/WH/EOP/OSTP/html/00413_2.html|title=President honors outstanding young scientist|website=clintonwhitehouse4.archives.gov|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mitchell, John}}\n[[Category:Cornell University alumni]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:American chemists]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eReferences:add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Mitchell_(chemist)"}
{"title_page": "Hole.io", "text_new": "\n\nLm\n\n\n\nM\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\n\nM\n| title = Hole.io\n| image = Hole.io logo.jpg\n| developer = [[Voodoo (company)|Voodoo]]\n| publisher = Voodoo\n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| released = 2018\n| genre = [[Arcade game|Arcade]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer]], [[single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Hole.io''''' is a 2018 [[arcade game|arcade]] [[Puzzle video game#Physics game|physics puzzle game]] with [[battle royale game|battle royale]] mechanics created by French studio [[Voodoo (company)|Voodoo]] for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]].\n\nPlayers control a [[black hole]] moving around an urban area. By consuming various objects, holes will increase in size, allowing players to consume larger objects as well as smaller players.\n\nThe game was received positively by critics and took the top spot in the free apps section on the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] and on [[Google Play]]. Some critics however, characterized the game as a [[video game clone|clone]] of the 2018 independent game ''[[Donut County]]''. It has also been criticized for being promoted as a multiplayer game when in fact the other \"players\" are computer controlled [[Non-player character|NPC]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/mobile-gaming-fake-multiplayer-epidemic-jonathan-jungck |title=Mobile Gaming: The Fake Multiplayer Epidemic |last=Jungck |first=Johnathan |date=August 1, 2018 |website=www.linkedin.com |language=en |access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Hole.io'' combines several [[game mechanics|gameplay mechanics]]. In Classic mode, the player's objective is to become the largest black hole by the end of a two minute round by travelling around the area and consuming trees, humans, cars and other objects which fall into the black hole if appropriately sized.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\">{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/hole-io-review-bright-colourful-game-player-with-biggest-black-hole-wins/articleshow/65369436.cms |title=Hole.io review: Bright, colourful game; player with biggest black hole wins |last=Bhagat |first=Hitesh Raj |date=2018-08-11 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref> Gradually the hole becomes larger and capable of sucking in buildings and smaller black holes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> If an object is too big it will not fall in and might block the way preventing other objects from going through. Players need to utilize the game's real time physics to their advantage and optimize their path for effective growth.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> Other black holes can consume the player's hole  resulting in \"death\" and [[respawning]] several seconds later.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/wikis/hole-io/Tips_and_Tricks/#General_Strategies |title=Hole.io Tips and Tricks |date=2 July 2018 |work=[[IGN]]}}</ref>\n\n\"Battle\" mode is a [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] mode that pits players against each other with the goal of being the last hole standing. While players can still consume the environment, the goal is to eliminate all other holes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" />\n\nBoth Classic and \"Battle\" mode are not played against players, but rather computers. Additionally, a solo mode exists which allows players to play alone with the goal of consuming as close to 100% of the city within two minutes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> The simple mechanics of the game put it in the hyper-casual genre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mobileindustryeye.com/featured/the-monumental-rise-of-hyper-casual-games/ |title=The monumental rise of hyper-casual games |publisher=Mobile Industry Eye}}</ref>\n\nPlayers are awarded points at the end of each round that count toward their level. Each level unlocks new [[Skin (video gaming)|skins]] to customize the hole's appearance. Other skins can also be unlocked by performing certain tasks within the game.\n\n== Comparison to ''Donut County'' ==\n''[[Donut County]]'' is a 2018 independent video game that was in development for at least six years before its release on 28 August 2018, sparking allegations by that game's developer that Voodoo copied his idea.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/day6/episode-397-journalism-and-black-communities-scott-thompson-video-game-clones-iceland-s-dna-and-more-1.4733558/maker-of-donut-county-is-shocked-when-a-free-knock-off-beats-his-game-to-the-market-1.4734793 |title=Maker of Donut County is shocked when a free knock-off beats his game to the market |last=Ore |first=Jonathan |date=6 July 2018 |work=CBC |access-date=15 November 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Both games use the same mechanic of a hole in the ground swallowing objects to grow bigger; however, ''Donut County'' additionally features a storyline and a cast of characters which ''Hole.io'' lacks.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\" /> Conversely, ''Hole.io'' adds multiplayer features and a cityscape.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\" /> According to ''Variety'', ''Hole.io''<nowiki/>'s developer Voodoo's entire range of games consists of clones of other games and Voodoo managed to secure a $200 million investment from [[Goldman Sachs]] shortly after releasing ''Hole.io''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/features/donut-county-hole-io-apple-1202866615/ |title=Goldman Sachs-Backed Cloner Uses War Chest, Ad Buys to Overshadow Original Games |last=Futter |first=Michael |date=2018-07-06 |work=Variety |access-date=2018-11-15 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSoon after its release, ''Hole.io'' made it to the top of the free games section on the Apps Store<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/6/25/17501882/donut-county-game-knockoff-ben-esposito-holeio |title=Donut County lookalike is number one on the App Store |last=Radulovic |first=Petrana |date=6 July 2018 |website=Polygon}}</ref> and Google Play,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://appsamurai.com/mobile-app-success-story-hole-io/ |title=Mobile App Success Story: Hole.io |last=Ta\u015f |first=Yunus |date=18 July 2018 |website=AppSamurai}}</ref> receiving over 10 million downloads on Google Play alone.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=io.voodoo.holeio&hl=en |title=Hole.io on Google Play |date=2 July 2018 |website=IGN}}</ref>\n\nWhile some reviewers criticized it for copying core mechanics of ''[[Donut County]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/clever-indie-game-donut-county-isnt-even-out-yet-and-al-1827117824 |title=Indie Games Are Getting Cloned Before They're Even Out |last=D'Anastasio |first=Cecilia |date=6 June 2018 |website=Kotaku}}</ref> others characterized the game as being \"oddly satisfying and addictive\".<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> However, many players often lose interest after realizing that the game is only playable against bots. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IoGames/comments/91zwow/holeios_multiplayer_is_fake/ |title=Reddit |date=2 July 2018 |website=Reddit}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Battle royale games]]\n[[Category:Video game clones]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in France]]\n[[Category:.io video games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox video game\n| title = Hole.io\n| image = Hole.io logo.jpg\n| developer = [[Voodoo (company)|Voodoo]]\n| publisher = Voodoo\n| platforms = [[Android (operating system)|Android]], [[iOS]]\n| released = 2018\n| genre = [[Arcade game|Arcade]]\n| modes = [[Multiplayer]], [[single-player]]\n}}\n'''''Hole.io''''' is a 2018 [[arcade game|arcade]] [[Puzzle video game#Physics game|physics puzzle game]] with [[battle royale game|battle royale]] mechanics created by French studio [[Voodoo (company)|Voodoo]] for [[Android (operating system)|Android]] and [[iOS]].\n\nPlayers control a [[black hole]] moving around an urban area. By consuming various objects, holes will increase in size, allowing players to consume larger objects as well as smaller players.\n\nThe game was received positively by critics and took the top spot in the free apps section on the [[App Store (iOS)|App Store]] and on [[Google Play]]. Some critics however, characterized the game as a [[video game clone|clone]] of the 2018 independent game ''[[Donut County]]''. It has also been criticized for being promoted as a multiplayer game when in fact the other \"players\" are computer controlled [[Non-player character|NPC]]<nowiki/>s.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.linkedin.com/pulse/mobile-gaming-fake-multiplayer-epidemic-jonathan-jungck |title=Mobile Gaming: The Fake Multiplayer Epidemic |last=Jungck |first=Johnathan |date=August 1, 2018 |website=www.linkedin.com |language=en |access-date=2019-04-03}}</ref>\n\n==Gameplay==\n''Hole.io'' combines several [[game mechanics|gameplay mechanics]]. In Classic mode, the player's objective is to become the largest black hole by the end of a two minute round by travelling around the area and consuming trees, humans, cars and other objects which fall into the black hole if appropriately sized.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\">{{Cite news |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/magazines/panache/hole-io-review-bright-colourful-game-player-with-biggest-black-hole-wins/articleshow/65369436.cms |title=Hole.io review: Bright, colourful game; player with biggest black hole wins |last=Bhagat |first=Hitesh Raj |date=2018-08-11 |work=The Economic Times |access-date=2018-11-15}}</ref> Gradually the hole becomes larger and capable of sucking in buildings and smaller black holes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> If an object is too big it will not fall in and might block the way preventing other objects from going through. Players need to utilize the game's real time physics to their advantage and optimize their path for effective growth.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> Other black holes can consume the player's hole  resulting in \"death\" and [[respawning]] several seconds later.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.ign.com/wikis/hole-io/Tips_and_Tricks/#General_Strategies |title=Hole.io Tips and Tricks |date=2 July 2018 |work=[[IGN]]}}</ref>\n\n\"Battle\" mode is a [[Battle royale game|battle royale]] mode that pits players against each other with the goal of being the last hole standing. While players can still consume the environment, the goal is to eliminate all other holes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" />\n\nBoth Classic and \"Battle\" mode are not played against players, but rather computers. Additionally, a solo mode exists which allows players to play alone with the goal of consuming as close to 100% of the city within two minutes.<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> The simple mechanics of the game put it in the hyper-casual genre.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mobileindustryeye.com/featured/the-monumental-rise-of-hyper-casual-games/ |title=The monumental rise of hyper-casual games |publisher=Mobile Industry Eye}}</ref>\n\nPlayers are awarded points at the end of each round that count toward their level. Each level unlocks new [[Skin (video gaming)|skins]] to customize the hole's appearance. Other skins can also be unlocked by performing certain tasks within the game.\n\n== Comparison to ''Donut County'' ==\n''[[Donut County]]'' is a 2018 independent video game that was in development for at least six years before its release on 28 August 2018, sparking allegations by that game's developer that Voodoo copied his idea.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\">{{Cite news |url=https://www.cbc.ca/radio/day6/episode-397-journalism-and-black-communities-scott-thompson-video-game-clones-iceland-s-dna-and-more-1.4733558/maker-of-donut-county-is-shocked-when-a-free-knock-off-beats-his-game-to-the-market-1.4734793 |title=Maker of Donut County is shocked when a free knock-off beats his game to the market |last=Ore |first=Jonathan |date=6 July 2018 |work=CBC |access-date=15 November 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> Both games use the same mechanic of a hole in the ground swallowing objects to grow bigger; however, ''Donut County'' additionally features a storyline and a cast of characters which ''Hole.io'' lacks.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\" /> Conversely, ''Hole.io'' adds multiplayer features and a cityscape.<ref name=\"Ore 2018\" /> According to ''Variety'', ''Hole.io''<nowiki/>'s developer Voodoo's entire range of games consists of clones of other games and Voodoo managed to secure a $200 million investment from [[Goldman Sachs]] shortly after releasing ''Hole.io''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/features/donut-county-hole-io-apple-1202866615/ |title=Goldman Sachs-Backed Cloner Uses War Chest, Ad Buys to Overshadow Original Games |last=Futter |first=Michael |date=2018-07-06 |work=Variety |access-date=2018-11-15 |language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Reception==\nSoon after its release, ''Hole.io'' made it to the top of the free games section on the Apps Store<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.polygon.com/2018/6/25/17501882/donut-county-game-knockoff-ben-esposito-holeio |title=Donut County lookalike is number one on the App Store |last=Radulovic |first=Petrana |date=6 July 2018 |website=Polygon}}</ref> and Google Play,<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://appsamurai.com/mobile-app-success-story-hole-io/ |title=Mobile App Success Story: Hole.io |last=Ta\u015f |first=Yunus |date=18 July 2018 |website=AppSamurai}}</ref> receiving over 10 million downloads on Google Play alone.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://play.google.com/store/apps/details?id=io.voodoo.holeio&hl=en |title=Hole.io on Google Play |date=2 July 2018 |website=IGN}}</ref>\n\nWhile some reviewers criticized it for copying core mechanics of ''[[Donut County]]'',<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://kotaku.com/clever-indie-game-donut-county-isnt-even-out-yet-and-al-1827117824 |title=Indie Games Are Getting Cloned Before They're Even Out |last=D'Anastasio |first=Cecilia |date=6 June 2018 |website=Kotaku}}</ref> others characterized the game as being \"oddly satisfying and addictive\".<ref name=\"Bhagat 2018\" /> However, many players often lose interest after realizing that the game is only playable against bots. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.reddit.com/r/IoGames/comments/91zwow/holeios_multiplayer_is_fake/ |title=Reddit |date=2 July 2018 |website=Reddit}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:2018 video games]]\n[[Category:Android (operating system) games]]\n[[Category:IOS games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Battle royale games]]\n[[Category:Video game clones]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in France]]\n[[Category:.io video games]]\n", "name_user": "2600:8803:7b00:8600:f850:826f:b285:3c58", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(Lm)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hole.io"}
{"title_page": "2023 NFL Draft", "text_new": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=2023 NFL Draft|timestamp=20200424200629|year=2020|month=April|day=24|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=2023 NFL Draft|date=24 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox sports draft|name=2023 NFL Draft|logo=|logosize=|logoalt=|image=|imagesize=|alt=|caption=|date=TBD|time=|location=[[Kansas City, Missouri]]|network=|sponsor=|league=[[National Football League|NFL]]|first=|first_round=|fewest=|fewnum=|most=|mostnum=|overall=|prev=[[2022 NFL Draft|2022]]|next=[[2024 NFL Draft|2024]]|rounds=7|mr_irrelevant=|hofnum=}}The '''2023 NFL Draft''' will be the 88th annual meeting of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) franchises to select newly eligible players. It will be held in [[Kansas City, Missouri]].\n\n== Host City Bid Prcocess ==\nOn May 22, 2019 during the NFL Spring League Meeting, the host cities for the 2021 and 2023 NFL Draft were chosen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001031662/article/nfl-awards-2021-2023-drafts-to-cleveland-kansas-city|title=NFL awards 2021, 2023 drafts to Cleveland, Kansas City|date=May 22, 2019|publisher=National Football League|website=NFL.com}}</ref> Cleveland and Kansas City were announced as the hosts for 2021 and 2023 respectively. Both cities were finalists to host the 2020 NFL Draft, however Las Vegas was selected instead. Upon Denver withdrawing from their bid, Cleveland and Kansas City were the final 2 remaining. Cleveland was voted upon for the 2021 NFL Draft and Kansas City was given 2023.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NFL drafts}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League Draft]]\n[[Category:21st century in Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Events in Kansas City, Missouri]]\n", "text_old": "<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the discussion has been closed. -->\n{{Article for deletion/dated|page=2023 NFL Draft|timestamp=20200424200629|year=2020|month=April|day=24|substed=yes|help=off}}\n<!-- Once discussion is closed, please place on talk page: {{Old AfD multi|page=2023 NFL Draft|date=24 April 2020|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n{{Infobox sports draft|name=2023 NFL Draft|logo=|logosize=|logoalt=|image=|imagesize=|alt=|caption=|date=TBD|time=|location=[[Kansas City, Missouri]]|network=|sponsor=|league=[[National Football League|NFL]]|first=|first_round=|fewest=|fewnum=|most=|mostnum=|overall=|prev=[[2022 NFL Draft|2022]]|next=[[2024 NFL Draft|2024]]|rounds=7|mr_irrelevant=|hofnum=}}The '''2023 NFL Draft''' will be the 88th annual meeting of the [[National Football League]] (NFL) franchises to select newly eligible players. It will be held in [[Kansas City, Missouri]].\n\n== Host City Bid Prcocess ==\nOn May 22, 2019 during the NFL Spring League Meeting, the host cities for the 2021 and 2023 NFL Draft were chosen.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001031662/article/nfl-awards-2021-2023-drafts-to-cleveland-kansas-city|title=NFL awards 2021, 2023 drafts to Cleveland, Kansas City|date=May 22, 2019|publisher=National Football League|website=NFL.com}}</ref> Cleveland and Kansas City were announced as the hosts for 2021 and 2023 respectively. Both cities were finalists to host the 2020 NFL Draft, however Las Vegas was selected instead. Upon Denver withdrawing from their bid, Cleveland and Kansas City were the final 2 remaining. Cleveland was voted upon for the 2021 NFL Draft and Kansas City was given 2023.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{NFL drafts}}\n\n[[Category:National Football League Draft]]\n[[Category:2023 in Kansas City]]\n[[Category:21st century in Kansas City, Missouri]]\n[[Category:American football in Kansas City]]\n[[Category:Events in Kansas City, Missouri]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "-Category:2023 in Kansas City; -Category:American football in Kansas CityusingHotCat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2023_NFL_Draft"}
{"title_page": "Multimodal interaction", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Mode (user interface)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=May 2009}}\n{{lead too short|date=October 2009}}\n{{confusing|date=October 2009}}\n}}\n\n'''Multimodal interaction''' provides the user with multiple modes of interacting with a system. A '''multimodal''' interface provides several distinct tools for [[input and output]] of data. For example, a multimodal [[Question answering|question answering system]] employs multiple [[Modality (human\u2013computer interaction)|modalities]] (such as text and photo) at both question (input) and answer (output) level.<ref>Mittal et al. (2011). \"[https://www.academia.edu/2475776 Versatile question answering systems: seeing in synthesis]\", International Journal of Intelligent Information Database Systems, 5(2), 119-142.</ref>\n\n== Introduction ==\nMultimodal human-computer interaction refers to the \"interaction with the virtual and physical environment through natural modes of communication\",<ref>Bourguet, M.L.( 2003). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.98.1958&rep=rep1&type=pdf Designing and Prototyping Multimodal Commands]\". Proceedings of Human-Computer Interaction (INTERACT'03), pp. 717-720.</ref> This implies that multimodal interaction enables a more free and natural communication, interfacing users with automated systems in both input and output.<ref>Stivers, T., Sidnell, J. Introduction: Multimodal interaction. Semiotica, 156(1/4), pp. 1-20. 2005.</ref> Specifically, multimodal systems can offer a flexible, efficient and usable environment allowing users to interact through input modalities, such as [[speech recognition|speech]], [[handwriting recognition|handwriting]], [[gesture recognition|hand gesture]] and [[eye tracking|gaze]], and to receive information by the system through output modalities, such as speech synthesis, smart graphics and other modalities, opportunely combined. Then a multimodal system has to recognize the inputs from the different modalities combining them according to temporal and contextual constraints<ref name=\"Caschera1\">Caschera M. C., Ferri F., Grifoni P. (2007). \"[https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1358498 Multimodal interaction systems: information and time features]\".  International Journal of Web and Grid Services (IJWGS), Vol. 3 - Issue 1, pp 82-99.</ref> in order to allow their interpretation. This process is known as multimodal fusion, and it is the object of several research works from nineties to now.<ref name=\"Dulizia2\">D'Ulizia,  A.,  Ferri, F. and  Grifoni,  P. (2010). \"Generating Multimodal Grammars for Multimodal Dialogue Processing\".  IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man and Cybernetics, Part A: Systems and Humans, Vol 40, no 6, pp. 1130 \u2013 1145.</ref><ref name=\"Dulizia1\">D'Ulizia , A. (2009). \"[https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/20dd/37bf8c9f2f9b5e07efcf6441b2890c393192.pdf Exploring Multimodal Input Fusion Strategies]\". In: Grifoni P (ed) Handbook of Research on Multimodal Human Computer Interaction and Pervasive Services: Evolutionary Techniques for Improving Accessibility. IGI Publishing, pp. 34-57.</ref><ref name=\"Sun\">Sun, Y., Shi, Y., Chen,  F. and Chung , V.(2007). \"An Efficient Multimodal Language Processor for Parallel Input Strings in Multimodal Input Fusion,\" in Proc. of the international Conference on Semantic Computing, pp. 389-396.</ref><ref name=\"Russ\">Russ, G., Sallans, B., Hareter, H. (2005). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.94.4023&rep=rep1&type=pdf Semantic Based Information Fusion in a Multimodal Interface]\". International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCI'05), Las Vegas, Nevada, USA, 20\u201323 June, pp 94-100.</ref><ref name=\"Corradini\">Corradini, A., Mehta M., Bernsen, N.O., Martin, J.-C. (2003). \"Multimodal Input Fusion in Human-Computer Interaction on the Example of the on-going NICE Project\". In Proceedings of the NATO-ASI conference on Data Fusion for Situation Monitoring, Incident Detection, Alert and Response Management, Yerevan, Armenia.</ref><ref name=\"Pavlovic\">Pavlovic, V.I., Berry, G.A., Huang, T.S. (1997). \"[https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/647399/ Integration of audio/visual information for use in human-computer intelligent interaction]\". Proceedings of the 1997 International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP '97), Volume 1, pp. 121-124.</ref><ref name=\"Andre\">Andre, M., Popescu, V.G., Shaikh, A., Medl, A., Marsic, I., Kulikowski, C., Flanagan J.L. (1998). \"[http://www.cvauni.edu.vn/imgupload_dinhkem/file/Chuyen%20De%20HCI/11_%20Integration%20of%20Speech%20and%20Gesture%20for%20Multimodal%20HCI.pdf Integration of Speech and Gesture for Multimodal Human-Computer Interaction]\". In Second International Conference on Cooperative Multimodal Communication. 28\u201330 January, Tilburg, The Netherlands.</ref><ref name=\"Vo\">Vo, M.T., Wood, C. (1996). \"Building an application framework for speech and pen input integration in multimodal learning interfaces\". In Proceedings of the Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing (ICASSP'96), May 7\u201310, IEEE Computer Society, Volume 06, pp. 3545-3548.</ref> The fused inputs are interpreted by the system.  Naturalness and flexibility can produce more than one interpretation for each different modality (channel) and for their simultaneous use, and they consequently can produce multimodal ambiguity<ref name=\"Caschera5\">Caschera, M.C. , Ferri, F. , Grifoni, P. (2013). \"[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1704.02841 From Modal to Multimodal Ambiguities: a Classification Approach]\", Journal of Next Generation Information Technology  (JNIT), Vol. 4, No. 5, pp. 87 -109.</ref> generally due to imprecision, noises or other similar factors.  For solving ambiguities, several methods have been proposed.<ref name=\"Caschera2\">Caschera, M.C. , Ferri, F. , Grifoni, P. (2013). InteSe: An Integrated Model for Resolving Ambiguities in Multimodal Sentences\". IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics: Systems,  Volume: 43, Issue: 4, pp. 911 - 931.18.\tSpilker, J., Klarner, M., G\u00f6rz, G. (2000). \"Processing Self Corrections in a speech to speech system\". COLING 2000. pp. 1116-1120.</ref><ref name=\"Caschera3\">Caschera M.C., Ferri F., Grifoni P., (2007). \"The Management of ambiguities\". In  Visual Languages for Interactive Computing: Definitions and Formalizations. IGI Publishing. pp.129-140.</ref><ref name=\"Chai\">J. Chai, P. Hong, and M. X. Zhou, (2004 ).\"A probabilistic approach to reference resolution in multimodal user interface\" in Proc. 9th Int. Conf. Intell. User Interf., Madeira, Portugal, Jan. 2004, pp. 70\u201377.</ref><ref name=\"Dey\">Dey, A. K. Mankoff , J., (2005). \"[https://kilthub.cmu.edu/articles/Designing_Mediation_for_Context_Aware_Applications/6469979/files/11898533.pdf Designing mediation for context-aware applications]\". ACM Trans. Comput.-Hum. Interact. 12(1), pp. 53-80.</ref><ref name=\"Spilker\">Spilker, J., Klarner, M., G\u00f6rz, G. (2000). \"Processing Self Corrections in a speech to speech system\". COLING 2000. pp. 1116-1120.</ref><ref name=\"Mank\">Mankoff, J., Hudson, S.E., Abowd, G.D. (2000). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.42.9386&rep=rep1&type=pdf Providing integrated toolkit-level support for ambiguity in recognition-based interfaces]\". Proceedings of ACM CHI'00 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems. pp. 368 \u2013 375.</ref> Finally the system returns to the user outputs through the various modal channels (disaggregated) arranged according to a consistent feedback (fission).<ref>Grifoni P (2009) Multimodal fission. In: Multimodal human computer interaction and pervasive services. IGI Global, pp 103\u2013120</ref>\nThe pervasive use of mobile devices, sensors and web technologies can offer adequate computational resources to manage the complexity implied by the multimodal interaction. \"Using cloud for involving shared computational resources in managing the complexity of multimodal interaction represents an opportunity. In fact, cloud computing allows delivering shared scalable, configurable computing resources that can be dynamically and automatically provisioned and released\".<ref>Patrizia Grifoni, Fernando Ferri, Maria Chiara Caschera, Arianna D'Ulizia, Mauro Mazzei, \"MIS: Multimodal Interaction Services in a cloud perspective\", JNIT: Journal of Next Generation Information Technology, Vol. 5, No. 4, pp. 01 ~ 10, 2014</ref>\n\n== Multimodal input ==\nTwo major groups of multimodal interfaces have merged, one concerned in alternate input methods and the other in combined input/output. The first group of interfaces combined various user input modes beyond the traditional [[computer keyboard|keyboard]] and [[mouse (computing)|mouse]] [[input/output]], such as speech, pen, touch, manual gestures,<ref>Kettebekov, Sanshzar, and Rajeev Sharma (2001). \"[https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/3-540-45348-2_20.pdf Toward Natural Gesture/Speech Control of a Large Display].\" ProceedingsEHCI '01 Proceedings of the 8th IFIP International Conference on Engineering for Human-Computer Interaction Pages 221-234</ref> gaze and head and body movements.<ref>Marius Vassiliou, V. Sundareswaran, S. Chen, R. Behringer, C. Tam, M. Chan, P. Bangayan, and J. McGee (2000), \"Integrated Multimodal Human-Computer Interface and Augmented Reality for Interactive Display Applications,\" in Darrel G. Hopper (ed.) Cockpit Displays VII: Displays for Defense Applications (Proc. SPIE . 4022), 106-115. {{ISBN|0-8194-3648-8}}</ref> The most common such interface combines a visual modality (e.g. a display, keyboard, and mouse) with a voice modality ([[speech recognition]] for input, [[speech synthesis]] and recorded audio for output). However other modalities, such as pen-based input or [[Haptic technology|haptic]] input/output may be used. Multimodal user interfaces are a research area in [[human-computer interaction]] (HCI).\n\nThe advantage of multiple input [[Modality (human-computer interaction)|modalities]] is increased [[usability]]: the weaknesses of one modality are offset by the strengths of another. On a mobile device with a small visual interface and keypad, a word may be quite difficult to type but very easy to say (e.g. [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]]).  Consider how you would access and search through [[digital media]] catalogs from these same devices or set top boxes. And in one real-world example, patient information in an operating room environment is accessed verbally by members of the surgical team to maintain an antiseptic environment, and presented in near realtime aurally and visually to maximize comprehension.\n\nMultimodal input user interfaces have implications for [[accessibility]].<ref>{{cite conference |first1=H.S. |last1=Vitense |first2=J.A. |last2=Jacko |first3=V.K. |last3=Emery |title=Multimodal feedback: establishing a performance baseline for improved access by individuals with visual impairments |booktitle=ACM Conf. on Assistive Technologies |year=2002}}</ref> A well-designed multimodal application can be used by people with a wide variety of impairments. Visually impaired users rely on the voice modality with some keypad input.  Hearing-impaired users rely on the visual modality with some speech input. Other users will be \"situationally impaired\" (e.g. wearing gloves in a very noisy environment, driving, or needing to enter a credit card number in a public place) and will simply use the appropriate modalities as desired. On the other hand, a multimodal application that requires users to be able to operate all modalities is very poorly designed.\n\nThe most common form of input multimodality in the market makes use of the [[XHTML+Voice]] (aka X+V) Web markup language, an open [[specification]] developed by [[IBM]], [[Motorola]], and [[Opera Software]]. [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] is currently under consideration by the [[World Wide Web Consortium|W3C]] and combines several [[W3C Recommendation]]s including [[Extensible HyperText Markup Language|XHTML]] for visual markup, [[VoiceXML]] for voice markup, and [[XML Events]], a standard for integrating [[Extensible Markup Language|XML]] languages.  [[Multimodal browser]]s supporting [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] include IBM WebSphere Everyplace Multimodal Environment, [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]] for [[embedded system|Embedded]] [[Linux]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], and [[ACCESS Systems]] [[NetFront]] for [[Windows Mobile]]. To develop multimodal applications, [[software developer]]s may use a [[software development kit]], such as IBM WebSphere Multimodal Toolkit, based on the [[open source]] [[Eclipse (software)|Eclipse]] [[Software framework|framework]], which includes an [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] [[debugger]], [[source code editor|editor]], and [[simulator]].\n\n== Multimodal output ==\nThe second group of multimodal systems presents users with multimedia displays and multimodal output, primarily in the form of visual and auditory cues. Interface designers have also started to make use of other modalities, such as touch and olfaction. Proposed benefits of multimodal output system include synergy and redundancy. The information that is presented via several modalities is merged and refers to various aspects of the same process. The use of several modalities for processing exactly the same information provides an increased bandwidth of information transfer \n.<ref>{{Citation |first=S. |last=Oviatt |contribution=Multimodal interfaces |editor1-first=J. |editor1-last=Jacko |editor2-first=A |editor2-last=Sears |title=The Human-Computer Interaction Handbook |year=2002 |publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum |url=https://www.cogsci.msu.edu/DSS/2004-2005/Oviatt/Multimodel%20Interfaces.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first1=C. |last1=Bauckhage |first2=J. |last2=Fritsch |first3=K.J. |last3=Rohlfing |first4=S. |last4=Wachsmuth |first5=G. |last5=Sagerer |title=Evaluating integrated speech-and image understanding |booktitle=Int. Conf. on Multimodal Interfaces |year=2002 |doi=10.1109/ICMI.2002.1166961 }}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first1=N.A. |last1=Ismail |first2=E.A. |last2=O'Brien |title=Enabling Multimodal Interaction in Web-Based Personal Digital Photo Browsing |booktitle=Int. Conf. on Computer and Communication Engineering |year=2008 |url=http://eprints.utm.my/5732/1/ICCCE2008_preprint_version_UTM_IR.pdf |conference= |access-date=2010-03-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718171351/http://eprints.utm.my/5732/1/ICCCE2008_preprint_version_UTM_IR.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Currently, multimodal output is used mainly for improving the mapping between communication medium and content and to support attention management in data-rich environment where operators face considerable visual attention demands.<ref name=sarter>{{cite journal|first=N.B. |last=Sarter |title=Multimodal information presentation: Design guidance and research challenges |journal=International Journal of Industrial Ergonomics |volume=36 |issue=5 |pages=439\u2013445 |year=2006 |url=|doi=10.1016/j.ergon.2006.01.007}}</ref>\n\nAn important step in multimodal interface design is the creation of natural mappings between modalities and the information and tasks. The auditory channel differs from vision in several aspects. It is omnidirectional, transient and is always reserved.<ref name=sarter/> Speech output, one form of auditory information, received considerable attention. Several guidelines have been developed for the use of speech. Michaelis and Wiggins (1982) suggested that speech output should be used for simple short messages that will not be referred to later. It was also recommended that speech should be generated in time and require an immediate response.\n\nThe sense of touch was first utilized as a medium for communication in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite journal|first=F.A |last=Geldar |title=Adventures in tactile literacy |journal=American Psychologist |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=115\u2013124 |year=1957 |doi=10.1037/h0040416}}</ref> It is not only a promising but also a unique communication channel. In contrast to vision and hearing, the two traditional senses employed in HCI, the sense of touch is proximal: it senses objects that are in contact with the body, and it is bidirectional in that it supports both perception and acting on the environment.\n\nExamples of auditory feedback include auditory icons in computer operating systems indicating users' actions (e.g. deleting a file, open a folder, error), speech output for presenting navigational guidance in vehicles, and speech output for warning pilots on modern airplane cockpits. Examples of tactile signals include vibrations of the turn-signal lever to warn drivers of a car in their blind spot, the vibration of auto seat as a warning to drivers, and the [[stick shaker]] on modern aircraft alerting pilots to an impending stall.<ref name=sarter/>\n\nInvisible interface spaces became available using sensor technology. Infrared, ultrasound and cameras are all now commonly used.<ref>{{cite conference |first1=A. |last1=Brooks |first2=E. |last2=Petersson |title=SoundScapes: non-formal learning potentials from interactive VEs |booktitle=SIGGRAPH |year=2007 |doi=10.1145/1282040.1282059 |url=http://vbn.aau.dk/ws/files/13321650/pdf }}</ref> Transparency of interfacing with content is enhanced providing an immediate and direct link via meaningful mapping is in place, thus the user has direct and immediate feedback to input and content response becomes interface affordance (Gibson 1979).\n\n==Multimodal fusion==\nThe process of integrating information from various input modalities and combining them into a complete command is referred as multimodal fusion.<ref name=Dulizia1 /> In literature, three main approaches to the fusion process have been proposed, according to the main architectural levels (recognition and decision) at which the fusion of the input signals can be performed: recognition-based,<ref name=Pavlovic /><ref name=Andre /><ref name=\"Vo2\">Vo, M.T. (1998). \"[https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a352310.pdf A framework and Toolkit for the Construction of Multimodal Learning Interfaces]\", PhD. Thesis, Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, USA.</ref> decision-based,<ref name=Russ /><ref name=Corradini /><ref name=Vo /><ref name=\"Cohen\">Cohen, P.R.; Johnston, M.; McGee, D.; Oviatt, S.L.; Pittman, J.; Smith, I.A.; Chen, L.; Clow, J. (1997). \"Quickset: Multimodal interaction for distributed applications\", ACM Multimedia, pp. 31-40.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston1\">Johnston, M. (1998). \"[https://www.aclweb.org/anthology/P98-1102 Unification-based Multimodal Parsing]\". Proceedings of the 36th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics and 17th International Conference on Computational Linguistics (COLING-ACL '98), August 10\u201314, Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al, Montreal, Quebec, Canada. pp. 624-630.</ref><ref name=\"Nigay1\">Nigay, L.; Coutaz, J. (1995). \"[http://iihm.imag.fr/bouchet/ICARE/CHI95_Fusion.pdf A generic platform for addressing the multimodal challenge]\". Proceedings of the Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, ACM Press.</ref><ref name=\"Bouchet1\">Bouchet, J.; Nigay, L.; Ganille, T. (2004). \"[http://iihm.imag.fr/publs/2004/ICMI04-bouchet.pdf Icare software components for rapidly developing multimodal interfaces]\". ICMI '04: Proceedings of the 6th international conference on Multimodal interfaces (New York, NY, USA), ACM, pp. 251-258.</ref> and hybrid multi-level fusion.<ref name=Dulizia2 /><ref name=Sun /><ref name=\"Dulizia3\">D'Ulizia, A.; Ferri, F.; Grifoni P. (2007). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Arianna_DUlizia/publication/220831520_A_Hybrid_Grammar-Based_Approach_to_Multimodal_Languages_Specification/links/0fcfd5081034a1aa4f000000.pdf A Hybrid Grammar-Based Approach to Multimodal Languages Specification]\", OTM 2007 Workshop Proceedings, 25\u201330 November 2007, Vilamoura, Portugal, Springer-Verlag, Lecture Notes in Computer Science 4805, pp. 367-376.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston2\">Johnston, M.; Bangalore, S. (2000). \"[https://www.aclweb.org/anthology/C00-1054 Finite-state Multimodal Parsing and Understanding]\", In Proceedings of the International Conference on Computational Linguistics, Saarbruecken, Germany.</ref><ref name=\"Sun2\">Sun, Y.; Chen, F.; Shi, Y.D.; Chung, V. (2006). \"[https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1228257 A novel method for multi-sensory data fusion in multimodal human computer interaction]\". In Proceedings of the 20th conference of the computer-human interaction special interest group (CHISIG) of Australia on Computer-human interaction: design: activities, artefacts and environments, Sydney, Australia, pp. 401-404</ref><ref name=\"Shimazu\">Shimazu, H.; Takashima, Y. (1995). \"Multimodal Definite Clause Grammar,\"  Systems and Computers in Japan, vol. 26, no 3, pp. 93-102.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston3\">Johnston, M.; Bangalore, S. (2005). \"[https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/natural-language-engineering/article/finitestate-multimodal-integration-and-understanding/1C7CF3D7713704F09A81A386AADB2E67 Finite-state multimodal integration and understanding],\" Nat. Lang. Eng, Vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 159-187.</ref><ref name=\"Reitter\">Reitter, D.; Panttaja, E. M.; Cummins, F. (2004). \"UI on the fly: Generating a multimodal user interface,\" in Proc. of HLT-NAACL-2004, Boston, Massachusetts, USA.</ref>\n\nThe recognition-based fusion (also known as early fusion) consists in merging the outcomes of each modal recognizer by using integration mechanisms, such as, for example, statistical integration techniques, agent theory, hidden Markov models, artificial neural networks, etc. Examples of recognition-based fusion strategies are action frame,<ref name=Vo2 /> input vectors<ref name=Pavlovic />  and slots.<ref name=Andre />\n\nThe decision-based fusion (also known as late fusion) merges the semantic information that are extracted by using specific dialogue-driven fusion procedures to yield the complete interpretation. Examples of decision-based fusion strategies are typed feature structures,<ref name=Cohen /><ref name=Johnston2 /> melting pots,<ref name=Nigay1 /><ref name=Bouchet1 /> semantic frames,<ref name=Russ /><ref name=Vo /> and time-stamped lattices.<ref name=Corradini />\n\nThe potential applications for multimodal fusion include learning environments, consumer relations, security/surveillance, computer animation, etc.  Individually, modes are easily defined, but difficulty arises in having technology consider them a combined fusion.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://ieee-cas.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Guan_MultimodalFusion.pdf|title = Methods and Techniques for MultiModal Information Fusion|date = |accessdate = |website = Circuits & Systems Society|last = Guan|first = Ling}}</ref>  It's difficult for the algorithms to factor in dimensionality; there exist variables outside of current computation abilities.  For example, semantic meaning: two sentences could have the same lexical meaning but different emotional information.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the hybrid multi-level fusion, the integration of input modalities is distributed among the recognition and decision levels. The hybrid multi-level fusion includes the following three methodologies: finite-state transducers,<ref name=Johnston2 /> multimodal grammars<ref name=Sun /><ref name=Dulizia3 /><ref name=Sun2 /><ref name=Shimazu /><ref name=Johnston3 /><ref name=Reitter /><ref>D'Ulizia, A.; Ferri, F.; Grifoni P. (2011). \"A Learning Algorithm for Multimodal Grammar Inference\", IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics - Part B: Cybernetics, Vol. 41 (6), pp. 1495 - 1510.</ref>  and dialogue moves.<ref>P\u00e9rez, G.; Amores, G.; Manch\u00f3n, P. (2005). \"Two strategies for multimodal fusion\". In Proceedings of Multimodal Interaction for the Visualization and Exploration of Scientific Data, Trento, Italy, 26\u201332.</ref>\n\n==Ambiguity==\nUser's actions or commands produce multimodal inputs (multimodal message<ref name=\"Caschera1\"/>), which have to be interpreted by the system. The multimodal message is the medium that enables communication between users and multimodal systems. It is obtained by merging information that are conveyed via several modalities by considering the different types of cooperation between several modalities,<ref>Martin, J.C. (1997). \"Toward intelligent cooperation between modalities: the example of a system enabling multimodal interaction with a map\", Proceedings of International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI'97) Workshop on 'Intelligent Multimodal Systems', Nagoya, Japan</ref> the time relationships<ref>Allen, J.F.; Ferguson, G. (1994). \"Actions and events in interval temporal logic\", Journal of Logic and Computation, Vol. 4, No. 5, pp.531\u2013579</ref> among the involved modalities and the relationships between chunks of information connected with these modalities.<ref>Bellik, Y. (2001). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Yacine_Bellik/publication/228963930_Technical_requirements_for_a_successful_multimodal_interaction/links/0c960526a6a249c2dc000000/Technical-requirements-for-a-successful-multimodal-interaction.pdf Technical requirements for a successful multimodal interaction]\", International Workshop on Information Presentation and Natural Multimodal Dialogue, Verona, Italy, 14\u201315 December</ref>\n\nThe natural mapping between the multimodal input, which is provided by several interaction modalities (visual and auditory channel and sense of touch), and information and tasks imply to manage the typical problems of human-human communication, such as ambiguity. An ambiguity arises when more than one interpretation of input is possible. A multimodal ambiguity<ref name=Caschera5 />  arises both, if an element, which is provided by one modality, has more than one interpretation (i.e. ambiguities are propagated at the multimodal level), and/or if elements, connected with each modality, are univocally interpreted, but information referred to different modalities are incoherent at the syntactic or the semantic level (i.e. a multimodal sentence having different meanings or different  syntactic structure).\n\nIn \"The Management of Ambiguities\",<ref name=\"Caschera3\" /> the methods for solving ambiguities and for providing the correct interpretation of the user's input are organized in three main classes: prevention, a-posterior resolution and approximation resolution methods.<ref name=\"Caschera2\" /><ref name=\"Chai\" />\n\nPrevention methods impose users to follow predefined interaction behaviour according to a set of transitions between different allowed states of the interaction process. Example of prevention methods are: procedural method,<ref>Lee, Y.C.; Chin, F. (1995). \"An Iconic Query Language for Topological Relationship in GIS\". International Journal of geographical Information Systems 9(1). pp. 25-46</ref> reduction of the expressive power of the language grammar,<ref>Calcinelli, D.; Mainguenaud, M. (1994). \"Cigales, a visual language for geographic information system: the user interface\". Journal of Visual Languages and Computing 5(2). pp. 113-132</ref>  improvement of the expressive power of the language grammar.<ref>Ferri, F.; Rafanelli, M. (2005). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Maurizio_Rafanelli/publication/220461176_GeoPQL_A_Geographical_Pictorial_Query_Language_That_Resolves_Ambiguities_in_Query_Interpretation/links/00b7d51432479b48ac000000/GeoPQL-A-Geographical-Pictorial-Query-Language-That-Resolves-Ambiguities-in-Query-Interpretation.pdf GeoPQL: A Geographical Pictorial Query Language That Resolves Ambiguities in Query Interpretation]\". J. Data Semantics III. pp.50-80</ref>\n \nThe a-posterior resolution of ambiguities uses mediation approach.<ref name=\"Dey\" /> Examples of mediation techniques are: repetition, e.g. repetition by modality,<ref name=\"Dey\" /> granularity of repair<ref>Suhm, B., Myers, B. and Waibel,  A. (1999).  \"[http://isl.anthropomatik.kit.edu/cmu-kit/downloads/Model_Based_and_Empirical_Evaluation_of_Multimodal_Interactive_Error_Correction.pdf Model-based and empirical evaluation of multimodal interactive error correction]\". In Proc. Of CHI'99, May, 1999, pp. 584-591</ref> and undo,<ref name=\"Spilker\" />  and choice.<ref name=\"Mank\" />\n\nThe approximation resolution methods do not require any user involvement in the disambiguation process. They can all require the use of some theories, such as [[fuzzy logic]], [[Markov random field]], [[Bayesian network]]s and [[hidden Markov model]]s.<ref name=\"Caschera2\" /><ref name=\"Chai\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Device independence]]\n* [[Multimodal search]]\n* [[Multimodal sentiment analysis]]\n* [[Speech recognition]]\n*[[W3C MMI|W3C's Multimodal Interaction Activity]] \u2013 an initiative from [[W3C]] aiming to provide means (mostly [[XML]]) to support Multimodal Interaction scenarios on the Web.\n* [[Web accessibility]]\n* [[Wired glove]]\n* [[XHTML+Voice]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.w3.org/2002/mmi/ W3C Multimodal Interaction Activity]\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml+voice/ XHTML+Voice Profile 1.0], W3C Note 21 December 2001\n* Hoste, Lode, Dumas, Bruno and Signer, Beat: [https://www.academia.edu/808762 ''Mudra: A Unified Multimodal Interaction Framework''], In Proceedings of the 13th International Conference on Multimodal Interaction (ICMI 2011), Alicante, Spain, November 2011.\n* Toselli, Alejandro H\u00e9ctor, Vidal, Enrique, Casacuberta, Francisco: [https://www.springer.com/computer/hci/book/978-0-85729-478-4 ''Multimodal Interactive Pattern Recognition and Applications''], Springer, 2011.\n\n{{Mixed reality}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Multimodal Interaction}}\n[[Category:Multimodal interaction| ]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Mode (user interface)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{more footnotes|date=May 2009}}\n{{lead too short|date=October 2009}}\n{{confusing|date=October 2009}}\n}}\n\n'''Multimodal interaction''' provides the user with multiple modes of interacting with a system. A '''multimodal''' interface provides several distinct tools for [[input and output]] of data. For example, a multimodal [[Question answering|question answering system]] employs multiple [[Modality (human\u2013computer interaction)|modalities]] (such as text and photo) at both question (input) and answer (output) level.<ref>Mittal et al. (2011). \"[https://www.academia.edu/2475776 Versatile question answering systems: seeing in synthesis]\", International Journal of Intelligent Information Database Systems, 5(2), 119-142.</ref>\n\n== Introduction ==\nMultimodal human-computer interaction refers to the \"interaction with the virtual and physical environment through natural modes of communication\",<ref>Bourguet, M.L.( 2003). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.98.1958&rep=rep1&type=pdf Designing and Prototyping Multimodal Commands]\". Proceedings of Human-Computer Interaction (INTERACT'03), pp. 717-720.</ref> This implies that multimodal interaction enables a more free and natural communication, interfacing users with automated systems in both input and output.<ref>Stivers, T., Sidnell, J. Introduction: Multimodal interaction. Semiotica, 156(1/4), pp. 1-20. 2005.</ref> Specifically, multimodal systems can offer a flexible, efficient and usable environment allowing users to interact through input modalities, such as speech, handwriting, [[gesture recognition|hand gesture]] and gaze, and to receive information by the system through output modalities, such as speech synthesis, smart graphics and other modalities, opportunely combined. Then a multimodal system has to recognize the inputs from the different modalities combining them according to temporal and contextual constraints<ref name=\"Caschera1\">Caschera M. C., Ferri F., Grifoni P. (2007). \"[https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1358498 Multimodal interaction systems: information and time features]\".  International Journal of Web and Grid Services (IJWGS), Vol. 3 - Issue 1, pp 82-99.</ref> in order to allow their interpretation. This process is known as multimodal fusion, and it is the object of several research works from nineties to now.<ref name=\"Dulizia2\">D'Ulizia,  A.,  Ferri, F. and  Grifoni,  P. (2010). \"Generating Multimodal Grammars for Multimodal Dialogue Processing\".  IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man and Cybernetics, Part A: Systems and Humans, Vol 40, no 6, pp. 1130 \u2013 1145.</ref><ref name=\"Dulizia1\">D'Ulizia , A. (2009). \"[https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/20dd/37bf8c9f2f9b5e07efcf6441b2890c393192.pdf Exploring Multimodal Input Fusion Strategies]\". In: Grifoni P (ed) Handbook of Research on Multimodal Human Computer Interaction and Pervasive Services: Evolutionary Techniques for Improving Accessibility. IGI Publishing, pp. 34-57.</ref><ref name=\"Sun\">Sun, Y., Shi, Y., Chen,  F. and Chung , V.(2007). \"An Efficient Multimodal Language Processor for Parallel Input Strings in Multimodal Input Fusion,\" in Proc. of the international Conference on Semantic Computing, pp. 389-396.</ref><ref name=\"Russ\">Russ, G., Sallans, B., Hareter, H. (2005). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.94.4023&rep=rep1&type=pdf Semantic Based Information Fusion in a Multimodal Interface]\". International Conference on Human-Computer Interaction (HCI'05), Las Vegas, Nevada, USA, 20\u201323 June, pp 94-100.</ref><ref name=\"Corradini\">Corradini, A., Mehta M., Bernsen, N.O., Martin, J.-C. (2003). \"Multimodal Input Fusion in Human-Computer Interaction on the Example of the on-going NICE Project\". In Proceedings of the NATO-ASI conference on Data Fusion for Situation Monitoring, Incident Detection, Alert and Response Management, Yerevan, Armenia.</ref><ref name=\"Pavlovic\">Pavlovic, V.I., Berry, G.A., Huang, T.S. (1997). \"[https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/647399/ Integration of audio/visual information for use in human-computer intelligent interaction]\". Proceedings of the 1997 International Conference on Image Processing (ICIP '97), Volume 1, pp. 121-124.</ref><ref name=\"Andre\">Andre, M., Popescu, V.G., Shaikh, A., Medl, A., Marsic, I., Kulikowski, C., Flanagan J.L. (1998). \"[http://www.cvauni.edu.vn/imgupload_dinhkem/file/Chuyen%20De%20HCI/11_%20Integration%20of%20Speech%20and%20Gesture%20for%20Multimodal%20HCI.pdf Integration of Speech and Gesture for Multimodal Human-Computer Interaction]\". In Second International Conference on Cooperative Multimodal Communication. 28\u201330 January, Tilburg, The Netherlands.</ref><ref name=\"Vo\">Vo, M.T., Wood, C. (1996). \"Building an application framework for speech and pen input integration in multimodal learning interfaces\". In Proceedings of the Acoustics, Speech, and Signal Processing (ICASSP'96), May 7\u201310, IEEE Computer Society, Volume 06, pp. 3545-3548.</ref> The fused inputs are interpreted by the system.  Naturalness and flexibility can produce more than one interpretation for each different modality (channel) and for their simultaneous use, and they consequently can produce multimodal ambiguity<ref name=\"Caschera5\">Caschera, M.C. , Ferri, F. , Grifoni, P. (2013). \"[https://arxiv.org/pdf/1704.02841 From Modal to Multimodal Ambiguities: a Classification Approach]\", Journal of Next Generation Information Technology  (JNIT), Vol. 4, No. 5, pp. 87 -109.</ref> generally due to imprecision, noises or other similar factors.  For solving ambiguities, several methods have been proposed.<ref name=\"Caschera2\">Caschera, M.C. , Ferri, F. , Grifoni, P. (2013). InteSe: An Integrated Model for Resolving Ambiguities in Multimodal Sentences\". IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics: Systems,  Volume: 43, Issue: 4, pp. 911 - 931.18.\tSpilker, J., Klarner, M., G\u00f6rz, G. (2000). \"Processing Self Corrections in a speech to speech system\". COLING 2000. pp. 1116-1120.</ref><ref name=\"Caschera3\">Caschera M.C., Ferri F., Grifoni P., (2007). \"The Management of ambiguities\". In  Visual Languages for Interactive Computing: Definitions and Formalizations. IGI Publishing. pp.129-140.</ref><ref name=\"Chai\">J. Chai, P. Hong, and M. X. Zhou, (2004 ).\"A probabilistic approach to reference resolution in multimodal user interface\" in Proc. 9th Int. Conf. Intell. User Interf., Madeira, Portugal, Jan. 2004, pp. 70\u201377.</ref><ref name=\"Dey\">Dey, A. K. Mankoff , J., (2005). \"[https://kilthub.cmu.edu/articles/Designing_Mediation_for_Context_Aware_Applications/6469979/files/11898533.pdf Designing mediation for context-aware applications]\". ACM Trans. Comput.-Hum. Interact. 12(1), pp. 53-80.</ref><ref name=\"Spilker\">Spilker, J., Klarner, M., G\u00f6rz, G. (2000). \"Processing Self Corrections in a speech to speech system\". COLING 2000. pp. 1116-1120.</ref><ref name=\"Mank\">Mankoff, J., Hudson, S.E., Abowd, G.D. (2000). \"[http://citeseerx.ist.psu.edu/viewdoc/download?doi=10.1.1.42.9386&rep=rep1&type=pdf Providing integrated toolkit-level support for ambiguity in recognition-based interfaces]\". Proceedings of ACM CHI'00 Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems. pp. 368 \u2013 375.</ref> Finally the system returns to the user outputs through the various modal channels (disaggregated) arranged according to a consistent feedback (fission).<ref>Grifoni P (2009) Multimodal fission. In: Multimodal human computer interaction and pervasive services. IGI Global, pp 103\u2013120</ref>\nThe pervasive use of mobile devices, sensors and web technologies can offer adequate computational resources to manage the complexity implied by the multimodal interaction. \"Using cloud for involving shared computational resources in managing the complexity of multimodal interaction represents an opportunity. In fact, cloud computing allows delivering shared scalable, configurable computing resources that can be dynamically and automatically provisioned and released\".<ref>Patrizia Grifoni, Fernando Ferri, Maria Chiara Caschera, Arianna D'Ulizia, Mauro Mazzei, \"MIS: Multimodal Interaction Services in a cloud perspective\", JNIT: Journal of Next Generation Information Technology, Vol. 5, No. 4, pp. 01 ~ 10, 2014</ref>\n\n== Multimodal input ==\nTwo major groups of multimodal interfaces have merged, one concerned in alternate input methods and the other in combined input/output. The first group of interfaces combined various user input modes beyond the traditional [[computer keyboard|keyboard]] and [[mouse (computing)|mouse]] [[input/output]], such as speech, pen, touch, manual gestures,<ref>Kettebekov, Sanshzar, and Rajeev Sharma (2001). \"[https://link.springer.com/content/pdf/10.1007/3-540-45348-2_20.pdf Toward Natural Gesture/Speech Control of a Large Display].\" ProceedingsEHCI '01 Proceedings of the 8th IFIP International Conference on Engineering for Human-Computer Interaction Pages 221-234</ref> gaze and head and body movements.<ref>Marius Vassiliou, V. Sundareswaran, S. Chen, R. Behringer, C. Tam, M. Chan, P. Bangayan, and J. McGee (2000), \"Integrated Multimodal Human-Computer Interface and Augmented Reality for Interactive Display Applications,\" in Darrel G. Hopper (ed.) Cockpit Displays VII: Displays for Defense Applications (Proc. SPIE . 4022), 106-115. {{ISBN|0-8194-3648-8}}</ref> The most common such interface combines a visual modality (e.g. a display, keyboard, and mouse) with a voice modality ([[speech recognition]] for input, [[speech synthesis]] and recorded audio for output). However other modalities, such as pen-based input or [[Haptic technology|haptic]] input/output may be used. Multimodal user interfaces are a research area in [[human-computer interaction]] (HCI).\n\nThe advantage of multiple input [[Modality (human-computer interaction)|modalities]] is increased [[usability]]: the weaknesses of one modality are offset by the strengths of another. On a mobile device with a small visual interface and keypad, a word may be quite difficult to type but very easy to say (e.g. [[Poughkeepsie, New York|Poughkeepsie]]).  Consider how you would access and search through [[digital media]] catalogs from these same devices or set top boxes. And in one real-world example, patient information in an operating room environment is accessed verbally by members of the surgical team to maintain an antiseptic environment, and presented in near realtime aurally and visually to maximize comprehension.\n\nMultimodal input user interfaces have implications for [[accessibility]].<ref>{{cite conference |first1=H.S. |last1=Vitense |first2=J.A. |last2=Jacko |first3=V.K. |last3=Emery |title=Multimodal feedback: establishing a performance baseline for improved access by individuals with visual impairments |booktitle=ACM Conf. on Assistive Technologies |year=2002}}</ref> A well-designed multimodal application can be used by people with a wide variety of impairments. Visually impaired users rely on the voice modality with some keypad input.  Hearing-impaired users rely on the visual modality with some speech input. Other users will be \"situationally impaired\" (e.g. wearing gloves in a very noisy environment, driving, or needing to enter a credit card number in a public place) and will simply use the appropriate modalities as desired. On the other hand, a multimodal application that requires users to be able to operate all modalities is very poorly designed.\n\nThe most common form of input multimodality in the market makes use of the [[XHTML+Voice]] (aka X+V) Web markup language, an open [[specification]] developed by [[IBM]], [[Motorola]], and [[Opera Software]]. [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] is currently under consideration by the [[World Wide Web Consortium|W3C]] and combines several [[W3C Recommendation]]s including [[Extensible HyperText Markup Language|XHTML]] for visual markup, [[VoiceXML]] for voice markup, and [[XML Events]], a standard for integrating [[Extensible Markup Language|XML]] languages.  [[Multimodal browser]]s supporting [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] include IBM WebSphere Everyplace Multimodal Environment, [[Opera (web browser)|Opera]] for [[embedded system|Embedded]] [[Linux]] and [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]], and [[ACCESS Systems]] [[NetFront]] for [[Windows Mobile]]. To develop multimodal applications, [[software developer]]s may use a [[software development kit]], such as IBM WebSphere Multimodal Toolkit, based on the [[open source]] [[Eclipse (software)|Eclipse]] [[Software framework|framework]], which includes an [[XHTML+Voice|X+V]] [[debugger]], [[source code editor|editor]], and [[simulator]].\n\n== Multimodal output ==\nThe second group of multimodal systems presents users with multimedia displays and multimodal output, primarily in the form of visual and auditory cues. Interface designers have also started to make use of other modalities, such as touch and olfaction. Proposed benefits of multimodal output system include synergy and redundancy. The information that is presented via several modalities is merged and refers to various aspects of the same process. The use of several modalities for processing exactly the same information provides an increased bandwidth of information transfer \n.<ref>{{Citation |first=S. |last=Oviatt |contribution=Multimodal interfaces |editor1-first=J. |editor1-last=Jacko |editor2-first=A |editor2-last=Sears |title=The Human-Computer Interaction Handbook |year=2002 |publisher=Lawrence Erlbaum |url=https://www.cogsci.msu.edu/DSS/2004-2005/Oviatt/Multimodel%20Interfaces.pdf}}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first1=C. |last1=Bauckhage |first2=J. |last2=Fritsch |first3=K.J. |last3=Rohlfing |first4=S. |last4=Wachsmuth |first5=G. |last5=Sagerer |title=Evaluating integrated speech-and image understanding |booktitle=Int. Conf. on Multimodal Interfaces |year=2002 |doi=10.1109/ICMI.2002.1166961 }}</ref><ref>{{cite conference |first1=N.A. |last1=Ismail |first2=E.A. |last2=O'Brien |title=Enabling Multimodal Interaction in Web-Based Personal Digital Photo Browsing |booktitle=Int. Conf. on Computer and Communication Engineering |year=2008 |url=http://eprints.utm.my/5732/1/ICCCE2008_preprint_version_UTM_IR.pdf |conference= |access-date=2010-03-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718171351/http://eprints.utm.my/5732/1/ICCCE2008_preprint_version_UTM_IR.pdf |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref> Currently, multimodal output is used mainly for improving the mapping between communication medium and content and to support attention management in data-rich environment where operators face considerable visual attention demands.<ref name=sarter>{{cite journal|first=N.B. |last=Sarter |title=Multimodal information presentation: Design guidance and research challenges |journal=International Journal of Industrial Ergonomics |volume=36 |issue=5 |pages=439\u2013445 |year=2006 |url=|doi=10.1016/j.ergon.2006.01.007}}</ref>\n\nAn important step in multimodal interface design is the creation of natural mappings between modalities and the information and tasks. The auditory channel differs from vision in several aspects. It is omnidirectional, transient and is always reserved.<ref name=sarter/> Speech output, one form of auditory information, received considerable attention. Several guidelines have been developed for the use of speech. Michaelis and Wiggins (1982) suggested that speech output should be used for simple short messages that will not be referred to later. It was also recommended that speech should be generated in time and require an immediate response.\n\nThe sense of touch was first utilized as a medium for communication in the late 1950s.<ref>{{cite journal|first=F.A |last=Geldar |title=Adventures in tactile literacy |journal=American Psychologist |volume=12 |issue=3 |pages=115\u2013124 |year=1957 |doi=10.1037/h0040416}}</ref> It is not only a promising but also a unique communication channel. In contrast to vision and hearing, the two traditional senses employed in HCI, the sense of touch is proximal: it senses objects that are in contact with the body, and it is bidirectional in that it supports both perception and acting on the environment.\n\nExamples of auditory feedback include auditory icons in computer operating systems indicating users' actions (e.g. deleting a file, open a folder, error), speech output for presenting navigational guidance in vehicles, and speech output for warning pilots on modern airplane cockpits. Examples of tactile signals include vibrations of the turn-signal lever to warn drivers of a car in their blind spot, the vibration of auto seat as a warning to drivers, and the [[stick shaker]] on modern aircraft alerting pilots to an impending stall.<ref name=sarter/>\n\nInvisible interface spaces became available using sensor technology. Infrared, ultrasound and cameras are all now commonly used.<ref>{{cite conference |first1=A. |last1=Brooks |first2=E. |last2=Petersson |title=SoundScapes: non-formal learning potentials from interactive VEs |booktitle=SIGGRAPH |year=2007 |doi=10.1145/1282040.1282059 |url=http://vbn.aau.dk/ws/files/13321650/pdf }}</ref> Transparency of interfacing with content is enhanced providing an immediate and direct link via meaningful mapping is in place, thus the user has direct and immediate feedback to input and content response becomes interface affordance (Gibson 1979).\n\n==Multimodal fusion==\nThe process of integrating information from various input modalities and combining them into a complete command is referred as multimodal fusion.<ref name=Dulizia1 /> In literature, three main approaches to the fusion process have been proposed, according to the main architectural levels (recognition and decision) at which the fusion of the input signals can be performed: recognition-based,<ref name=Pavlovic /><ref name=Andre /><ref name=\"Vo2\">Vo, M.T. (1998). \"[https://apps.dtic.mil/dtic/tr/fulltext/u2/a352310.pdf A framework and Toolkit for the Construction of Multimodal Learning Interfaces]\", PhD. Thesis, Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, USA.</ref> decision-based,<ref name=Russ /><ref name=Corradini /><ref name=Vo /><ref name=\"Cohen\">Cohen, P.R.; Johnston, M.; McGee, D.; Oviatt, S.L.; Pittman, J.; Smith, I.A.; Chen, L.; Clow, J. (1997). \"Quickset: Multimodal interaction for distributed applications\", ACM Multimedia, pp. 31-40.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston1\">Johnston, M. (1998). \"[https://www.aclweb.org/anthology/P98-1102 Unification-based Multimodal Parsing]\". Proceedings of the 36th Annual Meeting of the Association for Computational Linguistics and 17th International Conference on Computational Linguistics (COLING-ACL '98), August 10\u201314, Universit\u00e9 de Montr\u00e9al, Montreal, Quebec, Canada. pp. 624-630.</ref><ref name=\"Nigay1\">Nigay, L.; Coutaz, J. (1995). \"[http://iihm.imag.fr/bouchet/ICARE/CHI95_Fusion.pdf A generic platform for addressing the multimodal challenge]\". Proceedings of the Conference on Human Factors in Computing Systems, ACM Press.</ref><ref name=\"Bouchet1\">Bouchet, J.; Nigay, L.; Ganille, T. (2004). \"[http://iihm.imag.fr/publs/2004/ICMI04-bouchet.pdf Icare software components for rapidly developing multimodal interfaces]\". ICMI '04: Proceedings of the 6th international conference on Multimodal interfaces (New York, NY, USA), ACM, pp. 251-258.</ref> and hybrid multi-level fusion.<ref name=Dulizia2 /><ref name=Sun /><ref name=\"Dulizia3\">D'Ulizia, A.; Ferri, F.; Grifoni P. (2007). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Arianna_DUlizia/publication/220831520_A_Hybrid_Grammar-Based_Approach_to_Multimodal_Languages_Specification/links/0fcfd5081034a1aa4f000000.pdf A Hybrid Grammar-Based Approach to Multimodal Languages Specification]\", OTM 2007 Workshop Proceedings, 25\u201330 November 2007, Vilamoura, Portugal, Springer-Verlag, Lecture Notes in Computer Science 4805, pp. 367-376.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston2\">Johnston, M.; Bangalore, S. (2000). \"[https://www.aclweb.org/anthology/C00-1054 Finite-state Multimodal Parsing and Understanding]\", In Proceedings of the International Conference on Computational Linguistics, Saarbruecken, Germany.</ref><ref name=\"Sun2\">Sun, Y.; Chen, F.; Shi, Y.D.; Chung, V. (2006). \"[https://dl.acm.org/citation.cfm?id=1228257 A novel method for multi-sensory data fusion in multimodal human computer interaction]\". In Proceedings of the 20th conference of the computer-human interaction special interest group (CHISIG) of Australia on Computer-human interaction: design: activities, artefacts and environments, Sydney, Australia, pp. 401-404</ref><ref name=\"Shimazu\">Shimazu, H.; Takashima, Y. (1995). \"Multimodal Definite Clause Grammar,\"  Systems and Computers in Japan, vol. 26, no 3, pp. 93-102.</ref><ref name=\"Johnston3\">Johnston, M.; Bangalore, S. (2005). \"[https://www.cambridge.org/core/journals/natural-language-engineering/article/finitestate-multimodal-integration-and-understanding/1C7CF3D7713704F09A81A386AADB2E67 Finite-state multimodal integration and understanding],\" Nat. Lang. Eng, Vol. 11, no. 2, pp. 159-187.</ref><ref name=\"Reitter\">Reitter, D.; Panttaja, E. M.; Cummins, F. (2004). \"UI on the fly: Generating a multimodal user interface,\" in Proc. of HLT-NAACL-2004, Boston, Massachusetts, USA.</ref>\n\nThe recognition-based fusion (also known as early fusion) consists in merging the outcomes of each modal recognizer by using integration mechanisms, such as, for example, statistical integration techniques, agent theory, hidden Markov models, artificial neural networks, etc. Examples of recognition-based fusion strategies are action frame,<ref name=Vo2 /> input vectors<ref name=Pavlovic />  and slots.<ref name=Andre />\n\nThe decision-based fusion (also known as late fusion) merges the semantic information that are extracted by using specific dialogue-driven fusion procedures to yield the complete interpretation. Examples of decision-based fusion strategies are typed feature structures,<ref name=Cohen /><ref name=Johnston2 /> melting pots,<ref name=Nigay1 /><ref name=Bouchet1 /> semantic frames,<ref name=Russ /><ref name=Vo /> and time-stamped lattices.<ref name=Corradini />\n\nThe potential applications for multimodal fusion include learning environments, consumer relations, security/surveillance, computer animation, etc.  Individually, modes are easily defined, but difficulty arises in having technology consider them a combined fusion.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url = http://ieee-cas.org/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/Guan_MultimodalFusion.pdf|title = Methods and Techniques for MultiModal Information Fusion|date = |accessdate = |website = Circuits & Systems Society|last = Guan|first = Ling}}</ref>  It's difficult for the algorithms to factor in dimensionality; there exist variables outside of current computation abilities.  For example, semantic meaning: two sentences could have the same lexical meaning but different emotional information.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the hybrid multi-level fusion, the integration of input modalities is distributed among the recognition and decision levels. The hybrid multi-level fusion includes the following three methodologies: finite-state transducers,<ref name=Johnston2 /> multimodal grammars<ref name=Sun /><ref name=Dulizia3 /><ref name=Sun2 /><ref name=Shimazu /><ref name=Johnston3 /><ref name=Reitter /><ref>D'Ulizia, A.; Ferri, F.; Grifoni P. (2011). \"A Learning Algorithm for Multimodal Grammar Inference\", IEEE Transactions on Systems, Man, and Cybernetics - Part B: Cybernetics, Vol. 41 (6), pp. 1495 - 1510.</ref>  and dialogue moves.<ref>P\u00e9rez, G.; Amores, G.; Manch\u00f3n, P. (2005). \"Two strategies for multimodal fusion\". In Proceedings of Multimodal Interaction for the Visualization and Exploration of Scientific Data, Trento, Italy, 26\u201332.</ref>\n\n==Ambiguity==\nUser's actions or commands produce multimodal inputs (multimodal message<ref name=\"Caschera1\"/>), which have to be interpreted by the system. The multimodal message is the medium that enables communication between users and multimodal systems. It is obtained by merging information that are conveyed via several modalities by considering the different types of cooperation between several modalities,<ref>Martin, J.C. (1997). \"Toward intelligent cooperation between modalities: the example of a system enabling multimodal interaction with a map\", Proceedings of International Joint Conference on Artificial Intelligence (IJCAI'97) Workshop on 'Intelligent Multimodal Systems', Nagoya, Japan</ref> the time relationships<ref>Allen, J.F.; Ferguson, G. (1994). \"Actions and events in interval temporal logic\", Journal of Logic and Computation, Vol. 4, No. 5, pp.531\u2013579</ref> among the involved modalities and the relationships between chunks of information connected with these modalities.<ref>Bellik, Y. (2001). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Yacine_Bellik/publication/228963930_Technical_requirements_for_a_successful_multimodal_interaction/links/0c960526a6a249c2dc000000/Technical-requirements-for-a-successful-multimodal-interaction.pdf Technical requirements for a successful multimodal interaction]\", International Workshop on Information Presentation and Natural Multimodal Dialogue, Verona, Italy, 14\u201315 December</ref>\n\nThe natural mapping between the multimodal input, which is provided by several interaction modalities (visual and auditory channel and sense of touch), and information and tasks imply to manage the typical problems of human-human communication, such as ambiguity. An ambiguity arises when more than one interpretation of input is possible. A multimodal ambiguity<ref name=Caschera5 />  arises both, if an element, which is provided by one modality, has more than one interpretation (i.e. ambiguities are propagated at the multimodal level), and/or if elements, connected with each modality, are univocally interpreted, but information referred to different modalities are incoherent at the syntactic or the semantic level (i.e. a multimodal sentence having different meanings or different  syntactic structure).\n\nIn \"The Management of Ambiguities\",<ref name=\"Caschera3\" /> the methods for solving ambiguities and for providing the correct interpretation of the user's input are organized in three main classes: prevention, a-posterior resolution and approximation resolution methods.<ref name=\"Caschera2\" /><ref name=\"Chai\" />\n\nPrevention methods impose users to follow predefined interaction behaviour according to a set of transitions between different allowed states of the interaction process. Example of prevention methods are: procedural method,<ref>Lee, Y.C.; Chin, F. (1995). \"An Iconic Query Language for Topological Relationship in GIS\". International Journal of geographical Information Systems 9(1). pp. 25-46</ref> reduction of the expressive power of the language grammar,<ref>Calcinelli, D.; Mainguenaud, M. (1994). \"Cigales, a visual language for geographic information system: the user interface\". Journal of Visual Languages and Computing 5(2). pp. 113-132</ref>  improvement of the expressive power of the language grammar.<ref>Ferri, F.; Rafanelli, M. (2005). \"[https://www.researchgate.net/profile/Maurizio_Rafanelli/publication/220461176_GeoPQL_A_Geographical_Pictorial_Query_Language_That_Resolves_Ambiguities_in_Query_Interpretation/links/00b7d51432479b48ac000000/GeoPQL-A-Geographical-Pictorial-Query-Language-That-Resolves-Ambiguities-in-Query-Interpretation.pdf GeoPQL: A Geographical Pictorial Query Language That Resolves Ambiguities in Query Interpretation]\". J. Data Semantics III. pp.50-80</ref>\n \nThe a-posterior resolution of ambiguities uses mediation approach.<ref name=\"Dey\" /> Examples of mediation techniques are: repetition, e.g. repetition by modality,<ref name=\"Dey\" /> granularity of repair<ref>Suhm, B., Myers, B. and Waibel,  A. (1999).  \"[http://isl.anthropomatik.kit.edu/cmu-kit/downloads/Model_Based_and_Empirical_Evaluation_of_Multimodal_Interactive_Error_Correction.pdf Model-based and empirical evaluation of multimodal interactive error correction]\". In Proc. Of CHI'99, May, 1999, pp. 584-591</ref> and undo,<ref name=\"Spilker\" />  and choice.<ref name=\"Mank\" />\n\nThe approximation resolution methods do not require any user involvement in the disambiguation process. They can all require the use of some theories, such as [[fuzzy logic]], [[Markov random field]], [[Bayesian network]]s and [[hidden Markov model]]s.<ref name=\"Caschera2\" /><ref name=\"Chai\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Device independence]]\n* [[Multimodal search]]\n* [[Multimodal sentiment analysis]]\n* [[Speech recognition]]\n*[[W3C MMI|W3C's Multimodal Interaction Activity]] \u2013 an initiative from [[W3C]] aiming to provide means (mostly [[XML]]) to support Multimodal Interaction scenarios on the Web.\n* [[Web accessibility]]\n* [[Wired glove]]\n* [[XHTML+Voice]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.w3.org/2002/mmi/ W3C Multimodal Interaction Activity]\n* [http://www.w3.org/TR/xhtml+voice/ XHTML+Voice Profile 1.0], W3C Note 21 December 2001\n* Hoste, Lode, Dumas, Bruno and Signer, Beat: [https://www.academia.edu/808762 ''Mudra: A Unified Multimodal Interaction Framework''], In Proceedings of the 13th International Conference on Multimodal Interaction (ICMI 2011), Alicante, Spain, November 2011.\n* Toselli, Alejandro H\u00e9ctor, Vidal, Enrique, Casacuberta, Francisco: [https://www.springer.com/computer/hci/book/978-0-85729-478-4 ''Multimodal Interactive Pattern Recognition and Applications''], Springer, 2011.\n\n{{Mixed reality}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Multimodal Interaction}}\n[[Category:Multimodal interaction| ]]\n", "name_user": "Jarble", "label": "safe", "comment": "linking", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Multimodal_interaction"}
{"title_page": "Mrs. Wiggins", "text_new": "\"'''Mrs. Wiggins'''\" (also known as '''\"Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins\"''') is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the skit series during its ninth season in 1975\u201376 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" would not air until August 18, 1979 on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show'' which had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978. All together, there were 19 installments of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" sketches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timelife.com/products/the-carol-burnett-show-the-ultimate-collection |title=THE CAROL BURNETT SHOW: THE ULTIMATE COLLECTION |publisher=Time Life |date= |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\n\"Mrs. Wiggins\" features two characters created by [[Tim Conway]]: Mr. Bernie Tudball (played by Conway) and Mrs. Wanda Wiggins (played by [[Carol Burnett]]). [[Vicki Lawrence]] would occasionally play Mr. Tudball's wife. Mr. Tudball is a businessman with an off-color [[toupee]] and a mock [[Romanian language|Romanian]] accent, pronouncing his secretary's name \"Mrs. Uh-Whiggins\".<ref>King, Susan. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-tim-conway-20131112-story.html Tim Conway's life off script]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', November 11, 2013. Accessed September 21, 2016.</ref> Mrs. Wiggins is his [[secretary]], a \"bimbo who the IQ fairy never visited\".<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> She was notably recognized by how she walked in her skirt, as designed by [[Bob Mackie]], and her near-constant fingernail filing. The sketches center on Mr. Tudbull's frustration over Mrs. Wiggins' dimwittedness, such as not being able to properly use the office intercom system.{{citation needed|date = February 2017}}\n\n==Background==\nTim Conway created the sketch after ''The Carol Burnett Show'' writers' office secretary, Charlene, would constantly press the wrong button on the intercom.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/tim-conway#| title=Interview: Tim Conway| publisher=Archive of American Television| date=29 April 2004| last=Herman| first=Karen}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Wiggins was originally written to be a little old lady, but Bob Mackie decided to go another route.<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> He decided to base the look of Mrs. Wiggins on the kind of secretary that would sit around and file her nails and go to lunch.<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Bob Mackie |work=Archive of American Television | date=June 29, 2000  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/bob-mackie# | accessdate=Jun 26, 2016}}</ref> In the costuming of Mrs. Wiggins, Mackie put Burnett in a very tight skirt that would control the way she walked. He told Burnett to stick her behind in the bagging part in the back of the skirt, and this gave her the \"Wiggins walk.\"<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Carol Burnett |work=Archive of American Television | date=April 29, 2003  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/carol-burnett | accessdate=June 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sketches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Episode\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Airdate\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Title & Description\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 17\n| January 10, 1976\n| ''The Intercom'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins how to use the office's new intercom system.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 21\n| February 14, 1976\n| ''The Intercom\u2026Again'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has even more difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins the workings of the office intercom.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 24\n| March 13, 1976\n| ''The Birthday Party'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball attempts to surprise Mrs. Wiggins on her birthday.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 4\n| October 16, 1976\n| ''The Vending Machine'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball does battle with a difficult [[coffee vending machine]].\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 7\n| October 30, 1976\n| ''Buzz Off'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball gets into trouble with a newly-installed door buzzer system, and Mrs. Wiggins is no help.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 10\n| November 27, 1976\n| Mr. Tudball tries to get Mrs. Wiggins to cover for him by lying to his wife.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 13\n| December 25, 1976\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins at Lunch'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball treats Mrs. Wiggins to a lunch in honor of National Secretary Week. \n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 17\n| January 29, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins' Lunch Date'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins has a lunch date with a millionaire suitor ([[Rock Hudson]]), but she wants to dump him.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 18\n| February 5, 1977\n| ''Enter Mrs. Tudball'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is thrown out of the house by his wife for playing poker.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 19\n| February 12, 1977\n| ''The Vacation'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball teaches Mrs. Wiggins to play blackjack in preparation for her Las Vegas vacation.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 23\n| March 26, 1977\n| ''The Fire Drill'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has a hard time coordinating a fire-safety plan with Mrs. Wiggins before an inspector arrives.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 4\n| October 15, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball picks a fitting coffin for Mrs. Wiggins' deceased canary.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 6\n| October 29, 1977\n| ''Ol' Paint'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball tries to paint the office and relies on Mrs. Wiggins for help.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 9\n| November 19, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins in Hawaii'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins goes to Hawaii for a convention with Mr. and Mrs. Tudball.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 11\n| December 3, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball nudges Mrs. Wiggins to clean-up her desk which leads to office chaos.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 13\n| December 18, 1977\n| ''Christmas Eve'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins enjoy a champagne-laden Christmas Eve.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 20\n| February 26, 1978\n| ''Car Problem'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball takes a telephone call from Mrs. Wiggins' car repairman, thinking it's her doctor.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 24\n| March 29, 1978\n| ''Flashbacks'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is moving his office and has a flashback to the first time he interviewed Mrs. Wiggins.\n|-\n| ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''\n| Ep 1.1\n| August 18, 1979\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins and the Energy Crisis'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins make a mess of energy conservation.\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{The Carol Burnett Show}}\n\n[[Category:Comedy sketches]]\n[[Category:Fictional secretaries|Wiggins]]\n[[Category:Carol Burnett]]\n", "text_old": "\"'''Mrs. Wiggins'''\" (also known as '''\"Mr. Tudball and Mrs. Wiggins\"''') is a series of [[sketch comedy|comedy sketches]] featured on ''[[The Carol Burnett Show]]'', with one installment airing on ''[[Carol Burnett & Company]]''. ''The Carol Burnett Show'' introduced the skit series during its ninth season in 1975\u201376 and continued to air new installments for the remainder of its 11-season run, through its final season in 1977\u201378. However, the final installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" would not air until August 18, 1979 on a different four-week summer series titled ''Carol Burnett & Company''. This was the only installment of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" that did not air on ''The Carol Burnett Show'' which had completed its run almost a year and a half earlier on March 29, 1978. All together, there were 19 installments of \"Mrs. Wiggins\" sketches.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timelife.com/products/the-carol-burnett-show-the-ultimate-collection |title=THE CAROL BURNETT SHOW: THE ULTIMATE COLLECTION |publisher=Time Life |date= |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n==Premise==\n\"Mrs. Wiggins\" features two characters created by [[Tim Conway]]: Mr. Bernie Tudball (played by Conway) and Mrs. Wanda Wiggins (played by [[Carol Burnett]]). [[Vicki Lawrence]] would occasionally play Mr. Tudball's wife. Mr. Tudball is a businessman with an off-color [[toupee]] and a mock [[Romanian language|Romanian]] accent, pronouncing his secretary's name \"Mrs. Uh-Whiggins\".<ref>King, Susan. \"[http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/tv/showtracker/la-et-st-tim-conway-20131112-story.html Tim Conway's life off script]\", ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'', November 11, 2013. Accessed September 21, 2016.</ref> Mrs. Wiggins is his [[secretary]], a \"bimbo who the IQ fairy never visited\".<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> She was notably recognized by how she walked in her skirt, as designed by [[Bob Mackie]], and her near-constant fingernail filing. The sketches center on Mr. Tudbull's frustration over Mrs. Wiggins' dimwittedness, such as not being able to properly use the office intercom system.{{citation needed|date = February 2017}}\n\n==Background==\nTim Conway created the sketch after ''The Carol Burnett Show'' writers' office secretary, Charlene, would constantly press the wrong button on the intercom.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/tim-conway#| title=Interview: Tim Conway| publisher=Archive of American Television| date=29 April 2004| last=Herman| first=Karen}}</ref>\n\nMrs. Wiggins was originally written to be a little old lady, but Bob Mackie decided to go another route.<ref name=\"Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2010/apr/25/entertainment/la-et-burnett-conway-20100426 |title=Carol Burnett and Tim Conway: bonded through comedy |publisher=Los Angeles Times |date=April 25, 2010 |accessdate=2016-06-26}}</ref> He decided to base the look of Mrs. Wiggins on the kind of secretary that would sit around and file her nails and go to lunch.<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Bob Mackie |work=Archive of American Television | date=June 29, 2000  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/bob-mackie# | accessdate=Jun 26, 2016}}</ref> In the costuming of Mrs. Wiggins, Mackie put Burnett in a very tight skirt that would control the way she walked. He told Burnett to stick her behind in the bagging part in the back of the skirt, and this gave her the \"Wiggins walk.\"<ref>{{Cite web | first= | last= | title=Carol Burnett |work=Archive of American Television | date=April 29, 2003  | url=http://www.emmytvlegends.org/interviews/people/carol-burnett | accessdate=June 26, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Sketches==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:left\"\n|-\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Season\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Episode\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Airdate\n! style=\"padding:0 8px;\" | Title & Description\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 17\n| January 10, 1976\n| ''The Intercom'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins how to use the office's new intercom system.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 21\n| February 14, 1976\n| ''The Intercom\u2026Again'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has even more difficulty teaching Mrs. Wiggins the workings of the office intercom.\n|-\n| Season 9\n| Ep 24\n| March 13, 1976\n| ''The Birthday Party'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball attempts to surprise Mrs. Wiggins on her birthday.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 4\n| October 16, 1976\n| ''The Vending Machine'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball does battle with a difficult [[coffee vending machine]].\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 7\n| October 30, 1976\n| ''Buzz Off'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball gets into trouble with a newly-installed door buzzer system, and Mrs. Wiggins is no help.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 10\n| November 27, 1976\n| Mr. Tudball tries to get Mrs. Wiggins to cover for him by lying to his wife.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 13\n| December 25, 1976\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins at Lunch'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball treats Mrs. Wiggins to a lunch in honor of National Secretary Week. \n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 17\n| January 29, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins' Lunch Date'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins has a lunch date with a millionaire suitor ([[Rock Hudson]]), but she wants to dump him.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 18\n| February 5, 1977\n| ''Enter Mrs. Tudball'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball is thrown out of the house by his wife for playing poker.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 19\n| February 12, 1977\n| ''The Vacation'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball teaches Mrs. Wiggins to play blackjack in preparation for her Las Vegas vacation.\n|-\n| Season 10\n| Ep 23\n| March 26, 1977\n| ''The Fire Drill'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball has a hard time coordinating a fire-safety plan with Mrs. Wiggins before an inspector arrives.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 4\n| October 15, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball picks a fitting coffin for Mrs. Wiggins' deceased canary.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 6\n| October 29, 1977\n| ''Ol' Paint'' \u2013 Mr. Tudball tries to paint the office and relies on Mrs. Wiggins for help.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 9\n| November 19, 1977\n| ''Mrs. Wiggins in Hawaii'' \u2013 Mrs. Wiggins goes to Hawaii with Mr. and Mrs. Tudball for a convention.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 11\n| December 3, 1977\n| Mr. Tudball nudges Mrs. Wiggins to clean-up her desk which leads to office chaos.\n|-\n| Season 11\n| Ep 13\n| D