{"title_page": "John McCaskill", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{COI|date=September 2017}}\n\n[[File:John_McCaskill.jpg|right|thumb|John McCaskill]]\n\n'''John S. McCaskill''' (born 1957) is an Australian chemist who works in a wide variety of fields ranging from theoretical biochemistry to novel computation to artificial life.\n\n==Biography==\nAfter graduating from [[Sydney University]] in 1978 ([[Robert Gilbert (chemist)|R. G. Gilbert]] advisor) and obtaining his PhD (D. Phil.) in 1982 as a Rhodes Scholar at New College, Oxford, McCaskill joined the group of Nobel prize-winner [[Manfred Eigen]] at the [[Max Planck Society|Max Planck Institute]] for Biophysical Chemistry in G\u00f6ttingen, Germany. He became Professor for Theoretical Biochemistry at the [[University of Jena|Friedrich Schiller University Jena]] in 1992, founding a multidisciplinary research group in Biomolecular Information Processing (BioMIP) at the Institute for Molecular Biotechnology (imb Jena), a field which he pioneered for 25 years while holding positions at the GMD (National Research Center for Information Technology), the [[Fraunhofer Society]], [[Ruhr University Bochum]], the [[Santa Fe Institute]], and the [http://ecltech.org European Center for Living Technology] at the [[Ca' Foscari University of Venice]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=John |first1=McCaskill |url=http://www.biomip.org/profile/cv_mccaskill_short_aug_2019.pdf |website=biomip.org |title=McCaskill CV |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nMcCaskill is best known  for his work on [[information processing]] in [[evolving]] and [[self-organizing]] [[molecular]] systems, spanning theoretical and experimental approaches that include novel devices and systems. His early work on [[molecular evolution]] was theoretical, using non-equilibrium [[statistical mechanics]] to solve Eigen\u2019s equations of [[Quasispecies model|molecular quasispecies]] for realistic [[fitness landscape]]s<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1063/1.446590|title = A localization threshold for macromolecular quasispecies from continuously distributed replication rates|journal = The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume = 80|issue = 10|pages = 5194\u20135202|year = 1984|last1 = McCaskill|first1 = J. S.}}</ref>\n.<ref name=QuasiSpecies>Eigen, Manfred, McCaskill, John, and Schuster, Peter. \"The molecular quasi-species.\" Adv. Chem. Phys 75 (1989): 149-263, 1988. [https://dx.doi.org/10.1002/9780470141243.ch4 doi:10.1002/9780470141243.ch4]</ref>  He developed an ensemble approach to [[RNA structure prediction]], now in wide use,<ref name=\"RNA partition\">{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=The equilibrium partition function and base pair binding probabilities for RNA secondary structure |journal=Biopolymers |date=1990 |volume=29 |issue=6\u20137 |pages=1105\u20131119 | doi=10.1002/bip.360290621 |hdl=11858/00-001M-0000-0013-0DE3-9 |hdl-access=free }}</ref> and made several contributions, both theoretical and experimental, to the study of spatially-resolved [[molecular evolution]], including the experimental implementation of [[reaction-diffusion systems|spatially-resolved]] capillary and [[microfluidics|microfluidic]] flow [[microreactor|reactors]] \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=J.S. |last2=Bauer |first2=G.J. |title=Images of evolution: origin of spontaneous RNA replication waves |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA |date=1993 |volume=90 |issue=9 |pages=4191\u20134195 |doi=10.1073/pnas.90.9.4191 |pmid=7683426 |pmc=46472 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=Spatially resolved in vitro molecular ecology |journal=Biophysical Chemistry |date=1997 |volume=66 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=145\u2013158 |doi=10.1016/s0301-4622(97)00073-2 |pmid=9362557 }}</ref>\nand also including the construction of NGEN and MEREGEN, large-scale reconfigurable [[Systolic array|systolic computers]] for simulating spatial evolution based on reprogrammmable [[Field Programmable Gate Array|FPGA]] hardware<ref>Tangen, U., Maeke, Th and McCaskill, J.S. \"Advanced simulation in the configurable massively parallel hardware MereGen.\" Coupling of Biological and Electronic Systems. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, 2002. 107-118.</ref>\n\nSince 2000, he has established a [http://www.ruhr-uni-bochum.de/ECCell/work_packages_2/4_eccell_integration/background_2/chemical_microprocessors/index.html chemical microprocessor] technology for electronically [[programmable matter]] via [[microscale chemistry|microscale electrochemistry]], and\napplied it to the development of novel approaches towards [[artificial cell]]s and DNA/RNA processing systems, including ''in vitro'' DNA/RNA processing systems, including [[Spiegelman's Monster|Q\u00df RNA]], [[Autonomously replicating sequence|3SR]], [[Multiple displacement amplification|SDA]], 3SR-Predator-Prey \n,<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wlotzka |first1=Britta |last2=McCaskill |first2=John |title=A molecular predator and its prey: coupled isothermal amplification of nucleic acids |journal=Chemistry and Biology |date=1996 |volume=4 |issue=25\u201333 |pages=25\u201333 |doi=10.1016/s1074-5521(97)90234-9 |url=https://www.cell.com/cell-chemical-biology/pdf/S1074-5521(97)90234-9.pdf |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref> CATCH \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ellinger |first1=Thomas |last2=Ehricht |first2=Ralf |last3=McCaskill |first3=John |title=In vitro evolution of molecular cooperation in CATCH, a cooperatively coupled amplification system |journal=Cell Chemical Biology |date=1998 |volume=5 |issue=12 |pages=729\u2013241 |doi=10.1016/s1074-5521(98)90665-2 |url=https://www.cell.com/cell-chemical-biology/fulltext/S1074-5521(98)90665-2?code=cell-site |accessdate=13 August 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> and optical DNA Computing systems based on magnetic beads in microfluidic reactors\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=Optically programming DNA computing in microflow reactors |journal=Bio Systems |date=2001 |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=125\u2013138 |doi=10.1016/s0303-2647(01)00099-5 |pmid=11267740 }}</ref>\nMcCaskill led an international initiative to investigate evolvable artificial chemical cells with an EU-funded project, [http://www.istpace.org/Web_Final_Report/the_pace_report/index.html PACE], one of the earliest projects to explore a bottom-up approach to create an artificial living cell\n<ref>{{cite news |title=Holy Grail of Artificial Life |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/holy-grail-of-artificial-life-1.1155883 |agency=The Irish Times |date=2 September 2004}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |title=The God-Machine. Is life to be created anew? (Die Gottes-Maschine. Ist das Leben ganz neu zu erfinden?)|agency=GEO|date=August 2009}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=L\u00fctke-Wissing |first1=Stefan |title=Die geheimen Baupl\u00e4ne der Natur |url=https://www.tib.eu/de/suchen/id/datacite%3Adoi~10.5445%252FDIVA%252F2008-21/Die-geheimen-Baupl\u00e4ne-der-Natur/ |website=TIB Leibniz-Informationszentrum |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Regis |first1=Ed |title=What is Life? |date=2008 |publisher=Farrar, Strauss and Giroux |location=New York |isbn=978-0-374-28851-8 |pages=140\u2013141}}</ref>  Most recently his research has led to the development of novel autonomous and programmable electronic-chemical systems, leading other EU-funded projects, [http://www.biomip.org/eccell ECCell] and [http://www.biomip.org/micreagents/ MICREAgents], and opening a wide range of potential applications in basic and applied research.\n\nMcCaskill's current work includes modeling the essential interplay of [[self-organization]] and [[evolution]] in life-like chemical systems, and exploring the potential of electronic-chemical hybrid [[Information Technology]] based on these properties. He has produced over 100 scientific publications, taught courses and supervised PhD theses in disciplines ranging from chemistry, physics and biology to computer science, and his multidisciplinary work straddling theory and experiment has been recognized in invited lectures at international conferences around the world. He was an inaugural director of the  [http://ecltech.org European Center for Living Technology], and has since served on its science board. While McCaskill's main work is in basic science, it has helped spawn several start-up companies and continues to involve the coordination of major collaborative projects fostering novel links between science and industry.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.biomip.org/pacereport/index.html '''PACE'''] (Programmable Artificial Cell Evolution)\n* [http://www.biomip.org/eccell/index.html '''ECCell'''] (Electronic Chemical Cell)\n* [http://www.biomip.org/micreagents/index.html '''MICREAgents'''] (Microscale Chemically Reactive Agents)\n* [http://www.biomip.org J. McCaskill BioMIP page].\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCaskill, John}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ruhr University Bochum faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian scientists]]\n[[Category:Australian chemists]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Jena faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Ca' Foscari University of Venice faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Researchers of artificial life]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=November 2019}}\n{{COI|date=September 2017}}\n\n[[File:John_McCaskill.jpg|right|thumb|John McCaskill]]\n\n'''John S. McCaskill''' (born 1957) is an Australian chemist who works in a wide variety of fields ranging from theoretical biochemistry to novel computation to artificial life.   \n\n==Biography==\nAfter graduating from [[Sydney University]] in 1978 ([[Robert Gilbert (chemist)|R. G. Gilbert]] advisor) and obtaining his PhD (D. Phil.) in 1982 as a Rhodes Scholar at New College, Oxford, McCaskill joined the group of Nobel prize-winner [[Manfred Eigen]] at the [[Max Planck Society|Max Planck Institute]] for Biophysical Chemistry in G\u00f6ttingen, Germany. He became Professor for Theoretical Biochemistry at the [[University of Jena|Friedrich Schiller University Jena]] in 1992, founding a multidisciplinary research group in Biomolecular Information Processing (BioMIP) at the Institute for Molecular Biotechnology (imb Jena), a field which he pioneered for 25 years while holding positions at the GMD (National Research Center for Information Technology), the [[Fraunhofer Society]], [[Ruhr University Bochum]], the [[Santa Fe Institute]], and the [http://ecltech.org European Center for Living Technology] at the [[Ca' Foscari University of Venice]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=John |first1=McCaskill |url=http://www.biomip.org/profile/cv_mccaskill_short_aug_2019.pdf |website=biomip.org |title=McCaskill CV |accessdate=7 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Research ==\nMcCaskill is best known  for his work on [[information processing]] in [[Evolving|evolving]] and [[self-organizing]] [[molecular]] systems, spanning theoretical and experimental approaches that include novel devices and systems. His early work on [[molecular evolution]] was theoretical, using non-equilibrium [[statistical mechanics]] to solve Eigen\u2019s equations of [[Quasispecies model|molecular quasispecies]] for realistic [[fitness landscape]]s<ref>{{Cite journal |doi = 10.1063/1.446590|title = A localization threshold for macromolecular quasispecies from continuously distributed replication rates|journal = The Journal of Chemical Physics|volume = 80|issue = 10|pages = 5194\u20135202|year = 1984|last1 = McCaskill|first1 = J. S.}}</ref>\n<ref name=QuasiSpecies> Eigen, Manfred, McCaskill, John, and Schuster, Peter. \"The molecular quasi-species.\" Adv. Chem. Phys 75 (1989): 149-263, 1988. [https://dx.doi.org/10.1002/9780470141243.ch4 doi:10.1002/9780470141243.ch4]</ref>.  He developed an ensemble approach to [[RNA structure prediction]], now in wide use<ref name=\"RNA partition\">{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=The equilibrium partition function and base pair binding probabilities for RNA secondary structure |journal=Biopolymers |date=1990 |volume=29 |issue=6\u20137 |pages=1105\u20131119 | doi=10.1002/bip.360290621 |hdl=11858/00-001M-0000-0013-0DE3-9 |hdl-access=free }}</ref>, and made several contributions, both theoretical and experimental, to the study of spatially-resolved [[molecular evolution]], including the experimental implementation of [[reaction-diffusion systems|spatially-resolved]] capillary and [[microfluidics|microfluidic]] flow [[microreactor|reactors]] \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=J.S. |last2=Bauer |first2=G.J. |title=Images of evolution: origin of spontaneous RNA replication waves |journal=Proc. Natl. Acad. Sci. USA |date=1993 |volume=90 |issue=9 |pages=4191\u20134195 |doi=10.1073/pnas.90.9.4191 |pmid=7683426 |pmc=46472 }}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=Spatially resolved in vitro molecular ecology |journal=Biophysical Chemistry |date=1997 |volume=66 |issue=2\u20133 |pages=145\u2013158 |doi=10.1016/s0301-4622(97)00073-2 |pmid=9362557 }}</ref>\nand also including the construction of NGEN and MEREGEN, large-scale reconfigurable [[Systolic array|systolic computers]] for simulating spatial evolution based on reprogrammmable [[Field Programmable Gate Array|FPGA]] hardware<ref> Tangen, U., Maeke, Th and McCaskill, J.S. \"Advanced simulation in the configurable massively parallel hardware MereGen.\" Coupling of Biological and Electronic Systems. Springer, Berlin, Heidelberg, 2002. 107-118.</ref>\n\nSince 2000, he has established a [http://www.ruhr-uni-bochum.de/ECCell/work_packages_2/4_eccell_integration/background_2/chemical_microprocessors/index.html chemical microprocessor] technology for electronically [[programmable matter]] via [[microscale chemistry|microscale electrochemistry]], and\napplied it to the development of novel approaches towards [[Artificial cell|artificial cells]] and DNA/RNA processing systems, including ''in vitro'' DNA/RNA processing systems, including [[Spiegelman's_Monster | Q\u00df RNA]], [[Autonomously_replicating_sequence| 3SR]], [[Multiple_displacement_amplification | SDA]], 3SR-Predator-Prey \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Wlotzka |first1=Britta |last2=McCaskill |first2=John |title=A molecular predator and its prey: coupled isothermal amplification of nucleic acids |journal=Chemistry and Biology |date=1996 |volume=4 |issue=25\u201333 |pages=25\u201333 |doi=10.1016/s1074-5521(97)90234-9 |url=https://www.cell.com/cell-chemical-biology/pdf/S1074-5521(97)90234-9.pdf |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>, CATCH \n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Ellinger |first1=Thomas |last2=Ehricht |first2=Ralf |last3=McCaskill |first3=John |title=In vitro evolution of molecular cooperation in CATCH, a cooperatively coupled amplification system |journal=Cell Chemical Biology |date=1998 |volume=5 |issue=12 |pages=729\u2013241 |doi=10.1016/s1074-5521(98)90665-2 |url=https://www.cell.com/cell-chemical-biology/fulltext/S1074-5521(98)90665-2?code=cell-site |accessdate=13 August 2019|doi-access=free }}</ref> and optical DNA Computing systems based on magnetic beads in microfluidic reactors\n<ref>{{cite journal |last1=McCaskill |first1=John |title=Optically programming DNA computing in microflow reactors |journal=Bio Systems |date=2001 |volume=59 |issue=2 |pages=125\u2013138 |doi=10.1016/s0303-2647(01)00099-5 |pmid=11267740 }}</ref>\nMcCaskill led an international initiative to investigate evolvable artificial chemical cells with an EU-funded project, [http://www.istpace.org/Web_Final_Report/the_pace_report/index.html PACE], one of the earliest projects to explore a bottom-up approach to create an artificial living cell\n<ref>{{cite news |title=Holy Grail of Artificial Life |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/holy-grail-of-artificial-life-1.1155883 |agency=The Irish Times |date=2 September 2004}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite news |title=The God-Machine. Is life to be created anew? (Die Gottes-Maschine. Ist das Leben ganz neu zu erfinden?)|agency=GEO|date=August 2009}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite web |last1=L\u00fctke-Wissing |first1=Stefan |title=Die geheimen Baupl\u00e4ne der Natur |url=https://www.tib.eu/de/suchen/id/datacite%3Adoi~10.5445%252FDIVA%252F2008-21/Die-geheimen-Baupl\u00e4ne-der-Natur/ |website=TIB Leibniz-Informationszentrum |accessdate=13 August 2019}}</ref>\n<ref>{{cite book |last1=Regis |first1=Ed |title=What is Life? |date=2008 |publisher=Farrar, Strauss and Giroux |location=New York |isbn=978-0-374-28851-8 |pages=140\u2013141}}</ref>.  Most recently his research has led to the development of novel autonomous and programmable electronic-chemical systems, leading other EU-funded projects, [http://www.biomip.org/eccell ECCell] and [http://www.biomip.org/micreagents/ MICREAgents], and opening a wide range of potential applications in basic and applied research. \n\nMcCaskill's current work includes modeling the essential interplay of [[self-organization]] and [[evolution]] in life-like chemical systems, and exploring the potential of electronic-chemical hybrid [[Information Technology]] based on these properties. He has produced over 100 scientific publications, taught courses and supervised PhD theses in disciplines ranging from chemistry, physics and biology to computer science, and his multidisciplinary work straddling theory and experiment has been recognized in invited lectures at international conferences around the world. He was an inaugural director of the  [http://ecltech.org European Center for Living Technology], and has since served on its science board. While McCaskill's main work is in basic science, it has helped spawn several start-up companies and continues to involve the coordination of major collaborative projects fostering novel links between science and industry.\n\n== References ==\n<!-- Inline citations added to your article will automatically display here. See https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WP:REFB for instructions on how to add citations. -->\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n[http://www.biomip.org/pacereport/index.html '''PACE'''] (Programmable Artificial Cell Evolution)\n\n[http://www.biomip.org/eccell/index.html '''ECCell'''] (Electronic Chemical Cell)\n\n[http://www.biomip.org/micreagents/index.html '''MICREAgents'''] (Microscale Chemically Reactive Agents)\n\n[http://www.biomip.org J. McCaskill BioMIP page].\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McCaskill, John}}\n[[Category:1957 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ruhr University Bochum faculty]]\n[[Category:21st-century chemists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Australian scientists]]\n[[Category:Australian chemists]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in the United States]]\n[[Category:University of Jena faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in Germany]]\n[[Category:Alumni of New College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:University of Sydney alumni]]\n[[Category:Australian Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Ca' Foscari University of Venice faculty]]\n[[Category:Australian expatriates in Italy]]\n[[Category:Researchers of artificial life]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McCaskill"}
{"title_page": "Star Carr", "text_new": "{{Short description|Mesolithic archaeological site in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name = Star Carr\n| native_name = \n| alternate_name = \n| image = View of Star Carr site looking NWW..jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = View of the Star Carr site looking {{nowrap|north-west-west}}\n| map_type = North Yorkshire\n| map_alt = \n| map_size = \n| relief = \n| coordinates = {{coord|54|12|51|N|00|25|24|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| region = \n| type = Settlement\n| part_of = \n| length = \n| width = \n| area = \n| height = \n| builder = \n| material = \n| built = Approximately 9300&nbsp;BC\n| abandoned = Approximately 8480&nbsp;BC\n| epochs = [[Mesolithic]]\n| cultures = \n| dependency_of = \n| occupants = \n| event = \n| excavations = \n| archaeologists = \n| condition = \n| ownership = \n| management = \n| public_access = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes = \n}}\n{{Mesolithic|233}}\n\n'''Star Carr''' is a [[Mesolithic]] archaeological site in [[North Yorkshire]], England. It is around five miles ({{convert|5|mi|abbr=out|disp=output only|0}}) south of [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]].<ref name=Pastscape>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=80206 |mname= Star Carr|accessdate=15 January 2008}}</ref>\nIt is generally regarded as the most important and informative Mesolithic site in [[Great Britain]]. It is as important to the Mesolithic period as [[Stonehenge]] is to the [[Neolithic]] period or [[Scandinavian York]] is to understanding [[Viking Age]] Britain.\n\nThe site was occupied during the early Mesolithic archaeological period, which coincided with the [[preboreal]] and [[boreal (period)|boreal]] climatic periods. Though the [[Last Glacial Period|ice age]] had ended and temperatures were close to modern averages, sea levels had not yet risen sufficiently to separate Britain from continental [[Europe]]. Highlights among the finds include Britain\u2019s oldest structure, 21 [[red deer]] stag skull-caps that may have been headdresses and nearly 200 projectile, or harpoon, points made of red deer [[antler]]. These organic materials were preserved due to having been buried in waterlogged [[peat]]. Normally all that remains on Mesolithic sites are [[stone tool]]s.\n\nExcavation of the site began in 1948, a year after artefacts were first noticed by an amateur archaeologist. The site is most famous for some of the extremely rare [[Artifact (archaeology)|artefacts]] discovered during the original excavations but its importance has been reinforced by new understandings of the nature and extent of the Mesolithic archaeology in the area and reinterpretations of the original material.\n\n==General information==\n\n===Environmental context===\nStar Carr now lies under farmland at the eastern end of the [[Vale of Pickering]]. During the Mesolithic the site was near the outflow at the western end of a palaeolake, known as [[Lake Flixton]].{{Sfn|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=4,13}} At the end of the last ice age, a combination of glacial and post-glacial [[geomorphology]] caused the area to drain to the west (away from the shortest-distance to the [[North Sea]] at [[Filey]]). The basin filled by Lake Flixton was probably created by glacial 'scarring'.\n\nThe site is preserved due to Lake Flixton having been in-filled with peat during the course of the Mesolithic. Waterlogged peat prevents organic finds from oxidizing and has led to some of the best preservation conditions possible (such conditions have preserved the famous [[bog bodies]] found in other parts of northern Europe).\nAs a result of such good conditions, archaeologists were able to recover bone, antler, and wood in addition to the flints that are normally all that is left on sites from this period.\n\nDuring the period of Mesolithic occupation the area surrounding the lake would have been a mixed forest of [[birch]], [[aspen]] and [[willow]].{{Sfn|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=147\u2013161}} The lake edge and shallows would have been full of reeds, water lily and other aquatic plants and lake levels would have changed dynamically in response to rainfall or snow-melt.\n\nThese and many other plants would have formed the base of a complex [[food web]]. The [[mammal]]s that we have evidence for include [[herbivore]]s such as [[beaver]], red deer, [[roe deer]], [[moose|elk]] \n, [[aurochs]], [[wild boar]], [[hare]] and [[carnivore]]s such as [[wolf]], [[lynx]], [[bear]], [[fox]], [[pine marten]], [[badger]] and [[hedgehog]].{{Sfn|Milner|2006|p=72}}\n\n===Key artefacts===\nAlong with the flints that are characteristic of [[Mesolithic]] sites, there were a large number of objects made of red deer and elk antler, elk bone, aurochs bone and one piece of bird bone.{{sfn|Clark|1954|pp=115\u2013164}} Rarer objects included worked [[amber]], [[shale]], [[haematite]], [[iron pyrites]], a decorated [[pendant]], thought to be the oldest known Mesolithic art in Britain <ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8 | issue=40 | title=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain | year=2016 | journal=Internet Archaeology | last1 = Milner | first1 = Nicky| doi-access=free }}</ref> and tightly-rolled pieces of birch-bark and pieces of birch-resin pitch or tar and worked wood.\nThe flint found at Star Carr came from nearby beaches, which at time of occupation would have been about {{convert|10|to|20|km|0|abbr=on}} distant, and also from the [[Yorkshire Wolds]] immediately to the south of the site.\n\nThe two most outstanding categories of finds are the 'barbed points' and 'antler frontlets'. The barbed points are made of the antler of red deer stags. They are between {{convert|8|cm|in}} and {{convert|38|cm|in}} in length{{sfn|Clark|1954|p=123}} and the 195 examples found at Star Carr account for more than 95% of the total number from the British Mesolithic. Many of the barbed points and antler frontlets appear to be deliberately broken. The antler frontlets are made from red deer stag (male) skulls with the antlers still attached. The 21 antler frontlets are sufficiently complete to see how they have been manufactured: two holes were perforated through the skull with a [[flint]] tool and the inside of the skull cap was smoothed. The antlers on each frontlet has been carefully trimmed maybe to reduce weight. It seems very likely that these modifications are designed to allow the frontlets to be used as headgear. Finds from the site are now divided between four institutions: The [[British Museum]], the [[Yorkshire Museum]] in York, the University [[Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, University of Cambridge|Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]] at Cambridge and the [[Rotunda Museum|Scarborough Museum]].<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?place=5702&plaA=5702-3-1 British Museum Collection]</ref><ref name=\"sc2017\">{{cite web|title=Exhibitions|url=http://www.starcarr.com/exhibitions.html|website=Star Carr Archaeology Project|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Star Carr headdress cropped.JPG|thumb|left|300px|Red Deer Stag skull with holes]]\n[[File:Star Carr spear tips 01.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Barbed points]]\n\n===Evidence of structures===\nPost holes, a sunken area and concentrations of flints, burning and other artefacts indicate the presence of a structure approximately {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} wide. The posts were almost certainly made of wood and roughly {{convert|20|cm|in}} in diameter there may have been as many as 18 of them and the holes indicated that several may have been replaced over the course of the structure's use.\nIt is impossible to know the form or materials from which the walls and/or roof would have been made. They may have used [[Hide (skin)|hides]], [[thatch]], [[Peat|turf]] or [[Bark (botany)|bark]] on a conical ([[teepee]]-like) or rounded ([[wigwam]]-like) frame. There is no reason to suppose that the same materials and form would have been used for the structure's entire life-span. There was evidence that the floor was covered with a layer of moss, reeds and other soft plant materials {{convert|20|cm|in}}\u2013{{convert|30|cm|in}} deep.\n[[Radiocarbon]] dates indicated a use-life of between 200 and 500&nbsp;years.\nThe structure has been compared to the Mesolithic structure found at [[Howick, Northumberland|Howick]], Northumberland and British [[Iron Age]] [[Roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouses]].\n\nA large wooden platform has been discovered nearby on the shore of the former lake \u2013 the earliest known example of carpentry in Europe, though its purpose is as yet unknown. Timbers of Aspen and Willow were split along the grain using wedges (probably made of wood and antler); these were then laid in the boggy areas at the lake shore, presumably to provide firm footing.\nThe extent of the wooden platform is not known but it may be a significantly larger and more complex undertaking than the house-like structure.\n\n===Chronology===\nCurrent [[radiocarbon]] dates from the site indicate occupation first commenced between 9335\u20139275&nbsp;BC, lasting for a period of around 800 years until 8525\u20138440&nbsp;BC.{{sfn|Milner, Conneller and Taylor|2018|pp=225\u2013244}} However, such occupations may have been episodic in nature, varying in intensity between different periods.{{sfn|Milner, Conneller and Taylor|2018|pp=225\u2013244}}\n\n==History of investigations==\n\n===Discovery and initial excavations===\nStar Carr was discovered in 1947 when John Moore, an amateur archaeologist, noticed flints in the exposed soil of several recently dredged ditches in the eastern Vale of Pickering. One of these sites, bordering on the [[River Derwent, Yorkshire#Course and character of the Derwent catchment area|New Hertford River]] was to the south of Star Carr Farm. Moore decided to excavate a small trench at Star Carr in 1948 as part of a series of investigations. On the discovery of intact organic remains Moore contacted Professor [[Grahame Clark]] of the [[University of Cambridge]] via [[Harry Godwin]] and the curator of the [[Rotunda Museum|Scarborough Museum]], [[Arthur Roy Clapham]].{{Sfn|Clark|1954|pp=xvii\u2013xviii}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Alleyne |first=Richard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7937240/Oldest-house-in-Britain-discovered-to-be-11500-years-old.html |title=Oldest house in Britain discovered to be 11,500 years old |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nClark began his investigation with the explicit aim of building a more detailed picture of the Mesolithic environment and the ways in which people used it.<ref>Clark 1972, p. 7{{Full citation needed|date=October 2012}}</ref> The organic preservation enabled the recovery of the plant and animal remains necessary for this. Clark excavated from 1949 to 1951. Clark's 1954 publication of these excavations is a seminal text in the study of the British Mesolithic and prehistory generally.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nClark believed he had uncovered the entirety of the site and believed Star Carr could be used as a [[type-site]] for the British Mesolithic. He drew parallels between the finds at Star Carr and the site of [[Maglemosian|Maglemose]] in Denmark. It is now recognised that many of Clark\u2019s inferences were incorrect but the excavation remains one of the most important in the study of British prehistory ever undertaken.\n\n===Further investigations: The Lake Flixton Landscape===\nIn 1977 archaeologists excavated [[Iron Age]], [[Bronze Age]] and Mesolithic material from [[Seamer, Scarborough|Seamer]] Carr, just to the north of Star Carr. These excavations were conducted in advance of the Seamer Carr landfill site. The discovery of Mesolithic material led to a new series of investigations around Lake Flixton directed by [[Tim Schadla-Hall]] (currently [[University College London]]). This team returned to Star Carr in 1985 and 1989.<ref>{{harvnb|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=}}{{page needed|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis project investigated the archaeology and ecology of the wider landscape around Lake Flixton and found several more Mesolithic sites but none with as many of the unusual artefacts (such as barbed points and antler frontlets) discovered at Star Carr.\n\n===The latest investigations===\nIn the 2000s new excavations began at Star Carr. This reinvestigation is being directed by [[Nicky Milner]] ([[Department of Archaeology at the University of York|University of York]]), Chantal Conneller ([[University of Manchester]]) and Barry Taylor ([[University of Chester]]). This ongoing project has reinvestigated Clark's excavations and also excavated the dry-land, discovering the structure.\n\n[[File:Star Carr Engraved Pendant.gif|thumb|right|Animated image showing the sequence of engravings on a pendant excavated from the Mesolithic archaeological site of Starr Carr in 2015 <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Morgan | first1 = C. | last2 = Scholma-Mason | first2 = N. | year = 2017 | title = Animated GIFs as Expressive Visual Narratives and Expository Devices in Archaeology | url = | journal = Internet Archaeology | volume = | issue = 44| page = | doi = 10.11141/ia.44.11 | doi-access = free }}</ref>]]\n\nMost significantly, recent [[geochemical]] investigations have demonstrated that the preservation conditions have deteriorated. The result of this is that any remaining organic artefacts will be far less informative than those discovered by previous excavation projects. Though the reasons for this remain somewhat unclear, it appears that the acidity of the groundwater has massively increased in the last few years.\n\nA decorated pendant (the [[Star Carr Pendant]]), thought to be the oldest known Mesolithic art in Britain, was found at the site in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8 | issue=40 | title=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain | year=2016 | journal=Internet Archaeology | last1 = Milner | first1 = Nicky| doi-access=free }}</ref>  The 11,000 year old object has been on display at the [[Yorkshire Museum]] with other finds from the site since 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title = Yorkshire Stone Age pendant goes on display | publisher = [[BBC News Online]] | date = 26 February 2016 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-35669267 | accessdate = 26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Interpretive debates==\nClark, the original excavator, believed the Mesolithic people would have lived on a brushwood platform on the edge of the former Lake Flixton.{{sfn|Clark|1954|p=xvii}} Recent excavations have revealed that people lived on the dry land upslope of the lake and various activities were carried out at the lake edge.\n\nThere is much debate about the time of year the site was occupied. Mesolithic people hunted a number of animals including red and roe deer, elk, aurochs and wild boar but there are various seasonal assessments and as the site was occupied over several hundred years it is likely that seasonal practices varied over time.{{sfn|Scarre|2005|p=397}}\n\nIt has been suggested that the antler frontlets were used as a hunting disguise, or in some form of [[ritual]] practice. Recent work suggests that these, along with other objects made from red deer antler, appear to have been respectfully deposited at the lake edge due to the spiritual significance of red deer to the people who occupied the site.\n\nAnthony Legge and Peter Rowley-Conway re-examined the animal bones located at the site. They found strong evidence to suggest that the site was used only in late spring and summer; evidence that the cull of red and roe deer was biased towards three- and one-year-old animals respectively; revision of available meat; reduction in scale of occupation; no bias towards hunting of male red deer, and tentatively suggested that the site was used as a hunting camp.<ref>Star Carr Revisited</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite journal|last1=Boreham|first1=S|last2=Conneller|first2=C|last3=Milner|first3=N|last4=Needham|first4=A|last5=Boreham|first5=J|last6=Rolfe|first6=CJ|title=Geochemical indicators of preservation status and site deterioration at Star Carr|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science|date=2011|volume=30|issue=10|pages=2833\u20132857|doi=10.1016/j.jas.2011.01.016}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/excavationsatsta0000clar |url-access=registration |quote=moore. |title=Excavations at Star Carr: An Early Mesolithic Site at Seamer Near Scarborough, Yorkshire |first=Grahame |last=Clark |authorlink=Grahame Clark |publisher=[[CUP Archive]] |date=1954 |accessdate=15 August 2014 |pp=xvii\u2013xviii |isbn=9780521083942|ref=harv}}\n*Conneller, C., 2004. Becoming deer. Corporeal transformations at Star Carr. ''Archaeological dialogues'', ''11''(1), pp.37-56.\n*Conneller, C., Milner, N., Taylor, B. and Taylor, M., 2012. Substantial settlement in the European Early Mesolithic: new research at Star Carr. ''Antiquity'', ''86''(334), pp.1004-1020.\n*{{cite book | last = Legge | first = Anthony J. | authorlink = Anthony Legge | author2-link = Peter Rowley-Conwy |first2 = Peter | last2 = Rowley-Conwy | title = Star Carr Revisited; a Re-analysis of the Large Mammals|publisher=Birkbeck College|location=London|year = 1988|isbn=978-0-7187-0876-4}}\n*{{cite book|last= Mellars|first= Paul| authorlink = Paul Mellars |first2= Petra|last2= Dark|title=Star Carr in Context: New Archaeological and Palaeoecological Investigations at the Early Mesolithic Site of Star Carr, North Yorkshire |publisher=McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research|year= 1998|isbn = 978-0-9519420-4-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Milner\n | first = Nicky\n | editor = Conneller, Chantal\n | others = Warren, Graeme\n | title = Mesolithic Britain and Ireland: New Approaches\n | year = 2006\n | publisher = Tempus\n | location = Stroud\n | chapter = Subsistence\n | chapterurl =\n | isbn=978-0-7524-3734-7 \n | ref = harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal|last1=Milner|first1=N|last2=Bamforth|first2=M|last3=Beale|first3=G|last4=Carty|first4=J|last5=Chatzipanagis|first5=K|last6=Croft|first6=S|last7=Conneller|first7=C|last8=Elliot|first8=B|last9=Fitton|first9=L|last10=Knight|first10=B|last11=Kr\u00f6ger|first11=R|last12=Little|first12=A|\nlast13=Needham|first13=A|last14=Robson|first14=H|last15=Rowley|first15=C|last16=Taylor|first16=B|\ntitle=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain|journal=Internet Archaeology|date=2016|issue=40|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8|doi-access=free|url=http://intarch.ac.uk/journal/issue40/8/}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-first=Nicky |editor1-last=Milner |editor2-first=Chantal |editor2-last=Conneller |editor3-first=Barry |editor3-last=Taylor | title= Star Carr: Volume 1: A Persistent Place in a Changing World |publisher=[[White Rose University Press]] |location = York |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-912482-04-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Scarre |title=The Human Past: World Prehistory & the Development of Human Societies |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |location=London |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-500-28531-2 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/humanpastworldpr0000unse }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.starcarr.com ''New Excavations at Star Carr''], University of York\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081004191852/http://www.arch.cam.ac.uk/projects/starrcarr.html ''Star Carr''], Department of Archaeology, University of Cambridge\n<!--*[http://www.dot-domesday.me.uk/migrate.htm ''In The Beginning''], From Dot to Domesday  credentials of this not clear unlike others listed here -->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151018175654/http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/pe_prb/r/red_deer_antler_head-dress.aspx ''Red deer antler head-dress from Star Carr''], British Museum\n*[http://www.manchester.ac.uk/aboutus/news/display/?id=6009, ''Stone Age remains are Britain's earliest house''], University of Manchester\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/2205880 ''Star Carr \u2013 The Otherside of the Antler''], video about the excavations in 2006, Vale of Pickering Archaeological Trust\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Star Carr}}\n[[Category:10th millennium BC]]\n[[Category:Mesolithic Europe]]\n[[Category:Stone Age sites in England]]\n[[Category:History of North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in North Yorkshire]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Mesolithic archaeological site in North Yorkshire, England}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2018}}\n{{Infobox ancient site\n| name = Star Carr\n| native_name = \n| alternate_name = \n| image = View of Star Carr site looking NWW..jpg\n| alt = \n| caption = View of the Star Carr site looking {{nowrap|north-west-west}}\n| map_type = North Yorkshire\n| map_alt = \n| map_size = \n| relief = \n| coordinates = {{coord|54|12|51|N|00|25|24|W|display=inline,title}}\n| location = [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]], [[North Yorkshire]], [[England]]\n| region = \n| type = Settlement\n| part_of = \n| length = \n| width = \n| area = \n| height = \n| builder = \n| material = \n| built = Approximately 9300&nbsp;BC\n| abandoned = Approximately 8480&nbsp;BC\n| epochs = [[Mesolithic]]\n| cultures = \n| dependency_of = \n| occupants = \n| event = \n| excavations = \n| archaeologists = \n| condition = \n| ownership = \n| management = \n| public_access = \n| website = <!-- {{URL|example.com}} -->\n| notes = \n}}\n{{Mesolithic|233}}\n\n'''Star Carr''' is a [[Mesolithic]] archaeological site in [[North Yorkshire]], England. It is around five miles ({{convert|5|mi|abbr=out|disp=output only|0}}) south of [[Scarborough, North Yorkshire|Scarborough]].<ref name=Pastscape>{{cite PastScape|mnumber=80206 |mname= Star Carr|accessdate=15 January 2008}}</ref>\nIt is generally regarded as the most important and informative Mesolithic site in [[Great Britain]]. It is as important to the Mesolithic period as [[Stonehenge]] is to the [[Neolithic]] period or [[Scandinavian York]] is to understanding [[Viking Age]] Britain.\n\nThe site was occupied during the early Mesolithic archaeological period, which coincided with the [[preboreal]] and [[boreal (period)|boreal]] climatic periods. Though the [[Last Glacial Period|ice age]] had ended and temperatures were close to modern averages, sea levels had not yet risen sufficiently to separate Britain from continental [[Europe]]. Highlights among the finds include Britain\u2019s oldest structure, 21 [[red deer]] stag skull-caps that may have been headdresses and nearly 200 projectile, or harpoon, points made of red deer [[antler]]. These organic materials were preserved due to having been buried in waterlogged [[peat]]. Normally all that remains on Mesolithic sites are [[stone tool]]s.\n\nExcavation of the site began in 1948, a year after artefacts were first noticed by an amateur archaeologist. The site is most famous for some of the extremely rare [[Artifact (archaeology)|artefacts]] discovered during the original excavations but its importance has been reinforced by new understandings of the nature and extent of the Mesolithic archaeology in the area and reinterpretations of the original material.\n\n==General information==\n\n===Environmental context===\nStar Carr now lies under farmland at the eastern end of the [[Vale of Pickering]]. During the Mesolithic the site was near the outflow at the western end of a palaeolake, known as [[Lake Flixton]].{{Sfn|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=4,13}} At the end of the last ice age a combination of glacial and post-glacial [[geomorphology]] caused the area to drain to the west (away from the shortest-distance to the [[North Sea]] at [[Filey]]). The basin filled by Lake Flixton was probably created by glacial 'scarring'.\n\nThe site is preserved due to Lake Flixton having been in-filled with peat during the course of the Mesolithic. Waterlogged peat prevents organic finds from oxidising and has led to some of the best preservation conditions possible (such conditions have preserved the famous [[bog bodies]] found in other parts of northern Europe).\nAs a result of such good conditions archaeologists were able to recover bone, antler and wood in addition to the flints that are normally all that is left on sites from this period.\n\nDuring the period of Mesolithic occupation the area surrounding the lake would have been a mixed forest of [[birch]], [[aspen]] and [[willow]].{{Sfn|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=147\u2013161}} The lake edge and shallows would have been full of reeds, water lily and other aquatic plants and lake levels would have changed dynamically in response to rainfall or snow-melt.\n\nThese and many other plants would have formed the base of a complex [[food web]]. The [[mammal]]s that we have evidence for include [[herbivore]]s such as [[beaver]], red deer, [[roe deer]], [[moose|elk]] \n, [[aurochs]], [[wild boar]], [[hare]] and [[carnivore]]s such as [[wolf]], [[lynx]], [[bear]], [[fox]], [[pine marten]], [[badger]] and [[hedgehog]].{{Sfn|Milner|2006|p=72}}\n\n===Key artefacts===\nAlong with the flints that are characteristic of [[Mesolithic]] sites, there were a large number of objects made of red deer and elk antler, elk bone, aurochs bone and one piece of bird bone.{{sfn|Clark|1954|pp=115\u2013164}} Rarer objects included worked [[amber]], [[shale]], [[haematite]], [[iron pyrites]], a decorated [[pendant]], thought to be the oldest known Mesolithic art in Britain <ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8 | issue=40 | title=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain | year=2016 | journal=Internet Archaeology | last1 = Milner | first1 = Nicky| doi-access=free }}</ref> and tightly-rolled pieces of birch-bark and pieces of birch-resin pitch or tar and worked wood.\nThe flint found at Star Carr came from nearby beaches, which at time of occupation would have been about {{convert|10|to|20|km|0|abbr=on}} distant, and also from the [[Yorkshire Wolds]] immediately to the south of the site.\n\nThe two most outstanding categories of finds are the 'barbed points' and 'antler frontlets'. The barbed points are made of the antler of red deer stags. They are between {{convert|8|cm|in}} and {{convert|38|cm|in}} in length{{sfn|Clark|1954|p=123}} and the 195 examples found at Star Carr account for more than 95% of the total number from the British Mesolithic. Many of the barbed points and antler frontlets appear to be deliberately broken. The antler frontlets are made from red deer stag (male) skulls with the antlers still attached. The 21 antler frontlets are sufficiently complete to see how they have been manufactured: two holes were perforated through the skull with a [[flint]] tool and the inside of the skull cap was smoothed. The antlers on each frontlet has been carefully trimmed maybe to reduce weight. It seems very likely that these modifications are designed to allow the frontlets to be used as headgear. Finds from the site are now divided between four institutions: The [[British Museum]], the [[Yorkshire Museum]] in York, the University [[Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology, University of Cambridge|Museum of Archaeology and Anthropology]] at Cambridge and the [[Rotunda Museum|Scarborough Museum]].<ref>[https://www.britishmuseum.org/research/collection_online/search.aspx?place=5702&plaA=5702-3-1 British Museum Collection]</ref><ref name=\"sc2017\">{{cite web|title=Exhibitions|url=http://www.starcarr.com/exhibitions.html|website=Star Carr Archaeology Project|accessdate=20 December 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Star Carr headdress cropped.JPG|thumb|left|300px|Red Deer Stag skull with holes]]\n[[File:Star Carr spear tips 01.jpg|thumb|left|300px|Barbed points]]\n\n===Evidence of structures===\nPost holes, a sunken area and concentrations of flints, burning and other artefacts indicate the presence of a structure approximately {{convert|3.5|m|ft}} wide. The posts were almost certainly made of wood and roughly {{convert|20|cm|in}} in diameter there may have been as many as 18 of them and the holes indicated that several may have been replaced over the course of the structure's use.\nIt is impossible to know the form or materials from which the walls and/or roof would have been made. They may have used [[Hide (skin)|hides]], [[thatch]], [[Peat|turf]] or [[Bark (botany)|bark]] on a conical ([[teepee]]-like) or rounded ([[wigwam]]-like) frame. There is no reason to suppose that the same materials and form would have been used for the structure's entire life-span. There was evidence that the floor was covered with a layer of moss, reeds and other soft plant materials {{convert|20|cm|in}}\u2013{{convert|30|cm|in}} deep.\n[[Radiocarbon]] dates indicated a use-life of between 200 and 500&nbsp;years.\nThe structure has been compared to the Mesolithic structure found at [[Howick, Northumberland|Howick]], Northumberland and British [[Iron Age]] [[Roundhouse (dwelling)|roundhouses]].\n\nA large wooden platform has been discovered nearby on the shore of the former lake \u2013 the earliest known example of carpentry in Europe, though its purpose is as yet unknown. Timbers of Aspen and Willow were split along the grain using wedges (probably made of wood and antler); these were then laid in the boggy areas at the lake shore, presumably to provide firm footing.\nThe extent of the wooden platform is not known but it may be a significantly larger and more complex undertaking than the house-like structure.\n\n===Chronology===\nCurrent [[radiocarbon]] dates from the site indicate occupation first commenced between 9335\u20139275&nbsp;BC, lasting for a period of around 800 years until 8525\u20138440&nbsp;BC.{{sfn|Milner, Conneller and Taylor|2018|pp=225\u2013244}} However, such occupations may have been episodic in nature, varying in intensity between different periods.{{sfn|Milner, Conneller and Taylor|2018|pp=225\u2013244}}\n\n==History of investigations==\n\n===Discovery and initial excavations===\nStar Carr was discovered in 1947 when John Moore, an amateur archaeologist, noticed flints in the exposed soil of several recently dredged ditches in the eastern Vale of Pickering. One of these sites, bordering on the [[River Derwent, Yorkshire#Course and character of the Derwent catchment area|New Hertford River]] was to the south of Star Carr Farm. Moore decided to excavate a small trench at Star Carr in 1948 as part of a series of investigations. On the discovery of intact organic remains Moore contacted Professor [[Grahame Clark]] of the [[University of Cambridge]] via [[Harry Godwin]] and the curator of the [[Rotunda Museum|Scarborough Museum]], [[Arthur Roy Clapham]].{{Sfn|Clark|1954|pp=xvii\u2013xviii}}<ref>{{cite news|last=Alleyne |first=Richard |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/7937240/Oldest-house-in-Britain-discovered-to-be-11500-years-old.html |title=Oldest house in Britain discovered to be 11,500 years old |newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=10 August 2010 |accessdate=15 August 2014}}</ref>\n\nClark began his investigation with the explicit aim of building a more detailed picture of the Mesolithic environment and the ways in which people used it.<ref>Clark 1972, p. 7{{Full citation needed|date=October 2012}}</ref> The organic preservation enabled the recovery of the plant and animal remains necessary for this. Clark excavated from 1949 to 1951. Clark's 1954 publication of these excavations is a seminal text in the study of the British Mesolithic and prehistory generally.{{citation needed|date=August 2014}}\n\nClark believed he had uncovered the entirety of the site and believed Star Carr could be used as a [[type-site]] for the British Mesolithic. He drew parallels between the finds at Star Carr and the site of [[Maglemosian|Maglemose]] in Denmark. It is now recognised that many of Clark\u2019s inferences were incorrect but the excavation remains one of the most important in the study of British prehistory ever undertaken.\n\n===Further investigations: The Lake Flixton Landscape===\nIn 1977 archaeologists excavated [[Iron Age]], [[Bronze Age]] and Mesolithic material from [[Seamer, Scarborough|Seamer]] Carr, just to the north of Star Carr. These excavations were conducted in advance of the Seamer Carr landfill site. The discovery of Mesolithic material led to a new series of investigations around Lake Flixton directed by [[Tim Schadla-Hall]] (currently [[University College London]]). This team returned to Star Carr in 1985 and 1989.<ref>{{harvnb|Mellars|Dark|1998|pp=}}{{page needed|date=August 2014}}</ref>\n\nThis project investigated the archaeology and ecology of the wider landscape around Lake Flixton and found several more Mesolithic sites but none with as many of the unusual artefacts (such as barbed points and antler frontlets) discovered at Star Carr.\n\n===The latest investigations===\nIn the 2000s new excavations began at Star Carr. This reinvestigation is being directed by [[Nicky Milner]] ([[Department of Archaeology at the University of York|University of York]]), Chantal Conneller ([[University of Manchester]]) and Barry Taylor ([[University of Chester]]). This ongoing project has reinvestigated Clark's excavations and also excavated the dry-land, discovering the structure.\n\n[[File:Star Carr Engraved Pendant.gif|thumb|right|Animated image showing the sequence of engravings on a pendant excavated from the Mesolithic archaeological site of Starr Carr in 2015 <ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Morgan | first1 = C. | last2 = Scholma-Mason | first2 = N. | year = 2017 | title = Animated GIFs as Expressive Visual Narratives and Expository Devices in Archaeology | url = | journal = Internet Archaeology | volume = | issue = 44| page = | doi = 10.11141/ia.44.11 | doi-access = free }}</ref>]]\n\nMost significantly, recent [[geochemical]] investigations have demonstrated that the preservation conditions have deteriorated. The result of this is that any remaining organic artefacts will be far less informative than those discovered by previous excavation projects. Though the reasons for this remain somewhat unclear, it appears that the acidity of the groundwater has massively increased in the last few years.\n\nA decorated pendant (the [[Star Carr Pendant]]), thought to be the oldest known Mesolithic art in Britain, was found at the site in 2015.<ref>{{cite journal|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8 | issue=40 | title=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain | year=2016 | journal=Internet Archaeology | last1 = Milner | first1 = Nicky| doi-access=free }}</ref>  The 11,000 year old object has been on display at the [[Yorkshire Museum]] with other finds from the site since 2016.<ref>{{cite news | title = Yorkshire Stone Age pendant goes on display | publisher = [[BBC News Online]] | date = 26 February 2016 | url = https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-york-north-yorkshire-35669267 | accessdate = 26 February 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Interpretive debates==\nClark, the original excavator, believed the Mesolithic people would have lived on a brushwood platform on the edge of the former Lake Flixton.{{sfn|Clark|1954|p=xvii}} Recent excavations have revealed that people lived on the dry land upslope of the lake and various activities were carried out at the lake edge.\n\nThere is much debate about the time of year the site was occupied. Mesolithic people hunted a number of animals including red and roe deer, elk, aurochs and wild boar but there are various seasonal assessments and as the site was occupied over several hundred years it is likely that seasonal practices varied over time.{{sfn|Scarre|2005|p=397}}\n\nIt has been suggested that the antler frontlets were used as a hunting disguise, or in some form of [[ritual]] practice. Recent work suggests that these, along with other objects made from red deer antler, appear to have been respectfully deposited at the lake edge due to the spiritual significance of red deer to the people who occupied the site.\n\nAnthony Legge and Peter Rowley-Conway re-examined the animal bones located at the site. They found strong evidence to suggest that the site was used only in late spring and summer; evidence that the cull of red and roe deer was biased towards three- and one-year-old animals respectively; revision of available meat; reduction in scale of occupation; no bias towards hunting of male red deer, and tentatively suggested that the site was used as a hunting camp.<ref>Star Carr Revisited</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite journal|last1=Boreham|first1=S|last2=Conneller|first2=C|last3=Milner|first3=N|last4=Needham|first4=A|last5=Boreham|first5=J|last6=Rolfe|first6=CJ|title=Geochemical indicators of preservation status and site deterioration at Star Carr|journal=Journal of Archaeological Science|date=2011|volume=30|issue=10|pages=2833\u20132857|doi=10.1016/j.jas.2011.01.016}}\n*{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/excavationsatsta0000clar |url-access=registration |quote=moore. |title=Excavations at Star Carr: An Early Mesolithic Site at Seamer Near Scarborough, Yorkshire |first=Grahame |last=Clark |authorlink=Grahame Clark |publisher=[[CUP Archive]] |date=1954 |accessdate=15 August 2014 |pp=xvii\u2013xviii |isbn=9780521083942|ref=harv}}\n*Conneller, C., 2004. Becoming deer. Corporeal transformations at Star Carr. ''Archaeological dialogues'', ''11''(1), pp.37-56.\n*Conneller, C., Milner, N., Taylor, B. and Taylor, M., 2012. Substantial settlement in the European Early Mesolithic: new research at Star Carr. ''Antiquity'', ''86''(334), pp.1004-1020.\n*{{cite book | last = Legge | first = Anthony J. | authorlink = Anthony Legge | author2-link = Peter Rowley-Conwy |first2 = Peter | last2 = Rowley-Conwy | title = Star Carr Revisited; a Re-analysis of the Large Mammals|publisher=Birkbeck College|location=London|year = 1988|isbn=978-0-7187-0876-4}}\n*{{cite book|last= Mellars|first= Paul| authorlink = Paul Mellars |first2= Petra|last2= Dark|title=Star Carr in Context: New Archaeological and Palaeoecological Investigations at the Early Mesolithic Site of Star Carr, North Yorkshire |publisher=McDonald Institute for Archaeological Research|year= 1998|isbn = 978-0-9519420-4-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book\n | last = Milner\n | first = Nicky\n | editor = Conneller, Chantal\n | others = Warren, Graeme\n | title = Mesolithic Britain and Ireland: New Approaches\n | year = 2006\n | publisher = Tempus\n | location = Stroud\n | chapter = Subsistence\n | chapterurl =\n | isbn=978-0-7524-3734-7 \n | ref = harv}}\n\n*{{cite journal|last1=Milner|first1=N|last2=Bamforth|first2=M|last3=Beale|first3=G|last4=Carty|first4=J|last5=Chatzipanagis|first5=K|last6=Croft|first6=S|last7=Conneller|first7=C|last8=Elliot|first8=B|last9=Fitton|first9=L|last10=Knight|first10=B|last11=Kr\u00f6ger|first11=R|last12=Little|first12=A|\nlast13=Needham|first13=A|last14=Robson|first14=H|last15=Rowley|first15=C|last16=Taylor|first16=B|\ntitle=A Unique Engraved Shale Pendant from the Site of Star Carr: the oldest Mesolithic art in Britain|journal=Internet Archaeology|date=2016|issue=40|doi=10.11141/ia.40.8|doi-access=free|url=http://intarch.ac.uk/journal/issue40/8/}}\n*{{cite book |editor1-first=Nicky |editor1-last=Milner |editor2-first=Chantal |editor2-last=Conneller |editor3-first=Barry |editor3-last=Taylor | title= Star Carr: Volume 1: A Persistent Place in a Changing World |publisher=[[White Rose University Press]] |location = York |year=2018 |isbn=978-1-912482-04-7 |ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book |editor-first=Chris |editor-last=Scarre |title=The Human Past: World Prehistory & the Development of Human Societies |publisher=[[Thames & Hudson]] |location=London |year=2005 |isbn=978-0-500-28531-2 |ref=harv |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/humanpastworldpr0000unse }}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.starcarr.com ''New Excavations at Star Carr''], University of York\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20081004191852/http://www.arch.cam.ac.uk/projects/starrcarr.html ''Star Carr''], Department of Archaeology, University of Cambridge\n<!--*[http://www.dot-domesday.me.uk/migrate.htm ''In The Beginning''], From Dot to Domesday  credentials of this not clear unlike others listed here -->\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20151018175654/http://www.britishmuseum.org/explore/highlights/highlight_objects/pe_prb/r/red_deer_antler_head-dress.aspx ''Red deer antler head-dress from Star Carr''], British Museum\n*[http://www.manchester.ac.uk/aboutus/news/display/?id=6009, ''Stone Age remains are Britain's earliest house''], University of Manchester\n*[http://www.vimeo.com/2205880 ''Star Carr \u2013 The Otherside of the Antler''], video about the excavations in 2006, Vale of Pickering Archaeological Trust\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Star Carr}}\n[[Category:10th millennium BC]]\n[[Category:Mesolithic Europe]]\n[[Category:Stone Age sites in England]]\n[[Category:History of North Yorkshire]]\n[[Category:Archaeological sites in North Yorkshire]]\n", "name_user": "2604:2000:1740:e47d:d089:8da7:2e99:2a13", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEnvironmental context)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Star_Carr"}
